 team|Spain]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2018||1||0\n|-\n|2019||3||0\n|-\n!Total||4||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Valencia'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2018\u201319 Copa del Rey|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48367455|title=Barcelona 1\u20132 Valencia|website=BBC Sport|last=Chowdhury|first=Saj|date=25 May 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Spain U19'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]: [[2007 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2007]]<ref name=UEFA/>\n\n'''Spain U20'''\n*[[Mediterranean Games]]: [[Football at the 2009 Mediterranean Games|2009]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pescara2009.it/results/pdf/FB/FB_C73_FB040060100001ENG.pdf|title=ITA \u2013 ESP 1:2 (0:0)|publisher=Pescara 2009|date=4 July 2009|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215081712/http://www.pescara2009.it/results/pdf/FB/FB_C73_FB040060100001ENG.pdf|archivedate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2011]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deportevalenciano.com/2017/06/16/valencianistas-campeones-europa-sub-21|title=Los valencianistas que fueron campeones de europa sub 21|trans-title=The Valencia players who were under-21 European champions|website=Deportevalenciano|first=Jos\u00e9|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|language=Spanish|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[UEFA]] La Liga Team of The Season: [[2017\u201318 La Liga|2017\u201318]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2560163.html|title=Equipo de la Liga 2017/18|trans-title=2017/18 League All-star team|publisher=UEFA|language=Spanish|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref> [[2018\u201319 La Liga|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://es.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2606161.html|title=Equipo de la Liga 2018/19|trans-title=2018/19 League All-star team|publisher=UEFA|first=Gonzalo|last=Aguado|language=Spanish|date=20 May 2019|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.valenciacf.com/en/sports/en-first-team-01/player/daniel-parejo Valencia official profile]\n*{{BDFutbol}}\n*[http://www.ciberche.net/histoche/jugador?player=976 CiberChe biography and stats] {{in lang|es}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{NFT player}}\n*{{FIFA player}}\n\n{{Valencia CF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parejo, Dani}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Coslada]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Madrilenian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2009 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Parejo|Mu\u00f1oz}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Dani Parejo\n| image = Real Valladolid-Valencia CF, 2019-05-18 (19) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Parejo with [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in 2019\n| fullname = Daniel Parejo Mu\u00f1oz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=59877|title=Acta del partido celebrado el 04 de enero de 2020, en Valencia|trans-title=Minutes of the match held on 4 January 2020, in Valencia|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=Spanish|date=4 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|4|16|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|24877|Daniel Parejo|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Coslada]], Spain<ref name=Street>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2008/02/08/deportes/1202425208_850215.html|title=Parejo, el futbolista de barrio|trans-title=Parejo, the neighbourhood footballer|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|first=Eleonora|last=Giovio|language=Spanish|date=8 February 2008|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| height = 1.82 m<ref>{{cite web|url=https://espanol.eurosport.com/futbol/daniel-parejo_prs117886/person.shtml|title=Daniel Parejo|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|Central midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| clubnumber = 10\n| youthyears1 = 1998\u20132000 | youthclubs1 = [[CD Coslada|Coslada]]\n| youthyears2 = 2000\u20132003 | youthclubs2 = Espinilla\n| youthyears3 = 2003\u20132006 | youthclubs3 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| years1 = 2006\u20132008 | clubs1 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]] | caps1 = 37 | goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs2 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps2 = 5 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2008 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] (loan) | caps3 = 14 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs4 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps4 = 64 | goals4 = 9\n| years5 = 2011\u2013 | clubs5 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] | caps5 = 272 | goals5 = 54\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps1 = 13 | nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2009 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps2 = 11 | nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 2008\u20132011 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps3 = 19 | nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u2013 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps4 = 4 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 6 March 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 8 September 2019\n}}\n'''Daniel \"Dani\" Parejo Mu\u00f1oz''' ({{IPA-es|da\u02c8njel \u02c8dani pa\u02c8\u027eexo}}; born 16 April 1989) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for [[Valencia CF]], where he is captain, and the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]].\n\nAfter starting out at [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], he first made a name in [[La Liga]] with [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]. Transferred to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in 2011, he went on to appear in 370 official matches for the latter club and win the [[2019 Copa del Rey Final|2019 Copa del Rey]]; he also spent four months in England, with [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].\n\nAcross all [[Spain national youth football team|youth levels]], Parejo won 43 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and scored nine goals. He made his full debut in 2018, at the age of 28.\n\n==Club career==\n===Real Madrid===\nBorn in [[Coslada]], [[Community of Madrid]],<ref name=Street/> Parejo was a product of [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]'s youth academy, joining at the age of 14. He was called on several occasions by first-team coach [[Bernd Schuster]] to train with the seniors and, during the [[2006\u201307 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2006\u201307 season]], played four games for [[Real Madrid Castilla]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2013/11/26/real-madrid/305872.html|title=La \u00faltima plantilla que descendi\u00f3 con el Castilla. \u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de ellos?|trans-title=The last squad to be relegated with Castilla. What happened to them?|publisher=[[Vavel]]|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last=Balderas|language=Spanish|date=26 November 2013|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 August 2008, Parejo signed a one-year [[Loan (sports)|loan]] deal with [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/queens-park-rangers/2504640/Flavio-Briatore-insists-QPR-signing-Daniel-Parejo-from-Real-Madrid-is-first-of-many.html|title=Flavio Briatore insists QPR signing Daniel Parejo from Real Madrid is first of many|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|first=Steve|last=Wilson|date=5 August 2008|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Soccer/EnglishPremiership/QPR-sign-Reals-Parejo-on-loan-20080909|title=QPR sign Real's Parejo on loan|website=Sport24|publisher=24.com|date=9 September 2008|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> and made his debut five days later, [[Substitute (association football)|coming off the bench]] in a 2\u20131 win over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] at [[Loftus Road]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/7540955.stm|title=QPR 2\u20131 Barnsley|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=9 August 2008|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> going on to total 18 official appearances. On 17 December, Real Madrid officially recalled the player from his loan effective 1 January 2009, after first-team midfielders [[Rub\u00e9n de la Red]] and [[Mahamadou Diarra]] were both out for [[2008\u201309 La Liga|the campaign]] with various physical problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=603189|title=Real Madrid recall Parejo from QPR loan deal|website=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=17 December 2008|accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nParejo was given the squad number 17, which had previously been assigned to [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]], who was also out for several months due to a serious injury. He appeared little during the season, his first match being the 4\u20130 [[La Liga]] away success against [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n]] on 15 February as he replaced [[Sergio Ramos]] for the final ten minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/uk/en/report/252940/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739|title=Sporting Gijon 0\u20134 Real Madrid|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=15 February 2009|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Getafe===\nIn late July 2009, as [[Esteban Granero]] was re-bought from [[Getafe CF]], Parejo went in the opposite direction with Real, as in Granero's case, having a similar option.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1084270.html|title=Getafe sign Parejo|publisher=FIFA|date=25 July 2009|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> On 25 March 2010, he scored against his former club after stealing the ball from [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Iker Casillas]], but the hosts lost it 2\u20134;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/275938?cc=5739|title=Ruthless Real return to the summit|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> having to compete for a starting berth in central midfield with coach [[M\u00edchel (footballer)|M\u00edchel]]'s son, [[Adri\u00e1n Gonz\u00e1lez (footballer, born 1988)|Adri\u00e1n]] \u2013 a former teammate in Real Madrid B \u2013 he nevertheless contributed solidly during [[2009\u201310 La Liga|the campaign]] as Getafe qualified for the second time in its history for the [[UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20100819/parejo-allana-camino-del-getafe-hacia-fase-grupos/348056.shtml|title=Parejo allana el camino del Getafe hacia la fase de grupos en la Liga Europa|trans-title=Parejo clears Getafe path towards Europa League group stage|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=Spanish|date=19 August 2010|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nParejo appeared more in [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311]] (36 matches), but the [[Madrid]] outskirts club only narrowly avoided relegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/abci-cronica-getafe-sevilla-201104160000_noticia.html|title=Miku quita el miedo al Getafe|trans-title=Miku takes fear from Getafe|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=16 April 2011|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20110530/getafe-decide-no-renovar-michel/435633.shtml|title=El Getafe decide no renovar a M\u00edchel|trans-title=Getafe decide against renewing M\u00edchel|publisher=RTVE|language=Spanish|date=30 May 2011|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://offsidecom.com/parejo-diez-anos-en-la-elite-del-futbol/|title=Parejo, diez a\u00f1os en la \u00e9lite del f\u00fatbol|trans-title=Parejo, ten years in football's elite|website=Offside|language=Spanish|date=9 August 2018|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Valencia===\n[[File:Dani Parejo.jpg|thumb|upright|Parejo playing for [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in 2015]]\n\nOn 14 June 2011, [[Valencia CF]] signed Parejo for a reported \u20ac6&nbsp;million, with out-of-favour goalkeeper [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Moy\u00e1]] going to Getafe on a year-long loan as part of the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valenciacf.com/contenidos/Actualidad/Noticias/2011/06/Noticia_30682.html?__locale=es|title=Comunicado oficial|trans-title=Official announcement|publisher=Valencia CF|language=Spanish|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=15 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617045204/http://www.valenciacf.com/contenidos/Actualidad/Noticias/2011/06/Noticia_30682.html?__locale=es|archivedate=17 June 2011|df=dmy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getafecf.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3136&Itemid=22|title=Acuerdo por Parejo|trans-title=Agreement for Parejo|publisher=Getafe CF|language=Spanish|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref> He made his league debut on 15 August, playing 80 minutes in a 1\u20131 away draw to [[RCD Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/323965?cc=5739|title=Last-gasp Mallorca deny Valencia|website=ESPN Soccernet|date=15 October 2011|accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nParejo was quickly deemed surplus to requirements at his new club, his situation not improving even after the serious injury suffered by [[Sergio Canales]], who played in his same position.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/10/04/futbol/equipos/valencia/1317716453.html|title=Unai Emery margina a Parejo y Ricardo Costa|trans-title=Unai Emery ousts Parejo and Ricardo Costa|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|location=Madrid|first=Diego|last=Pic\u00f3|language=Spanish|date=4 October 2011|accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> He bounced back, however, for [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]], scoring twice in 36 official games in an eventual fifth-place finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deportevalenciano.com/2012/12/14/nueva-oportunidad-para-dani-parejo|title=Nueva oportunidad para Dani Parejo|trans-title=New chance for Dani Parejo|website=Deportevalenciano|first=Nacho|last=Ballester|language=Spanish|date=14 December 2012|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.superdeporte.es/valencia/2013/02/20/triangulo-dani-parejo/188788.html|title=El tri\u00e1ngulo de Dani Parejo|trans-title=Dani Parejo's triangle|newspaper=[[Super Deporte]]|first=J.|last=Montoro|language=Spanish|date=21 February 2013|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.levante-emv.com/valencia-cf/2016/12/21/salida-parejo-precipita/1506781.html|title=La salida de Parejo se precipita|trans-title=Parejo's departure a growing certainty|newspaper=[[Levante-EMV]]|first=J.M.|last=Bort|language=Spanish|date=21 December 2016|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the following years, Parejo was an undisputed starter for several managers. In [[2014\u201315 La Liga|2014\u201315]] he scored a career-best 12 goals, being one of the best scorers in the competition from the midfielder position.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/05/03/futbol/equipos/valencia/1430687974.html|title=Parejo iguala a James como centrocampista m\u00e1s goleador de la Liga|trans-title=Parejo joins James as top scoring midfielder in League|newspaper=Marca|location=Madrid|language=Spanish|date=3 May 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> In the process, he also became the first Valencia midfielder to score ten or more goals since [[Vicente Rodr\u00edguez|Vicente]] in the [[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/OptaJose/status/592773411388162049|title=10 \u2013 Dani Parejo is the 1st Valencia midfielder to score 10 goals in a single La Liga season since Vicente in 03/04 (12). Star.|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=27 April 2015|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nParejo and [[Paco Alc\u00e1cer]] each scored twice in a 5\u20131 win away to third-place [[RC Celta de Vigo]] on 7 November 2015; his first came just before [[half-time]], through a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] to put the visitors ahead 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/07/celta-vigo-valencia-la-liga-match-report|title=Valencia's Paco Alc\u00e1cer and Dani Parejo on the double to beat Celta Vigo|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=7 November 2015|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> However, in January, after a poor run of form, the former was stripped of his [[Captain (association football)|captaincy]] in favour of the latter by manager [[Gary Neville]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3277/la-liga/2016/01/21/19569172/neville-replaces-valencia-captain-parejo-after-poor-results|title=Neville replaces Valencia captain Parejo after poor results|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Tom|last=Maston|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nParejo was named in the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spanish under-19]] squad for the [[2007 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2007 UEFA European Championship]]. In the tournament held in Austria, he scored the final winner against [[Greece national under-19 football team|Greece]] (1\u20130).<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under19/news/newsid=565156.html|title='The greatest feeling I've experienced'|publisher=UEFA|first=Paul|last=Woloszyn|date=27 July 2007|accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nParejo was promoted to the [[Spain national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] the following year, appearing in several [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualification matches]] for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2009 European Championship]]. He won his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the [[Spain national football team|senior team]] on 27 March 2018, replacing [[Thiago Alc\u00e2ntara]] late into the 6\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] defeat of [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/region/rested-messi-watches-argentina-get-crushed---by-spain/article_83e9f39d-1490-5652-bd33-a254e0f46999.html|title=Rested Messi watches Argentina get crushed 6\u20131 by Spain|newspaper=[[The Eagle-Tribune]]|location=North Andover|first=Teresa|last=Medrano|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|10 March 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/daniel-parejo/51278/|title=Dani Parejo: Summary|website=Soccerway|publisher=Perform Group|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||App