{"title_page": "Timeline of Class I railroads (1910\u20131929)", "text_new": "{{Class I timeline series}}\nThe following is a brief history of the North American rail system, mainly through major changes to [[Class I railroad]]s, the largest class by operating revenue.\n\n{{TOCyears|startyear=1910|endyear=1929}}\n\n;{{anchor|1910}}1910\n*July 1: The first year of classification by operating revenue begins.\n*July 1: The property of the independent [[Chicago, Cincinnati and Louisville Railroad]], which entered receivership on February 14, 1908,<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT167 pp. 160-161]</ref> is conveyed to the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 24 Val. Rep. 451 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 477, The Chesapeake and Ohio Railway Company of Indiana<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]]--></ref> a subsidiary of the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]].<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA686 p. 686]</ref>\n*December 23: The property of the [[Oregon Railroad and Navigation Company]] is sold to the [[Oregon-Washington Railroad and Navigation Company]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 44 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 329, Oregon-Washington Railroad & Navigation Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Oregon-Washington Railroad and Navigation Company]]--></ref> remaining a subsidiary of the [[Oregon Short Line Railroad]] ([[Union Pacific Railroad]] system).<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT245 p. 238]</ref><ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA716 p. 716]</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1911}}1911\n*January 1: The [[Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]] begins operations after acquiring the properties of the [[Southern Indiana Railway]] and subsidiary [[Chicago Southern Railway]], which entered receivership on August 19<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT177 pp. 170-171]</ref> and August 25, 1908, respectively.<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT211 pp. 204-205]</ref><ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 97 I.C.C. 535 (1925): Valuation Docket No. 41, Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]]--></ref>\n*February: The [[New York Central Railroad]] sells half of its majority interest in the [[Rutland Railroad]] to the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3JUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA235 The Earning Power of Railroads], 1916, p. 235</ref>\n*April 20: The [[Blacklick and Yellow Creek Railroad]] changes its name to [[Cambria and Indiana Railroad]] (not yet Class I).<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 130 I.C.C. 412 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 498, Cambria and Indiana Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cambria and Indiana Railroad]]--></ref>\n*June 30: The first year of classification by operating revenue ends. There are 177 Class I railroads, including two Canadian companies ([[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Canadian Northern Railway]]) not included in any totals by the ICC, and a separate listing for \"[[Canadian Pacific Lines in Maine]]\" (leased lines of the [[International Railway of Maine]], [[Aroostook River Railroad]], and [[Houlton Branch Railroad]]). [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] lessor [[Atlantic and St. Lawrence Railroad]] is also listed as a Class I railroad.<ref>ICC (1911)</ref>\n*July: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] gains control of the [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]] (not yet Class I)<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqw13|name=Wichita Falls and Wellington Railway|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> and [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I).{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*July 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Cleveland, Akron and Columbus Railway]] and [[Cincinnati and Muskingum Valley Railroad]], the latter not Class I, merge to form the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=ICC-CA&C>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 23 Val. Rep. 365 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 386, [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/ca_c.html Pennsylvania Company and its Leased Lines]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Illinois Central Railroad]] begins operating the property of former subsidiary [[Indianapolis Southern Railroad]], purchased at foreclosure.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA309 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, p. 309</ref>\n*July 21: The [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] buys the property of subsidiary [[Evansville and Terre Haute Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 31 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 202, Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]]--></ref>\n*September 15: The [[Bingham and Garfield Railway]] completes its main line.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 106 I.C.C. 450 (1925): Valuation Docket No. 267, Bingham & Garfield Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Bingham and Garfield Railway]]--></ref> It will be listed as Class II in 1912<ref>ICC (1912)</ref> and Class I in 1913.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA695 p. 695]</ref>\n*September 16: The [[International and Great Northern Railway]] begins operating the former International and Great Northern Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 149 I.C.C. 587 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 355, International and Great Northern Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/International and Great Northern Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since February 27, 1908.<ref name=\"p. 710\">ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA710 p. 710]</ref>\n*November: The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] and [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]] jointly buy control of the [[New Orleans, Mobile and Chicago Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=lScOAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA395 The Earning Power of Railroads], 1914, p. 395</ref>\n*December 28: The property of [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway]] is conveyed to AT&SF lessor [[California, Arizona and Santa Fe Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 127 I.C.C. 1 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 625, Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/California, Arizona and Santa Fe Railway]]--></ref><!--not quite sure about the details - apparently the lease wasn't until March 1, 1912?-->\n\n;{{anchor|1912}}1912\n*January 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pennsylvania Company]] leases the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=ICC-CA&C/>\n*January 1: The [[Minneapolis and St. Louis Railroad]] acquires the property of the [[Iowa Central Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 137 I.C.C. 761 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 510, Minneapolis & St. Louis Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Minneapolis and St. Louis Railroad]]--></ref> formerly independent.<ref name=\"p. 710\"/>\n*March 20: The [[Sunset Railroad]], controlled jointly by the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] and [[Southern Pacific Company]], merges with lessor [[Sunset Western Railway]] to form the [[Sunset Railway]] (no longer Class I).<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 32</ref>\n*April 4: The [[Crystal City and Uvalde Railroad]] is renamed [[San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad]] (not yet Class I).<ref name=sausage/>\n*June 30: The [[Sunset Railroad]] is demoted from Class I to II; it will never return to the former classification. The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] also becomes Class II, since [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]] had been listed as a lessor in 1911, but is now listed as an operating subsidiary, and the revenues of the parent alone are not enough to qualify for Class I. On the other hand, the [[Detroit and Toledo Shore Line Railroad]], [[Oahu Railway and Land Company]], and [[Western Pacific Railroad]] are newly listed as Class I. The [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]] begins including data for subsidiary [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]] with its own data. With the loss of the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]], [[Evansville and Terre Haute Railroad]], [[Indianapolis Southern Railroad]], [[Iowa Central Railway]], and [[Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway]], and electrification of the [[Spokane and Inland Empire Railroad]], the number of Class I railroads drops from 177 in 1911 to 171 as of June 30, 1912.<ref>ICC (1911, 1912)</ref>\n*October 1: The [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Syracuse, Binghamton and New York Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 707\">ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA707 p. 707]</ref>\n*December 9: [[Canadian Northern Railway]] subsidiary [[Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]] completes its line<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 503 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 856, Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]]--></ref> and becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA696 p. 696]</ref>\n*December 24<!--or December 31?-->: The property of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and Puget Sound Railway]] is conveyed to parent [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 44 Val. Rep. 441 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1072, Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]]--></ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1913}}1913\n*January 1: The [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]] begins operating the former Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railway of Illinois,<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA961 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 965</ref> in receivership since July 1, 1909.<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA709 p. 709]</ref>\n*May 1: The [[Denver and Salt Lake Railroad]] begins operating the former [[Denver, Northwestern and Pacific Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 119 I.C.C. 483 (1926): Valuation Docket No. 770, Denver and Salt Lake Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Denver and Salt Lake Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since May 2, 1912.<ref>ICC (1912), p. 665</ref>\n*May 28: The [[Butte, Anaconda and Pacific Railway]] begins electric service.<ref>[[Engineering & Mining Journal]], Volume 97, No. 11, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JR4rAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA3-PA559 p. 559: Butte, Anaconda & Pacific Electrification], March 14, 1914</ref>\n*June 30: The [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]], [[Bingham and Garfield Railway]], [[Florence and Cripple Creek Railroad]], [[Lehigh and New England Railroad]], [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railroad]], [[Missouri, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], and [[Spokane International Railway]] are reclassified from II to I, and the new [[Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]] is also Class I. The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]] starts including its data with parent [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]], and, with the disappearance of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and Puget Sound Railway]] and [[Syracuse, Binghamton and New York Railroad]], the number of Class I railroads rises from 171 in 1912 to 176 as of June 30, 1913.<ref>ICC (1912, 1913)</ref>\n*December 31: The [[Buffalo and Susquehanna Railroad]] is reorganized under the same name,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 36 Val. Rep. 199 (1931): Valuation Docket No. 340, Buffalo & Susquehanna Railroad Corporation et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Buffalo and Susquehanna Railroad]]--></ref> having been in receivership since July 23, 1910. Former parent [[Buffalo and Susquehanna Railway]] (Class II), also in receivership (since May 3, 1910),<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA674 p. 674]</ref> remains independent, and is reorganized as the [[Wellsville and Buffalo Railroad]] (Class II) on December 14, 1915<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA677 677], [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA696 696]</ref> and abandoned in November 1916.<ref>Arthur Stone Dewing, [https://books.google.com/books?id=J_EpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA111 The Financial Policy of Corporations], Volume 1 (Corporate Securities), p. 111</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1914}}1914\n*January 1: The [[Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]] begins recording its lease of the [[Peoria and Eastern Railway]], which dates from April 1, 1890, as such.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 28 Val. Rep. 90 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 264, The Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Peoria and Eastern Railway]]--></ref> Previously the P&E was listed as Class I.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA679 p. 679]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad]] begins operating the former Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railway, which had been in receivership since February 1, 1908.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 115 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 857, Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad]]--></ref> As a consequence of this reorganization, the DT&I no longer controls the [[Ann Arbor Railroad (1895-1976)|Ann Arbor Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 707\"/><ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA675 p. 675]</ref>\n*March 30<!--or April 1?-->: The [[Boston and Maine Railroad]] sells its controlling share in the [[Maine Central Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA1019 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, pp. 1019-1020</ref>\n*April 7: The [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]] is completed.\n*May 1: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I) to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]].<ref>290 I.C.C. 303 (1954): Finance Docket No. 18163, Wichita Falls & Southern Railroad Company et al. Abandonment, etc.</ref>\n*June 1: [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]] subsidiary [[Toledo and Ohio Central Railway]] buys control of the [[Kanawha and Michigan Railway]] from joint owners [[Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway]] (also a NYC subsidiary) and [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA493 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, p. 493</ref>\n*June 5: [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Southern Kansas Railway of Texas]] is renamed [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]].<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqs22|name=Southern Kansas Railway|author=Chris Cravens|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*June 30: Despite the loss of the [[Peoria and Eastern Railway]], the number of Class I railroads remains at 176, its 1913 value, since [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] lessor [[Chicago, Detroit and Canada Grand Trunk Junction Railroad]], which reports separately, is raised from Class II to I.<ref>ICC (1913, 1914)</ref>\n*July 1: [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Pecos and Northern Texas Railway]] is leased in part to the [[Gulf, Colorado and Santa Fe Railway]] and [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]], being split at [[Sweetwater, TX|Sweetwater]].<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqp09|name=Pecos and Northern Texas Railway|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*July 6: The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad]] begins operating the former Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 217 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 1050, Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since March 7, 1912.<ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA730 p. 730]</ref> [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]] is in receivership from March 9, 1912 to July 8, 1914.<ref name=handbook-KCM&O>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqk05|name=Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*July 29: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Northern Central Railway]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*August 14: The [[Utah Railway]] opens, initially operated by the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Utah>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 545 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 538, Utah Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Utah Railway]]--></ref>\n*December 23: The [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]] merges with ten subsidiaries, including Class I [[Chicago, Indiana and Southern Railroad]] and [[Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway]], to form the [[New York Central Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 27 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 1022, The New York Central Railroad Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/New York Central Railroad]]--></ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1915}}1915\n*January 23: The [[Canadian Northern Railway]] is completed.<ref>J. Castell Hopkins, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fDurWYs3XuUC&pg=PA753 The Canadian Annual Review of Public Affairs], 1915, p. 753</ref>\n*May 1: The [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] (recently renamed from [[Golden Circle Railroad]]) acquires a portion of the property of former lessee [[Florence and Cripple Creek Railroad]],<ref name=ICC-Midland/> the rest of which is abandoned.\n*June 1<!--or May 1?-->: Due to the financial problems of the [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]], which was to operate the mostly-completed [[National Transcontinental Railway]], the Canadian government retains control of the NTR, grouping it with the existing [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[Intercolonial Railway]] and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]).<ref>J. Castell Hopkins, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fDurWYs3XuUC&pg=PA751 The Canadian Annual Review of Public Affairs], 1915, pp. 751-752</ref><!--what about the last spike on November 17, 1913??-->\n<!--need to get 1915 ICC-->\n*July 1: The [[Monongahela Railroad]] (Class I) and [[Buckhannon and Northern Railroad]] (not Class I), both owned jointly by the [[Pennsylvania Company]] and [[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad]], merge to form the [[Monongahela Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 22 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/mga.html Valuation Docket No. 880, The Monongahela Railway Company]</ref>\n*November 1: The [[Wabash Railway]] begins operating the former Wabash Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 40 Val. Rep. 723 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 897, Wabash Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Wabash Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since December 26, 1911.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA686 p. 686]</ref> It will soon lose its control of subsidiaries [[Wabash Pittsburgh Terminal Railway]] and [[Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad (1899-1916)|Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad]] when they reorganize.\n*December 1: Independent [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]] begins operating the property of the former [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railway]], which had been leased to [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 755 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 937, Cincinnati, Indianapolis & Western Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]]--></ref> and entered receivership in February 1915.<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA641 Manual of Statistics], 1919, p. 641</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1916}}1916\n*January 1: The [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railway]] begins operating the former Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railroad,<ref>The Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA573 The Manual of Statistics], 1919, p. 573</ref> which had been in receivership since January 1, 1909.<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA700 p. 700]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] begins operating the former New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railroad,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA698 p. 698]</ref> which had been in receivership since July 5, 1913.<ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA734 p. 734]</ref> It retains control of subsidiaries [[Beaumont, Sour Lake and Western Railway]] (not yet Class I), [[Orange and Northwestern Railroad]] (never Class I), and [[St. Louis, Brownsville and Mexico Railway]] (Class I since 1911), but is freed of its former control by the [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]], itself in receivership.<ref>The Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA756 The Manual of Statistics], 1919, pp. 756-757</ref> This system comes to be known as the [[Gulf Coast Lines]].\n<!--need to get 1915 ICC-->\n*July: The [[New York Central Railroad]] sells subsidiary [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]] to the [[Van Sweringen brothers]].<ref name=Vans/>\n*July 1: The [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Virginia and Southwestern Railway]].<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT475 p. 490]</ref> This company still exists as a [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] lessor.\n*July 14: The [[Western Pacific Railroad]], owned by [[holding company]] [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]], acquires the property of the former Western Pacific Railway,<ref>ICC (December 31, 1916)</ref> a subsidiary of the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]] in receivership since March 5, 1915.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA688 p. 688]</ref> (When the D&RG reorganizes in 1921, the WP will control its successor.)\n*August 16: [[Union Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[San Pedro, Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad]] is renamed Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1058 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1062</ref>\n*September 1: The [[Pittsburg, Shawmut and Northern Railroad]], in receivership since August 1, 1905,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA674 p. 674]</ref> terminates its lease of the [[Pittsburg and Shawmut Railroad]],<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7hsUAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA809 Manual of Statistics], 1918, p. 809</ref> which becomes an independent Class I railroad.\n*November: The [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] buys control of the [[New Orleans and Northeastern Railroad]] from the [[Alabama, New Orleans, Texas and Pacific Junction Railways Company]],<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ex0UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA215 Manual of Statistics], 1917, p. 215</ref> as well as the latter's minority holdings<!--$448,700--> in [[Cincinnati, New Orleans and Texas Pacific Railway]] parent [[Southwestern Construction Company]]. Through existing shares of that [[holding company]] held by the Southern<!--$833,300--> and subsidiary [[Alabama Great Southern Railroad]]<!--$16,600-->, the Southern now controls the CNO&TP.<!--total of $1,298,600 out of $2,049,300, $100 per share-->\n*November 1: The [[St. Louis-San Francisco Railway]] begins operating the former St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 41 Val. Rep. 139 (1932): Valuation Docket No. 400, St. Louis-San Francisco Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/St. Louis-San Francisco Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since May 27, 1913.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA692 p. 692]</ref> During its receivership, it has lost control of the [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] and [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railroad]].\n*December 31: The ICC changes its year for which carriers report to end on December 31 rather than June 30. In the preceding six months, the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] has stopped reporting, [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] subsidiaries [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]] and [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]] and [[Kansas City Southern Railway]] subsidiary [[Texarkana and Fort Smith Railway]] have begun to report separately, the [[Pittsburg and Shawmut Railroad]] has commenced independent operations, and the [[Virginia and Southwestern Railway]] has been leased. With the raising of the [[Colorado and Wyoming Railway]] from Class II to I, the number of Class I railroads as of the end of 1916 is 183, up from 181 as of June 30.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916, December 31, 1916)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1917}}1917\n*January 1: The independent [[Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad]] begins operating the property of the former [[New Orleans, Mobile and Chicago Railroad]],<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT488 p. 503]</ref> in receivership since December 19, 1913,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA682 p. 682]</ref><ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 125 I.C.C. 765 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 866, Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad]]--></ref> and previously jointly owned by the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] and [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]].<!--did they sell the stock or did the receivership simply take it out of their control?--><ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA721 p. 721]</ref>\n*January 1: The independent [[Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway (1916-1988)|Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Wabash Railway]] subsidiary Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad,<ref name=ICC-Midland>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 31 Val. Rep. 707 (1930): Valuation Docket No. 396, The Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since June 8, 1908.<ref name=ICC-WPTWLE/>\n*January 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]], [[Vandalia Railroad (1905-1917)|Vandalia Railroad]], and others merge to form the [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=PRR>Christopher T. Baer, [http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR_hagley_intro.htm PRR Chronology] (Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society), accessed April 2009</ref>\n*February 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] acquires control of the [[Coal and Coke Railway]].<ref>Moody's (1986), p. 662</ref>\n*March 15: The [[Pere Marquette Railway]] acquires the property of the Pere Marquette Railroad.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1158 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1160</ref>\n*April 1: The independent [[Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Wabash Railway]] subsidiary [[Wabash Pittsburgh Terminal Railway]],<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1167 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1169</ref> in receivership since May 29, 1908.<ref name=ICC-WPTWLE>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ p. 677]</ref>\n*April<!--April 14?-->: The [[Sterling Trust]] succeeds the [[Alabama, New Orleans, Texas and Pacific Junction Railways Company]] as [[holding company]] for the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA348 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 348</ref>\n*May 31: The independent [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] begins operating the former Colorado Midland Railway,<ref name=ICC-Midland2>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 110 I.C.C. 451 (1926): Valuation Docket No. 673, Midland Terminal Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Midland Terminal Railway]], [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Colorado Midland Railroad]], and [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]]--></ref> a joint subsidiary of the [[Colorado and Southern Railway]] ([[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad]] system) and [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]] that entered receivership on December 13, 1912.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA691 p. 691]</ref>\n*June 1: The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] begins operating the former properties of the Missouri Pacific Railway and subsidiary [[St. Louis, Iron Mountain and Southern Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 40 Val. Rep. 249 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1006, Missouri Pacific Railroad Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Missouri Pacific Railroad]]--></ref> both in receivership since August 19, 1915.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA690 p. 690]</ref>\n*July 18: [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]], in receivership since July 2, 1914,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA664 p. 664]</ref> ceases operations after conveying much of its property to new B&O subsidiary and lessor [[Toledo and Cincinnati Railroad]]. Other pieces of the CH&D are either abandoned or sold to the newly incorporated independent [[Dayton, Toledo and Chicago Railway]];<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 42 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1068, The Baltimore and Ohio Rail Road Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Toledo and Cincinnati Railroad]]--></ref> former lessor [[Cincinnati, Findlay and Fort Wayne Railway]] is also freed of B&O control, and both independent companies soon abandon their lines.\n*August 1: The [[Savannah and Atlanta Railway]] (not yet Class I) acquires the property of the [[Savannah and Northwestern Railway]].<ref>187 I.C.C. 129 (1932): Savannah & Atlanta Railway Receiver Reconstruction Loan</ref>\n*September 30: The Canadian government acquires control of the [[Canadian Northern Railway]].<ref name=CNor>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA916 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 920</ref>\n*October 1: The [[San Diego and Arizona Railway]] (not yet Class I), half-owned by the [[Southern Pacific Company]], acquires the property of the [[San Diego and South Eastern Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 45 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1064, San Diego and Arizona Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/San Diego and Arizona Railway]]--></ref>\n*December 1: The [[Utah Railway]] begins operating its own line, heretofore leased to the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Utah/> It immediately becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1917)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1918}}1918\n*January 1: The [[United States Railroad Administration]] takes over operation of most of the U.S. rail network,<ref name=PRR/> including almost all Class I railroads.<ref name=\"ICC 1918, 1919\">ICC (1918, 1919)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases its subsidiaries that had been leased to the [[Pennsylvania Company]],<ref name=PRR/> as well as the [[Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 22 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 903, [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pb_w.html Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad Company]</ref>\n*January 17: The [[New York Connecting Railroad]], jointly owned by the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] and [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], begins hauling freight over the [[Hell Gate Bridge]].<ref name=PRR/> It will become Class I in 1920.<ref>ICC (1919, 1920)</ref>\n*August 5: The [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] ceases operations after entering receivership on July 1, 1918. A piece at the east end continues to be operated under [[trackage rights]] by the [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*August 6: The [[Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I) acquires the property of the former [[Minneapolis, St. Paul, Rochester and Dubuque Electric Traction Company]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 498 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 915, Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since February 20, 1916.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT482 p. 497]</ref>\n*October 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Coal and Coke Railway]].<ref>ICC (1918), [https://archive.org/details/annualreportons38statgoog/page/n681 <!-- pg=675 --> p. 762]</ref>\n*December 20: The title \"[[Canadian National Railways]]\" is adopted for the government-owned [[Canadian Northern Railway]] and [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[National Transcontinental Railway]], [[Intercolonial Railway]], and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]).<ref name=CNor/>\n\n;{{anchor|1919}}1919\n*January 1: Former lessor [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) leases the property owned by the [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] and its [[trackage rights]] operations over the remaining portion of the [[Colorado Midland Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*March 10: The [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] subsidiary [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]] enters receivership, under control of the Canadian government.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1015 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1019</ref>\n*June 2<!--or June 1?-->: The [[Cumberland Valley Railroad]] is merged into parent [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], but lessor [[Cumberland Valley and Martinsburg Railroad]] begins operating its own line,<ref name=PRR/> and is large enough to be Class I.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT53 p. 421]</ref>\n*July 31: The [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]] takes over the property of the former [[Missouri, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]],<ref name=Moodys-KO&G>Moody's (1970), p. 216</ref> in receivership since December 13, 1913.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA785 p. 785]</ref>\n*November 15: The [[San Diego and Arizona Railway]] (not yet Class I), half-owned by the [[Southern Pacific Company]], completes its line.\n*December 31: The [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]] is demoted to Class II.<ref name=\"ICC 1918, 1919\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1920}}1920\n*The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]], purchases 1.73% of the stock of the [[Atlanta and West Point Railroad]]. Combined with existing ownership - 1.95% by the ACL and 46.98% by joint subsidiary [[Georgia Railroad]] - this gives the ACL control of the West Point.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA773 p. 773]</ref><ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT49 p. 425]</ref>\n*February 29: The [[Washington Southern Railway]] merges into parent [[Richmond, Fredericksburg and Potomac Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 442\">ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT34 p. 442]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[United States Railroad Administration]] ceases operations, returning control to the railroad companies.<ref name=PRR/>\n*March 1: The [[Akron, Canton and Youngstown Railway]] (not yet Class I) leases the [[Northern Ohio Railway]], which had been leased to the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]], part of the [[New York Central Railroad]] system.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA766 p. 766]</ref><ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT62 p. 412]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] sells subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]], which was leased to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]], and it resumes independent operations (not yet Class I).<ref name=handbook-WF&SRy>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqw12|name=Wichita Falls and Southern Railway|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*June: The independent [[Evansville, Indianapolis and Terre Haute Railway]] begins operating the property of the former [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] subsidiary [[Evansville and Indianapolis Railroad]],<ref>ICC (1938)</ref> in receivership since February 5, 1916.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA761 p. 761]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases subsidiaries [[Cumberland Valley and Martinsburg Railroad]] and [[New York, Philadelphia and Norfolk Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*November 6: [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] subsidiary [[Southern Railway in Mississippi]] is renamed [[Columbus and Greenville Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 442\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1921}}1921\n*[[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]] gains control of the [[Evansville, Indianapolis and Terre Haute Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases a number of subsidiaries, including Class I [[Cincinnati, Lebanon and Northern Railway]], [[Grand Rapids and Indiana Railway]], and [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*March 26: The [[Missouri-Illinois Railroad]] (not yet Class I) begins operating the former [[Illinois Southern Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 45 Val. Rep. 867 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1185, Missouri-Illinois Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Missouri-Illinois Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since September 17, 1918.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA764 p. 764]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]] leases the [[Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA414 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 414</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railroad]] (not yet Class I) opens and leases the [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]].<ref name=handbook-WF&SRR>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqwue|name=Wichita Falls and Southern Railroad|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*August 1: The [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad]], a subsidiary of [[Western Pacific Railroad]] parent [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]], begins operating the former Denver and Rio Grande Railroad,<ref name=D&RG>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA374 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 374</ref> in receivership since January 26, 1918.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA782 p. 782]</ref> (The D&RG had controlled WP predecessor Western Pacific Railway until its 1916 reorganization.)\n*December 20: The [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) purchases the remaining property of lessor [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] (formerly Class I).<ref name=\"ICC 1921\">ICC (1921)</ref>\n*December 29: The [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) purchases the remaining property of lessor [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] (formerly Class I),<ref name=\"ICC 1921\"/> in receivership since July 1, 1918.<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*December 31: The [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]].<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1922}}1922\n*January: The [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]] begins distributing its [[Chicago and Alton Railroad]] stock, ending its control of that company.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA274 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 274</ref>\n*January 1<!--or 1921-12-31??-->: The [[El Paso and Southwestern Company]] buys the [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]] (no longer Class I) from the [[Phelps Dodge Corporation]] and leases it to lessor [[El Paso and Southwestern Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA378 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 378</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railway]] begins operating the former Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA276 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 276</ref> in receivership since May 27, 1913.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT61 p. 413]</ref> During its receivership, it has lost its relationships with parent [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]] and subsidiary [[Evansville and Indianapolis Railroad]] (not yet Class I).\n*January 1: The [[New York Central Railroad]] leases subsidiaries [[Toledo and Ohio Central Railway]] and [[Kanawha and Michigan Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA306 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 306</ref>\n*January 31: The [[Tennessee Central Railway]] acquires the property of the former Tennessee Central Railroad,<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/> in receivership since December 31, 1912.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT44 p. 430]</ref>\n*March: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] buy control of the [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]].<ref name=Vans/>\n*April 24: The [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railway]] begins operating the former [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railroad]],<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref> in receivership since April 1, 1912.<ref>ICC (1918), [https://archive.org/details/annualreportons38statgoog/page/n692 <!-- pg=686 --> p. 773]</ref>\n*April 26: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] buy the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]] from the [[New York Central Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*July 1: The [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]] leases the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]],<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/> both companies being controlled by the [[Van Sweringen brothers]].\n*December 1: The [[International-Great Northern Railroad]] begins operating the former International and Great Northern Railway,<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref> in receivership since August 11, 1914.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA784 p. 784]</ref>\n*December 31: The [[Akron, Canton and Youngstown Railway]] is raised from Class II to I.<ref>ICC (1921, 1922)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1923}}1923\n*<!--not sure what date - the property was sold at foreclosure January 16, but it usually takes a few weeks before operations are transferred-->The [[Fort Smith and Western Railway]] begins operating the former Fort Smith and Western Railroad,{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} in receivership since October 9, 1915.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA783 p. 783]</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] merge their [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]] and lessor [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]] into the [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=Vans>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 486</ref> The TStL&W had been in receivership since October 22, 1914.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT50 p. 424]</ref>\n*January 20: The new [[Canadian National Railway]] takes over operation of the [[Canadian National Railways]], consisting of the [[Canadian Northern Railway]] and [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[National Transcontinental Railway]], [[Intercolonial Railway]], and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]), as well as the [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--they're not merged yet - see 1956-->\n*January 30: The [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] is merged into the government-owned [[Canadian National Railway]], completing a process begun in 1920 to save the financially troubled Grand Trunk.<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 1201</ref>\n*April 1: The [[Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad]] begins operating most of the former [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] and subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]],<ref name=Moodys-MKT>Moody's (1986), p. 746</ref> in receivership since September 27, 1915 and May 29, 1917, respectively. [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]], placed under a receiver's control at the same time,<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT40 p. 436]</ref> is simultaneously reorganized as the [[Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad of Texas]].<ref name=handbook-MKT>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqm08|name=Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad|author=Donovan L. Hofsommer|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> Property not retained in the reorganization includes the [[Shreveport, LA|Shreveport]]-[[Dallas, TX|Dallas]] line, acquired by [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company]] subsidiary<!--?--> [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company of Texas]],<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eql08|name=Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company of Texas|author=Nancy Beck Young|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> and the [[Oklahoma City, OK|Oklahoma City]]-[[Atoka, OK|Atoka]] line, acquired by the [[Oklahoma City-Ada-Atoka Railway]] (not yet Class I).\n*August 6: The independent [[Columbus and Greenville Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] subsidiary Columbus and Greenville Railroad,<ref>Moody's (1972), p. 295</ref> in receivership since June 4, 1921.<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/>\n*August 17: The [[Lake Superior and Ishpeming Railway]] merges with the [[Munising, Marquette and Southeastern Railway]] (not Class I) to form the Lake Superior and Ishpeming Railroad.<ref>Moody's (1992), p. 435</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1924}}1924\n*January 1: The [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Grand Canyon Railway]] (no longer Class I).<ref name=\"ICC 1925\">ICC (1925)</ref>\n*January 1<!--or January 2?-->: The [[Philadelphia and Reading Railway]] merges into parent [[Reading Company]], which becomes an operating railroad.<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 218</ref>\n*February 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Baltimore and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I) begins operating the former [[Maryland, Delaware and Virginia Railway]] west of [[Denton, MD|Denton]].<ref name=Moodys-B&E/> Independent [[Maryland and Delaware Coast Railway]] (not Class I) will acquire the rest on May 14; it is reorganized in 1932 as the [[Maryland and Delaware Seacoast Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*May 14: The [[Texas and Pacific Railway]] exits a receivership{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} that began on October 27, 1916,<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT36 p. 440]</ref> and is acquired by the [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] by the end of the year.<ref name=\"ICC 1924\">ICC (1924)</ref>\n*June 20: The [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] ([[Gulf Coast Lines]]) buys control of the [[International-Great Northern Railroad]].<ref name=handbook-MP/>\n*October 29: The [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad]] exits a receivership that began on July 21, 1922,<ref name=D&RG/> and is now equally owned by the [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] and [[Western Pacific Railroad]] parent [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]].<ref name=Pacific>{{cite book|author=R. A. LeMassena|publisher=[[Sundance Publications]]|title=Rio Grande ... to the Pacific!|year=1974|isbn=0-913582-09-3}}, pp. 139, 149, 163</ref>\n*November: The [[Sterling Trust]] sells the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]] to New York and New Orleans bankers.<ref>Cleona Lewis and Karl T. Schlotterbeck, America's Stake in International Investments, [[Brookings Institution]], 1938, p. 104</ref>\n*November 1: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases the subsidiaries of the [[El Paso and Southwestern Company]], including the [[El Paso and Southwestern Railroad]] and [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]],<ref name=\"ICC 1924\"/> which the Class I EP&SW Company had operated.\n*November 8: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases subsidiary [[Arizona Eastern Railroad]].<ref name=Moodys-AZER>Moody's (1992), pp. 257-258</ref>\n*December 1: The [[Clinchfield Railroad]], an unincorporated entity organized jointly by the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]] and subsidiary [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], begins operating the [[Carolina, Clinchfield and Ohio Railway]] under lease.<ref name=Moodys-Clinchfield>Moody's (1983), p. 725</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1925}}1925\n*January 1: The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] gains control of the [[Gulf Coast Lines]], including parent [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] and several other Class I railroads: [[International-Great Northern Railroad]] (bought by the NOT&M on June 20, 1924), [[Beaumont, Sour Lake and Western Railway]], and [[St. Louis, Brownsville and Mexico Railway]].<ref name=handbook-MP>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqm06|name=Missouri Pacific System|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*March 31<!--or April 1?-->: The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] acquires the property of the former Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad,<ref name=\"ICC 1925\"/> in receivership since April 16, 1917.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT481 p. 481]</ref>\n*April 1: The [[Alton and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I) begins operating a short piece of the former [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]],<ref name=IT>Paul Stringham, Illinois Terminal, the Electric Years, {{ISBN|0-916374-82-3}}, pp. 98, 251</ref> in receivership since July 31, 1914.<ref name=\"p. 433\">ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT41 p. 433]</ref>\n*May 1: [[Southern Pacific Company]] subsidiary [[Galveston, Harrisburg and San Antonio Railway]] leases the [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]].<ref name=\"ICC 1926\">ICC (1926)</ref><!--when had SP bought control?-->\n*May 19: The [[Wabash Railway]] gains control of the [[Ann Arbor Railroad (1895-1976)|Ann Arbor Railroad]].<ref name=Moodys-AA>Moody's (1982), p. 852</ref>\n*June: The [[Muskogee Company]], parent of the [[Midland Valley Railroad]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--some stuff says they got the MV in June 1930!?--> acquires control of the [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], in receivership from June 7, 1924 until May 1, 1926.<ref name=Moodys-KO&G/>\n*July 1: The [[Illinois Central Railroad]] acquires control of the [[Gulf and Ship Island Railroad]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*November 5<!--or November 4?-->: [[Western Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[Sacramento Northern Railway]] acquires the property of the electric Sacramento Northern Railroad.<ref name=Moodys-SN>Moody's (1972), p. 98</ref><!--was it in receivership?--> (The Sacramento Northern Railroad had replaced the [[Northern Electric Railway (California)|Northern Electric Railway]] in 1918.)\n*December 31: The [[San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad]], acquired by [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] on December 1, leaves a receivership that began on August 14, 1914.<ref name=sausage>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqs12|name=San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad|author=Nancy Beck Young|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1926}}1926\n*The [[Springfield, Havana and Peoria Railroad]] takes over a portion of the former [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]], in receivership since July 31, 1914,<ref name=\"p. 433\"/> and leases it to the [[Chicago and Illinois Midland Railway]], which becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1926, 1937)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] creates lessor [[Pennsylvania, Ohio and Detroit Railroad]] by merging other lessors, including former Class I railroads [[Cincinnati, Lebanon and Northern Railway]] and [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*May: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] gains control of the [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]],<ref>Moody's (1986), p. 677</ref> whose predecessor had been leased to B&O subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]] until 1915.\n*June 1: The [[Yazoo and Mississippi Valley Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Illinois Central Railroad]], leases the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]].<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 379</ref>\n*June 1: The [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] leases the lines of the [[Boston and Maine Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Connecticut and Passumpsic Rivers Railroad]] and [[Massawippi Valley Railway]] between [[Wells River, VT|Wells River]] and [[Sherbrooke, QC|Sherbrooke]]. (North of [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport]] the lease is assigned to CP subsidiary [[Quebec Central Railway]].)<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, pp. 232, 243</ref> Along with the CP's operation under lease of the connecting [[Newport and Richford Railroad]], also controlled by the B&M, and of the short [[Midland Railroad (Vermont)|Midland Railroad]] (later abandoned), these \"[[Canadian Pacific Lines in Vermont]]\" become Class I in 1927.<ref name=\"ICC 1927\">ICC (1927)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1927}}1927\n*January 1: The [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Coast Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]], begins operating the former [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railway]],<ref>Oliphant's Earning Power of Railroads, 1945, p. 169</ref> in receivership since February 25, 1921.<ref name=\"ICC 1926\"/>\n*January 1: The [[Central New England Railway]] is merged into parent [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]].<ref>Moody's (1969), p. 146</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Denver and Salt Lake Railway]] begins operating the former Denver and Salt Lake Railroad,<ref>Oliphant's Earning Power of Railroads, 1946, p. 297</ref> in receivership since August 16, 1917.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT480 p. 495]</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Georgia and Florida Railroad (1926-1963)|Georgia and Florida Railroad]] begins operating the former Georgia and Florida Railway, in receivership since March 27, 1915.<ref>307 I.C.C. 707 (1959)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] buys a one-third share in the [[Monongahela Railway]], formerly owned jointly by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] and [[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad]].<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 445</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases subsidiaries [[Galveston, Harrisburg and San Antonio Railway]], [[Houston East and West Texas Railway]], [[Houston and Texas Central Railroad]], [[Louisiana Western Railroad]], [[Morgan's Louisiana and Texas Railroad and Steamship Company]], and GH&SA lessor [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]] to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Texas and New Orleans Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 47 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1196, Texas and New Orleans Railroad System</ref>\n*April 1: The new independent [[Toledo, Peoria and Western Railroad]] acquires the property of the former Toledo, Peoria and Western Railway,<ref name=Moodys-TP&Wold>Moody's (1976), p. 111</ref> owned jointly by the [[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad]] and [[Pennsylvania Company]] and in receivership since July 2, 1917.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT38 p. 438]</ref>\n*May 30: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]].<ref name=\"ICC 1927\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1928}}1928\n*The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] buys control of the [[Lehigh Valley Railroad]] and [[Wabash Railway]].<!--or was the LV in September (?) 1962 and the Wabash in 1942?-->{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Illinois Power and Light Corporation]], which controls the electric [[Illinois Traction System]], acquires the [[Illinois Terminal Company]] and leases several subsidiaries to the IT, which becomes Class I.<ref name=IT/><ref>ICC (1927, 1928)</ref>\n*January 14: The [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad]] begins operating the former Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway,<ref name=Moodys-MILW1>Moody's (1982), p. 1260</ref> in receivership since March 18, 1925.<ref name=\"ICC 1926\"/>\n*November 1: The [[Canadian National Railway]] consolidates ten of its U.S. subsidiaries to form the [[Grand Trunk Western Railroad]]. These subsidiaries include the Class I Grand Trunk Western Railway, [[Detroit, Grand Haven and Milwaukee Railway]], and [[Chicago, Detroit and Canada Grand Trunk Junction Railroad]], the latter actually operated under lease by the CN but reported separately.<ref>ICC (1928)</ref><ref>Moody's (1992), p. 237</ref>\n*November 28<!--or December 1?-->: Existing [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Baltimore and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I), successor to part of the [[Maryland, Delaware and Virginia Railway]], acquires the property of former Pennsylvania subsidiary [[Baltimore, Chesapeake and Atlantic Railway]].<ref name=Moodys-B&E>Moody's (1976), p. 261</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1929}}1929\n*The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] gains control of the [[Missouri-Illinois Railroad]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--can't verify that it's not a subsidiary in 1928--> which also becomes Class I this year.<ref>ICC (1928, 1929)</ref>\n*The [[Muskogee Company]], owner of the [[Midland Valley Railroad]] and [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], buys the [[Oklahoma City-Ada-Atoka Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Louisiana and Arkansas Railway]] leases the [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company]].<ref>ICC (1933)</ref><!--it apparently gained control in 1928?-->\n*January 1: The [[Reading Company]] leases subsidiaries [[Perkiomen Railroad]]<ref>ICC (1943)</ref> and [[Port Reading Railroad]].<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 220</ref>\n*January 17: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] gains full control of the [[Northwestern Pacific Railroad]] by purchasing the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]'s one-half share.<ref>Moody's (1992), p. 269</ref>\n*June 1<!--Moody's says June 1, 1928, but is apparently wrong-->: The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Louisville, Henderson and St. Louis Railway]].<ref>ICC (1930)</ref><ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 137</ref>\n*October 19: The [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] purchases the [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] and subsidiary [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]],<ref name=handbook-KCM&O/> and leases the former directly and the latter to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]].<!--says \"Both leases were effective August 1, 1929\" - meaning exactly what?--><ref>ICC (1937)</ref>\n\n==References==\n*[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], Annual Report on the Statistics of Railways in the United States, 1910-\n*Edward A. Lewis, American Shortline Railway Guide, 5th Edition, [[Kalmbach Publishing]], 1996\n*[[Moody's Transportation Manual]]\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Class I railroads}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline of Class I railroads (1910-29)}}\n[[Category:Class I railroads in North America| Timeline 1910]]\n[[Category:Rail transport timelines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Class I timeline series}}\nThe following is a brief history of the North American rail system, mainly through major changes to [[Class I railroad]]s, the largest class by operating revenue.\n\n{{TOCyears|startyear=1910|endyear=1929}}\n\n;{{anchor|1910}}1910\n*July 1: The first year of classification by operating revenue begins.\n*July 1: The property of the independent [[Chicago, Cincinnati and Louisville Railroad]], which entered receivership on February 14, 1908,<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT167 pp. 160-161]</ref> is conveyed to the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 24 Val. Rep. 451 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 477, The Chesapeake and Ohio Railway Company of Indiana<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]]--></ref> a subsidiary of the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]].<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA686 p. 686]</ref>\n*December 23: The property of the [[Oregon Railroad and Navigation Company]] is sold to the [[Oregon-Washington Railroad and Navigation Company]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 44 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 329, Oregon-Washington Railroad & Navigation Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Oregon-Washington Railroad and Navigation Company]]--></ref> remaining a subsidiary of the [[Oregon Short Line Railroad]] ([[Union Pacific Railroad]] system).<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT245 p. 238]</ref><ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA716 p. 716]</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1911}}1911\n*January 1: The [[Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]] begins operations after acquiring the properties of the [[Southern Indiana Railway]] and subsidiary [[Chicago Southern Railway]], which entered receivership on August 19<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT177 pp. 170-171]</ref> and August 25, 1908, respectively.<ref>ICC (1910), [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qx5ntDA_gccC&pg=PT211 pp. 204-205]</ref><ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 97 I.C.C. 535 (1925): Valuation Docket No. 41, Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]]--></ref>\n*February: The [[New York Central Railroad]] sells half of its majority interest in the [[Rutland Railroad]] to the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3JUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA235 The Earning Power of Railroads], 1916, p. 235</ref>\n*April 20: The [[Blacklick and Yellow Creek Railroad]] changes its name to [[Cambria and Indiana Railroad]] (not yet Class I).<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 130 I.C.C. 412 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 498, Cambria and Indiana Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cambria and Indiana Railroad]]--></ref>\n*June 30: The first year of classification by operating revenue ends. There are 177 Class I railroads, including two Canadian companies ([[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Canadian Northern Railway]]) not included in any totals by the ICC, and a separate listing for \"[[Canadian Pacific Lines in Maine]]\" (leased lines of the [[International Railway of Maine]], [[Aroostook River Railroad]], and [[Houlton Branch Railroad]]). [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] lessor [[Atlantic and St. Lawrence Railroad]] is also listed as a Class I railroad.<ref>ICC (1911)</ref>\n*July: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] gains control of the [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]] (not yet Class I)<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqw13|name=Wichita Falls and Wellington Railway|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> and [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I).{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*July 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Cleveland, Akron and Columbus Railway]] and [[Cincinnati and Muskingum Valley Railroad]], the latter not Class I, merge to form the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=ICC-CA&C>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 23 Val. Rep. 365 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 386, [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/ca_c.html Pennsylvania Company and its Leased Lines]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Illinois Central Railroad]] begins operating the property of former subsidiary [[Indianapolis Southern Railroad]], purchased at foreclosure.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA309 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, p. 309</ref>\n*July 21: The [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] buys the property of subsidiary [[Evansville and Terre Haute Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 31 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 202, Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]]--></ref>\n*September 15: The [[Bingham and Garfield Railway]] completes its main line.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 106 I.C.C. 450 (1925): Valuation Docket No. 267, Bingham & Garfield Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Bingham and Garfield Railway]]--></ref> It will be listed as Class II in 1912<ref>ICC (1912)</ref> and Class I in 1913.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA695 p. 695]</ref>\n*September 16: The [[International and Great Northern Railway]] begins operating the former International and Great Northern Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 149 I.C.C. 587 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 355, International and Great Northern Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/International and Great Northern Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since February 27, 1908.<ref name=\"p. 710\">ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA710 p. 710]</ref>\n*November: The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] and [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]] jointly buy control of the [[New Orleans, Mobile and Chicago Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=lScOAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA395 The Earning Power of Railroads], 1914, p. 395</ref>\n*December 28: The property of [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway]] is conveyed to AT&SF lessor [[California, Arizona and Santa Fe Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 127 I.C.C. 1 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 625, Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/California, Arizona and Santa Fe Railway]]--></ref><!--not quite sure about the details - apparently the lease wasn't until March 1, 1912?-->\n\n;{{anchor|1912}}1912\n*January 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pennsylvania Company]] leases the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=ICC-CA&C/>\n*January 1: The [[Minneapolis and St. Louis Railroad]] acquires the property of the [[Iowa Central Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 137 I.C.C. 761 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 510, Minneapolis & St. Louis Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Minneapolis and St. Louis Railroad]]--></ref> formerly independent.<ref name=\"p. 710\"/>\n*March 20: The [[Sunset Railroad]], controlled jointly by the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] and [[Southern Pacific Company]], merges with lessor [[Sunset Western Railway]] to form the [[Sunset Railway]] (no longer Class I).<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 32</ref>\n*April 4: The [[Crystal City and Uvalde Railroad]] is renamed [[San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad]] (not yet Class I).<ref name=sausage/>\n*June 30: The [[Sunset Railroad]] is demoted from Class I to II; it will never return to the former classification. The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] also becomes Class II, since [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]] had been listed as a lessor in 1911, but is now listed as an operating subsidiary, and the revenues of the parent alone are not enough to qualify for Class I. On the other hand, the [[Detroit and Toledo Shore Line Railroad]], [[Oahu Railway and Land Company]], and [[Western Pacific Railroad]] are newly listed as Class I. The [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]] begins including data for subsidiary [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]] with its own data. With the loss of the [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]], [[Evansville and Terre Haute Railroad]], [[Indianapolis Southern Railroad]], [[Iowa Central Railway]], and [[Santa Fe, Prescott and Phoenix Railway]], and electrification of the [[Spokane and Inland Empire Railroad]], the number of Class I railroads drops from 177 in 1911 to 171 as of June 30, 1912.<ref>ICC (1911, 1912)</ref>\n*October 1: The [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Syracuse, Binghamton and New York Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 707\">ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA707 p. 707]</ref>\n*December 9: [[Canadian Northern Railway]] subsidiary [[Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]] completes its line<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 503 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 856, Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]]--></ref> and becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA696 p. 696]</ref>\n*December 24<!--or December 31?-->: The property of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and Puget Sound Railway]] is conveyed to parent [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 44 Val. Rep. 441 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1072, Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]]--></ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1913}}1913\n*January 1: The [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]] begins operating the former Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railway of Illinois,<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA961 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 965</ref> in receivership since July 1, 1909.<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA709 p. 709]</ref>\n*May 1: The [[Denver and Salt Lake Railroad]] begins operating the former [[Denver, Northwestern and Pacific Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 119 I.C.C. 483 (1926): Valuation Docket No. 770, Denver and Salt Lake Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Denver and Salt Lake Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since May 2, 1912.<ref>ICC (1912), p. 665</ref>\n*May 28: The [[Butte, Anaconda and Pacific Railway]] begins electric service.<ref>[[Engineering & Mining Journal]], Volume 97, No. 11, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JR4rAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA3-PA559 p. 559: Butte, Anaconda & Pacific Electrification], March 14, 1914</ref>\n*June 30: The [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]], [[Bingham and Garfield Railway]], [[Florence and Cripple Creek Railroad]], [[Lehigh and New England Railroad]], [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railroad]], [[Missouri, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], and [[Spokane International Railway]] are reclassified from II to I, and the new [[Duluth, Winnipeg and Pacific Railway]] is also Class I. The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]] starts including its data with parent [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]], and, with the disappearance of the [[Chicago, Milwaukee and Puget Sound Railway]] and [[Syracuse, Binghamton and New York Railroad]], the number of Class I railroads rises from 171 in 1912 to 176 as of June 30, 1913.<ref>ICC (1912, 1913)</ref>\n*December 31: The [[Buffalo and Susquehanna Railroad]] is reorganized under the same name,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 36 Val. Rep. 199 (1931): Valuation Docket No. 340, Buffalo & Susquehanna Railroad Corporation et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Buffalo and Susquehanna Railroad]]--></ref> having been in receivership since July 23, 1910. Former parent [[Buffalo and Susquehanna Railway]] (Class II), also in receivership (since May 3, 1910),<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA674 p. 674]</ref> remains independent, and is reorganized as the [[Wellsville and Buffalo Railroad]] (Class II) on December 14, 1915<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA677 677], [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA696 696]</ref> and abandoned in November 1916.<ref>Arthur Stone Dewing, [https://books.google.com/books?id=J_EpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA111 The Financial Policy of Corporations], Volume 1 (Corporate Securities), p. 111</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1914}}1914\n*January 1: The [[Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]] begins recording its lease of the [[Peoria and Eastern Railway]], which dates from April 1, 1890, as such.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 28 Val. Rep. 90 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 264, The Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Peoria and Eastern Railway]]--></ref> Previously the P&E was listed as Class I.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA679 p. 679]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad]] begins operating the former Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railway, which had been in receivership since February 1, 1908.<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 115 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 857, Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Detroit, Toledo and Ironton Railroad]]--></ref> As a consequence of this reorganization, the DT&I no longer controls the [[Ann Arbor Railroad (1895-1976)|Ann Arbor Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 707\"/><ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA675 p. 675]</ref>\n*March 30<!--or April 1?-->: The [[Boston and Maine Railroad]] sells its controlling share in the [[Maine Central Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA1019 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, pp. 1019-1020</ref>\n*April 7: The [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]] is completed.\n*May 1: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I) to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]].<ref>290 I.C.C. 303 (1954): Finance Docket No. 18163, Wichita Falls & Southern Railroad Company et al. Abandonment, etc.</ref>\n*June 1: [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]] subsidiary [[Toledo and Ohio Central Railway]] buys control of the [[Kanawha and Michigan Railway]] from joint owners [[Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway]] (also a NYC subsidiary) and [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqkoAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA493 Poor's Intermediate Manual of Railroads], 1917, p. 493</ref>\n*June 5: [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Southern Kansas Railway of Texas]] is renamed [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]].<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqs22|name=Southern Kansas Railway|author=Chris Cravens|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*June 30: Despite the loss of the [[Peoria and Eastern Railway]], the number of Class I railroads remains at 176, its 1913 value, since [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] lessor [[Chicago, Detroit and Canada Grand Trunk Junction Railroad]], which reports separately, is raised from Class II to I.<ref>ICC (1913, 1914)</ref>\n*July 1: [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] subsidiary [[Pecos and Northern Texas Railway]] is leased in part to the [[Gulf, Colorado and Santa Fe Railway]] and [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]], being split at [[Sweetwater, TX|Sweetwater]].<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqp09|name=Pecos and Northern Texas Railway|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*July 6: The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad]] begins operating the former Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 217 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 1050, Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since March 7, 1912.<ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA730 p. 730]</ref> [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]] is in receivership from March 9, 1912 to July 8, 1914.<ref name=handbook-KCM&O>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqk05|name=Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*July 29: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Northern Central Railway]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*August 14: The [[Utah Railway]] opens, initially operated by the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Utah>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 141 I.C.C. 545 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 538, Utah Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Utah Railway]]--></ref>\n*December 23: The [[New York Central and Hudson River Railroad]] merges with ten subsidiaries, including Class I [[Chicago, Indiana and Southern Railroad]] and [[Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway]], to form the [[New York Central Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 27 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 1022, The New York Central Railroad Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/New York Central Railroad]]--></ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1915}}1915\n*January 23: The [[Canadian Northern Railway]] is completed.<ref>J. Castell Hopkins, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fDurWYs3XuUC&pg=PA753 The Canadian Annual Review of Public Affairs], 1915, p. 753</ref>\n*May 1: The [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] (recently renamed from [[Golden Circle Railroad]]) acquires a portion of the property of former lessee [[Florence and Cripple Creek Railroad]],<ref name=ICC-Midland/> the rest of which is abandoned.\n*June 1<!--or May 1?-->: Due to the financial problems of the [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]], which was to operate the mostly-completed [[National Transcontinental Railway]], the Canadian government retains control of the NTR, grouping it with the existing [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[Intercolonial Railway]] and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]).<ref>J. Castell Hopkins, [https://books.google.com/books?id=fDurWYs3XuUC&pg=PA751 The Canadian Annual Review of Public Affairs], 1915, pp. 751-752</ref><!--what about the last spike on November 17, 1913??-->\n<!--need to get 1915 ICC-->\n*July 1: The [[Monongahela Railroad]] (Class I) and [[Buckhannon and Northern Railroad]] (not Class I), both owned jointly by the [[Pennsylvania Company]] and [[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad]], merge to form the [[Monongahela Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 22 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/mga.html Valuation Docket No. 880, The Monongahela Railway Company]</ref>\n*November 1: The [[Wabash Railway]] begins operating the former Wabash Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 40 Val. Rep. 723 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 897, Wabash Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Wabash Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since December 26, 1911.<ref>ICC (1913), [https://books.google.com/books?id=NcQ7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA686 p. 686]</ref> It will soon lose its control of subsidiaries [[Wabash Pittsburgh Terminal Railway]] and [[Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad (1899-1916)|Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad]] when they reorganize.\n*December 1: Independent [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]] begins operating the property of the former [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railway]], which had been leased to [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 755 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 937, Cincinnati, Indianapolis & Western Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]]--></ref> and entered receivership in February 1915.<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA641 Manual of Statistics], 1919, p. 641</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1916}}1916\n*January 1: The [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railway]] begins operating the former Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railroad,<ref>The Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA573 The Manual of Statistics], 1919, p. 573</ref> which had been in receivership since January 1, 1909.<ref>ICC (1911), [https://books.google.com/books?id=jMI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA700 p. 700]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] begins operating the former New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railroad,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA698 p. 698]</ref> which had been in receivership since July 5, 1913.<ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA734 p. 734]</ref> It retains control of subsidiaries [[Beaumont, Sour Lake and Western Railway]] (not yet Class I), [[Orange and Northwestern Railroad]] (never Class I), and [[St. Louis, Brownsville and Mexico Railway]] (Class I since 1911), but is freed of its former control by the [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]], itself in receivership.<ref>The Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA756 The Manual of Statistics], 1919, pp. 756-757</ref> This system comes to be known as the [[Gulf Coast Lines]].\n<!--need to get 1915 ICC-->\n*July: The [[New York Central Railroad]] sells subsidiary [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]] to the [[Van Sweringen brothers]].<ref name=Vans/>\n*July 1: The [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Virginia and Southwestern Railway]].<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT475 p. 490]</ref> This company still exists as a [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] lessor.\n*July 14: The [[Western Pacific Railroad]], owned by [[holding company]] [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]], acquires the property of the former Western Pacific Railway,<ref>ICC (December 31, 1916)</ref> a subsidiary of the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]] in receivership since March 5, 1915.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA688 p. 688]</ref> (When the D&RG reorganizes in 1921, the WP will control its successor.)\n*August 16: [[Union Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[San Pedro, Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad]] is renamed Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1058 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1062</ref>\n*September 1: The [[Pittsburg, Shawmut and Northern Railroad]], in receivership since August 1, 1905,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA674 p. 674]</ref> terminates its lease of the [[Pittsburg and Shawmut Railroad]],<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7hsUAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PA809 Manual of Statistics], 1918, p. 809</ref> which becomes an independent Class I railroad.\n*November: The [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] buys control of the [[New Orleans and Northeastern Railroad]] from the [[Alabama, New Orleans, Texas and Pacific Junction Railways Company]],<ref>Manual of Statistics Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ex0UAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA215 Manual of Statistics], 1917, p. 215</ref> as well as the latter's minority holdings<!--$448,700--> in [[Cincinnati, New Orleans and Texas Pacific Railway]] parent [[Southwestern Construction Company]]. Through existing shares of that [[holding company]] held by the Southern<!--$833,300--> and subsidiary [[Alabama Great Southern Railroad]]<!--$16,600-->, the Southern now controls the CNO&TP.<!--total of $1,298,600 out of $2,049,300, $100 per share-->\n*November 1: The [[St. Louis-San Francisco Railway]] begins operating the former St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad,<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 41 Val. Rep. 139 (1932): Valuation Docket No. 400, St. Louis-San Francisco Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/St. Louis-San Francisco Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since May 27, 1913.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA692 p. 692]</ref> During its receivership, it has lost control of the [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] and [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railroad]].\n*December 31: The ICC changes its year for which carriers report to end on December 31 rather than June 30. In the preceding six months, the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] has stopped reporting, [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] subsidiaries [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]] and [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]] and [[Kansas City Southern Railway]] subsidiary [[Texarkana and Fort Smith Railway]] have begun to report separately, the [[Pittsburg and Shawmut Railroad]] has commenced independent operations, and the [[Virginia and Southwestern Railway]] has been leased. With the raising of the [[Colorado and Wyoming Railway]] from Class II to I, the number of Class I railroads as of the end of 1916 is 183, up from 181 as of June 30.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916, December 31, 1916)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1917}}1917\n*January 1: The independent [[Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad]] begins operating the property of the former [[New Orleans, Mobile and Chicago Railroad]],<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT488 p. 503]</ref> in receivership since December 19, 1913,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA682 p. 682]</ref><ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 125 I.C.C. 765 (1927): Valuation Docket No. 866, Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad]]--></ref> and previously jointly owned by the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] and [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]].<!--did they sell the stock or did the receivership simply take it out of their control?--><ref>ICC (1914), [https://books.google.com/books?id=AcU7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA721 p. 721]</ref>\n*January 1: The independent [[Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway (1916-1988)|Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Wabash Railway]] subsidiary Wheeling and Lake Erie Railroad,<ref name=ICC-Midland>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 31 Val. Rep. 707 (1930): Valuation Docket No. 396, The Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since June 8, 1908.<ref name=ICC-WPTWLE/>\n*January 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]], [[Vandalia Railroad (1905-1917)|Vandalia Railroad]], and others merge to form the [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=PRR>Christopher T. Baer, [http://www.prrths.com/Hagley/PRR_hagley_intro.htm PRR Chronology] (Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society), accessed April 2009</ref>\n*February 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] acquires control of the [[Coal and Coke Railway]].<ref>Moody's (1986), p. 662</ref>\n*March 15: The [[Pere Marquette Railway]] acquires the property of the Pere Marquette Railroad.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1158 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1160</ref>\n*April 1: The independent [[Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Wabash Railway]] subsidiary [[Wabash Pittsburgh Terminal Railway]],<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1167 Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1169</ref> in receivership since May 29, 1908.<ref name=ICC-WPTWLE>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ p. 677]</ref>\n*April<!--April 14?-->: The [[Sterling Trust]] succeeds the [[Alabama, New Orleans, Texas and Pacific Junction Railways Company]] as [[holding company]] for the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA348 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 348</ref>\n*May 31: The independent [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] begins operating the former Colorado Midland Railway,<ref name=ICC-Midland>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 110 I.C.C. 451 (1926): Valuation Docket No. 673, Midland Terminal Railway Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Midland Terminal Railway]], [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Colorado Midland Railroad]], and [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]]--></ref> a joint subsidiary of the [[Colorado and Southern Railway]] ([[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad]] system) and [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]] that entered receivership on December 13, 1912.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA691 p. 691]</ref>\n*June 1: The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] begins operating the former properties of the Missouri Pacific Railway and subsidiary [[St. Louis, Iron Mountain and Southern Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 40 Val. Rep. 249 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1006, Missouri Pacific Railroad Company et al.<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Missouri Pacific Railroad]]--></ref> both in receivership since August 19, 1915.<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA690 p. 690]</ref>\n*July 18: [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]], in receivership since July 2, 1914,<ref>ICC (June 30, 1916), [https://books.google.com/books?id=QJgZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA664 p. 664]</ref> ceases operations after conveying much of its property to new B&O subsidiary and lessor [[Toledo and Cincinnati Railroad]]. Other pieces of the CH&D are either abandoned or sold to the newly incorporated independent [[Dayton, Toledo and Chicago Railway]];<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 42 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1068, The Baltimore and Ohio Rail Road Company and its Leased Lines<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Toledo and Cincinnati Railroad]]--></ref> former lessor [[Cincinnati, Findlay and Fort Wayne Railway]] is also freed of B&O control, and both independent companies soon abandon their lines.\n*August 1: The [[Savannah and Atlanta Railway]] (not yet Class I) acquires the property of the [[Savannah and Northwestern Railway]].<ref>187 I.C.C. 129 (1932): Savannah & Atlanta Railway Receiver Reconstruction Loan</ref>\n*September 30: The Canadian government acquires control of the [[Canadian Northern Railway]].<ref name=CNor>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA916 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 920</ref>\n*October 1: The [[San Diego and Arizona Railway]] (not yet Class I), half-owned by the [[Southern Pacific Company]], acquires the property of the [[San Diego and South Eastern Railway]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 45 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1064, San Diego and Arizona Railway Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/San Diego and Arizona Railway]]--></ref>\n*December 1: The [[Utah Railway]] begins operating its own line, heretofore leased to the [[Denver and Rio Grande Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Utah/> It immediately becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1917)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1918}}1918\n*January 1: The [[United States Railroad Administration]] takes over operation of most of the U.S. rail network,<ref name=PRR/> including almost all Class I railroads.<ref name=\"ICC 1918, 1919\">ICC (1918, 1919)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases its subsidiaries that had been leased to the [[Pennsylvania Company]],<ref name=PRR/> as well as the [[Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 22 Val. Rep. 1 (1929): Valuation Docket No. 903, [http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pb_w.html Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad Company]</ref>\n*January 17: The [[New York Connecting Railroad]], jointly owned by the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]] and [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], begins hauling freight over the [[Hell Gate Bridge]].<ref name=PRR/> It will become Class I in 1920.<ref>ICC (1919, 1920)</ref>\n*August 5: The [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] ceases operations after entering receivership on July 1, 1918. A piece at the east end continues to be operated under [[trackage rights]] by the [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*August 6: The [[Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway]] (not yet Class I) acquires the property of the former [[Minneapolis, St. Paul, Rochester and Dubuque Electric Traction Company]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 135 I.C.C. 498 (1928): Valuation Docket No. 915, Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Minneapolis, Northfield and Southern Railway]]--></ref> in receivership since February 20, 1916.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT482 p. 497]</ref>\n*October 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Coal and Coke Railway]].<ref>ICC (1918), [https://archive.org/details/annualreportons38statgoog/page/n681 <!-- pg=675 --> p. 762]</ref>\n*December 20: The title \"[[Canadian National Railways]]\" is adopted for the government-owned [[Canadian Northern Railway]] and [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[National Transcontinental Railway]], [[Intercolonial Railway]], and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]).<ref name=CNor/>\n\n;{{anchor|1919}}1919\n*January 1: Former lessor [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) leases the property owned by the [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] and its [[trackage rights]] operations over the remaining portion of the [[Colorado Midland Railroad]].<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*March 10: The [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] subsidiary [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]] enters receivership, under control of the Canadian government.<ref>Commercial Newspaper Company, [https://books.google.com/books?id=InopAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1015 The Manual of Statistics], 1920, p. 1019</ref>\n*June 2<!--or June 1?-->: The [[Cumberland Valley Railroad]] is merged into parent [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], but lessor [[Cumberland Valley and Martinsburg Railroad]] begins operating its own line,<ref name=PRR/> and is large enough to be Class I.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT53 p. 421]</ref>\n*July 31: The [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]] takes over the property of the former [[Missouri, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]],<ref name=Moodys-KO&G>Moody's (1970), p. 216</ref> in receivership since December 13, 1913.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA785 p. 785]</ref>\n*November 15: The [[San Diego and Arizona Railway]] (not yet Class I), half-owned by the [[Southern Pacific Company]], completes its line.\n*December 31: The [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]] is demoted to Class II.<ref name=\"ICC 1918, 1919\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1920}}1920\n*The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]], purchases 1.73% of the stock of the [[Atlanta and West Point Railroad]]. Combined with existing ownership - 1.95% by the ACL and 46.98% by joint subsidiary [[Georgia Railroad]] - this gives the ACL control of the West Point.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA773 p. 773]</ref><ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT49 p. 425]</ref>\n*February 29: The [[Washington Southern Railway]] merges into parent [[Richmond, Fredericksburg and Potomac Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 442\">ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT34 p. 442]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[United States Railroad Administration]] ceases operations, returning control to the railroad companies.<ref name=PRR/>\n*March 1: The [[Akron, Canton and Youngstown Railway]] (not yet Class I) leases the [[Northern Ohio Railway]], which had been leased to the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]], part of the [[New York Central Railroad]] system.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA766 p. 766]</ref><ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT62 p. 412]</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] sells subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]], which was leased to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]], and it resumes independent operations (not yet Class I).<ref name=handbook-WF&SRy>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqw12|name=Wichita Falls and Southern Railway|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*June: The independent [[Evansville, Indianapolis and Terre Haute Railway]] begins operating the property of the former [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad]] subsidiary [[Evansville and Indianapolis Railroad]],<ref>ICC (1938)</ref> in receivership since February 5, 1916.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA761 p. 761]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases subsidiaries [[Cumberland Valley and Martinsburg Railroad]] and [[New York, Philadelphia and Norfolk Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*November 6: [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] subsidiary [[Southern Railway in Mississippi]] is renamed [[Columbus and Greenville Railroad]].<ref name=\"p. 442\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1921}}1921\n*[[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]] gains control of the [[Evansville, Indianapolis and Terre Haute Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] leases a number of subsidiaries, including Class I [[Cincinnati, Lebanon and Northern Railway]], [[Grand Rapids and Indiana Railway]], and [[Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*March 26: The [[Missouri-Illinois Railroad]] (not yet Class I) begins operating the former [[Illinois Southern Railway]],<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 45 Val. Rep. 867 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1185, Missouri-Illinois Railroad Company<!--relevant text at [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Trains/ICC valuations/Missouri-Illinois Railroad]]--></ref> in receivership since September 17, 1918.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA764 p. 764]</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway]] leases the [[Chicago, Terre Haute and Southeastern Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA414 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 414</ref>\n*July 1: The [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railroad]] (not yet Class I) opens and leases the [[Wichita Falls and Southern Railway]].<ref name=handbook-WF&SRR>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqwue|name=Wichita Falls and Southern Railroad|author=H. Allen Anderson|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*August 1: The [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad]], a subsidiary of [[Western Pacific Railroad]] parent [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]], begins operating the former Denver and Rio Grande Railroad,<ref name=D&RG>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA374 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 374</ref> in receivership since January 26, 1918.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA782 p. 782]</ref> (The D&RG had controlled WP predecessor Western Pacific Railway until its 1916 reorganization.)\n*December 20: The [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) purchases the remaining property of lessor [[Cripple Creek and Colorado Springs Railroad]] (formerly Class I).<ref name=\"ICC 1921\">ICC (1921)</ref>\n*December 29: The [[Midland Terminal Railway]] (not Class I) purchases the remaining property of lessor [[Colorado Midland Railroad]] (formerly Class I),<ref name=\"ICC 1921\"/> in receivership since July 1, 1918.<ref name=ICC-Midland/>\n*December 31: The [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Chesapeake and Ohio Railway of Indiana]].<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1922}}1922\n*January: The [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]] begins distributing its [[Chicago and Alton Railroad]] stock, ending its control of that company.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA274 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 274</ref>\n*January 1<!--or 1921-12-31??-->: The [[El Paso and Southwestern Company]] buys the [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]] (no longer Class I) from the [[Phelps Dodge Corporation]] and leases it to lessor [[El Paso and Southwestern Railroad]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA378 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 378</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railway]] begins operating the former Chicago and Eastern Illinois Railroad,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA276 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 276</ref> in receivership since May 27, 1913.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT61 p. 413]</ref> During its receivership, it has lost its relationships with parent [[St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad]] and subsidiary [[Evansville and Indianapolis Railroad]] (not yet Class I).\n*January 1: The [[New York Central Railroad]] leases subsidiaries [[Toledo and Ohio Central Railway]] and [[Kanawha and Michigan Railway]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5YpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA306 Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads], 1922, p. 306</ref>\n*January 31: The [[Tennessee Central Railway]] acquires the property of the former Tennessee Central Railroad,<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/> in receivership since December 31, 1912.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT44 p. 430]</ref>\n*March: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] buy control of the [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]].<ref name=Vans/>\n*April 24: The [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railway]] begins operating the former [[Missouri and North Arkansas Railroad]],<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref> in receivership since April 1, 1912.<ref>ICC (1918), [https://archive.org/details/annualreportons38statgoog/page/n692 <!-- pg=686 --> p. 773]</ref>\n*April 26: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] buy the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]] from the [[New York Central Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*July 1: The [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]] leases the [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]],<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/> both companies being controlled by the [[Van Sweringen brothers]].\n*December 1: The [[International-Great Northern Railroad]] begins operating the former International and Great Northern Railway,<ref name=\"ICC 1922\">ICC (1922)</ref> in receivership since August 11, 1914.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA784 p. 784]</ref>\n*December 31: The [[Akron, Canton and Youngstown Railway]] is raised from Class II to I.<ref>ICC (1921, 1922)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1923}}1923\n*<!--not sure what date - the property was sold at foreclosure January 16, but it usually takes a few weeks before operations are transferred-->The [[Fort Smith and Western Railway]] begins operating the former Fort Smith and Western Railroad,{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} in receivership since October 9, 1915.<ref>ICC (1919), [https://books.google.com/books?id=wsg7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA783 p. 783]</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Van Sweringen brothers]] merge their [[Toledo, St. Louis and Western Railroad]] and lessor [[Lake Erie and Western Railroad]] into the [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]].<ref name=Vans>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 486</ref> The TStL&W had been in receivership since October 22, 1914.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT50 p. 424]</ref>\n*January 20: The new [[Canadian National Railway]] takes over operation of the [[Canadian National Railways]], consisting of the [[Canadian Northern Railway]] and [[Canadian Government Railways]] (primarily the [[National Transcontinental Railway]], [[Intercolonial Railway]], and [[Prince Edward Island Railway]]), as well as the [[Grand Trunk Pacific Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--they're not merged yet - see 1956-->\n*January 30: The [[Grand Trunk Railway of Canada]] is merged into the government-owned [[Canadian National Railway]], completing a process begun in 1920 to save the financially troubled Grand Trunk.<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 1201</ref>\n*April 1: The [[Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad]] begins operating most of the former [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway]] and subsidiary [[Wichita Falls and Northwestern Railway]],<ref name=Moodys-MKT>Moody's (1986), p. 746</ref> in receivership since September 27, 1915 and May 29, 1917, respectively. [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Missouri, Kansas and Texas Railway of Texas]], placed under a receiver's control at the same time,<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT40 p. 436]</ref> is simultaneously reorganized as the [[Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad of Texas]].<ref name=handbook-MKT>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqm08|name=Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad|author=Donovan L. Hofsommer|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> Property not retained in the reorganization includes the [[Shreveport, LA|Shreveport]]-[[Dallas, TX|Dallas]] line, acquired by [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company]] subsidiary<!--?--> [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company of Texas]],<ref>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eql08|name=Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company of Texas|author=Nancy Beck Young|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref> and the [[Oklahoma City, OK|Oklahoma City]]-[[Atoka, OK|Atoka]] line, acquired by the [[Oklahoma City-Ada-Atoka Railway]] (not yet Class I).\n*August 6: The independent [[Columbus and Greenville Railway]] begins operating the property of former [[Southern Railway (U.S.)|Southern Railway]] subsidiary Columbus and Greenville Railroad,<ref>Moody's (1972), p. 295</ref> in receivership since June 4, 1921.<ref name=\"ICC 1922\"/>\n*August 17: The [[Lake Superior and Ishpeming Railway]] merges with the [[Munising, Marquette and Southeastern Railway]] (not Class I) to form the Lake Superior and Ishpeming Railroad.<ref>Moody's (1992), p. 435</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1924}}1924\n*January 1: The [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] leases subsidiary [[Grand Canyon Railway]] (no longer Class I).<ref name=\"ICC 1925\">ICC (1925)</ref>\n*January 1<!--or January 2?-->: The [[Philadelphia and Reading Railway]] merges into parent [[Reading Company]], which becomes an operating railroad.<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 218</ref>\n*February 1: [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Baltimore and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I) begins operating the former [[Maryland, Delaware and Virginia Railway]] west of [[Denton, MD|Denton]].<ref name=Moodys-B&E/> Independent [[Maryland and Delaware Coast Railway]] (not Class I) will acquire the rest on May 14; it is reorganized in 1932 as the [[Maryland and Delaware Seacoast Railroad]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*May 14: The [[Texas and Pacific Railway]] exits a receivership{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} that began on October 27, 1916,<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT36 p. 440]</ref> and is acquired by the [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] by the end of the year.<ref name=\"ICC 1924\">ICC (1924)</ref>\n*June 20: The [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] ([[Gulf Coast Lines]]) buys control of the [[International-Great Northern Railroad]].<ref name=handbook-MP/>\n*October 29: The [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad]] exits a receivership that began on July 21, 1922,<ref name=D&RG/> and is now equally owned by the [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] and [[Western Pacific Railroad]] parent [[Western Pacific Railroad Corporation]].<ref name=Pacific>{{cite book|author=R. A. LeMassena|publisher=[[Sundance Publications]]|title=Rio Grande ... to the Pacific!|year=1974|isbn=0-913582-09-3}}, pp. 139, 149, 163</ref>\n*November: The [[Sterling Trust]] sells the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]] to New York and New Orleans bankers.<ref>Cleona Lewis and Karl T. Schlotterbeck, America's Stake in International Investments, [[Brookings Institution]], 1938, p. 104</ref>\n*November 1: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases the subsidiaries of the [[El Paso and Southwestern Company]], including the [[El Paso and Southwestern Railroad]] and [[Arizona and New Mexico Railway]],<ref name=\"ICC 1924\"/> which the Class I EP&SW Company had operated.\n*November 8: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases subsidiary [[Arizona Eastern Railroad]].<ref name=Moodys-AZER>Moody's (1992), pp. 257-258</ref>\n*December 1: The [[Clinchfield Railroad]], an unincorporated entity organized jointly by the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]] and subsidiary [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], begins operating the [[Carolina, Clinchfield and Ohio Railway]] under lease.<ref name=Moodys-Clinchfield>Moody's (1983), p. 725</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1925}}1925\n*January 1: The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] gains control of the [[Gulf Coast Lines]], including parent [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] and several other Class I railroads: [[International-Great Northern Railroad]] (bought by the NOT&M on June 20, 1924), [[Beaumont, Sour Lake and Western Railway]], and [[St. Louis, Brownsville and Mexico Railway]].<ref name=handbook-MP>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqm06|name=Missouri Pacific System|author=George C. Werner|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n*March 31<!--or April 1?-->: The [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] acquires the property of the former Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railroad,<ref name=\"ICC 1925\"/> in receivership since April 16, 1917.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT481 p. 481]</ref>\n*April 1: The [[Alton and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I) begins operating a short piece of the former [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]],<ref name=IT>Paul Stringham, Illinois Terminal, the Electric Years, {{ISBN|0-916374-82-3}}, pp. 98, 251</ref> in receivership since July 31, 1914.<ref name=\"p. 433\">ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT41 p. 433]</ref>\n*May 1: [[Southern Pacific Company]] subsidiary [[Galveston, Harrisburg and San Antonio Railway]] leases the [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]].<ref name=\"ICC 1926\">ICC (1926)</ref><!--when had SP bought control?-->\n*May 19: The [[Wabash Railway]] gains control of the [[Ann Arbor Railroad (1895-1976)|Ann Arbor Railroad]].<ref name=Moodys-AA>Moody's (1982), p. 852</ref>\n*June: The [[Muskogee Company]], parent of the [[Midland Valley Railroad]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--some stuff says they got the MV in June 1930!?--> acquires control of the [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], in receivership from June 7, 1924 until May 1, 1926.<ref name=Moodys-KO&G/>\n*July 1: The [[Illinois Central Railroad]] acquires control of the [[Gulf and Ship Island Railroad]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*November 5<!--or November 4?-->: [[Western Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[Sacramento Northern Railway]] acquires the property of the electric Sacramento Northern Railroad.<ref name=Moodys-SN>Moody's (1972), p. 98</ref><!--was it in receivership?--> (The Sacramento Northern Railroad had replaced the [[Northern Electric Railway (California)|Northern Electric Railway]] in 1918.)\n*December 31: The [[San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad]], acquired by [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] subsidiary [[New Orleans, Texas and Mexico Railway]] on December 1, leaves a receivership that began on August 14, 1914.<ref name=sausage>{{Handbook of Texas|id=eqs12|name=San Antonio, Uvalde and Gulf Railroad|author=Nancy Beck Young|retrieved=April 2009}}</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1926}}1926\n*The [[Springfield, Havana and Peoria Railroad]] takes over a portion of the former [[Chicago, Peoria and St. Louis Railroad]], in receivership since July 31, 1914,<ref name=\"p. 433\"/> and leases it to the [[Chicago and Illinois Midland Railway]], which becomes Class I.<ref>ICC (1926, 1937)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] creates lessor [[Pennsylvania, Ohio and Detroit Railroad]] by merging other lessors, including former Class I railroads [[Cincinnati, Lebanon and Northern Railway]] and [[Cleveland, Akron and Cincinnati Railway]].<ref name=PRR/>\n*May: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] gains control of the [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]],<ref>Moody's (1986), p. 677</ref> whose predecessor had been leased to B&O subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway (1895-1917)|Cincinnati, Hamilton and Dayton Railway]] until 1915.\n*June 1: The [[Yazoo and Mississippi Valley Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Illinois Central Railroad]], leases the [[Alabama and Vicksburg Railway]] and [[Vicksburg, Shreveport and Pacific Railway]].<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 379</ref>\n*June 1: The [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] leases the lines of the [[Boston and Maine Railroad]] subsidiaries [[Connecticut and Passumpsic Rivers Railroad]] and [[Massawippi Valley Railway]] between [[Wells River, VT|Wells River]] and [[Sherbrooke, QC|Sherbrooke]]. (North of [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport]] the lease is assigned to CP subsidiary [[Quebec Central Railway]].)<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, pp. 232, 243</ref> Along with the CP's operation under lease of the connecting [[Newport and Richford Railroad]], also controlled by the B&M, and of the short [[Midland Railroad (Vermont)|Midland Railroad]] (later abandoned), these \"[[Canadian Pacific Lines in Vermont]]\" become Class I in 1927.<ref name=\"ICC 1927\">ICC (1927)</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1927}}1927\n*January 1: The [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Coast Railroad]], subsidiary of the [[Atlantic Coast Line Railroad]], begins operating the former [[Atlanta, Birmingham and Atlantic Railway]],<ref>Oliphant's Earning Power of Railroads, 1945, p. 169</ref> in receivership since February 25, 1921.<ref name=\"ICC 1926\"/>\n*January 1: The [[Central New England Railway]] is merged into parent [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad]].<ref>Moody's (1969), p. 146</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Denver and Salt Lake Railway]] begins operating the former Denver and Salt Lake Railroad,<ref>Oliphant's Earning Power of Railroads, 1946, p. 297</ref> in receivership since August 16, 1917.<ref>ICC (1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=_MY7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PT480 p. 495]</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Georgia and Florida Railroad (1926-1963)|Georgia and Florida Railroad]] begins operating the former Georgia and Florida Railway, in receivership since March 27, 1915.<ref>307 I.C.C. 707 (1959)</ref>\n*January 1: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] buys a one-third share in the [[Monongahela Railway]], formerly owned jointly by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] and [[New York Central Railroad]] subsidiary [[Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad]].<ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 445</ref>\n*March 1: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] leases subsidiaries [[Galveston, Harrisburg and San Antonio Railway]], [[Houston East and West Texas Railway]], [[Houston and Texas Central Railroad]], [[Louisiana Western Railroad]], [[Morgan's Louisiana and Texas Railroad and Steamship Company]], and GH&SA lessor [[San Antonio and Aransas Pass Railway]] to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Texas and New Orleans Railroad]].<ref>[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], 47 Val. Rep. 1 (1933): Valuation Docket No. 1196, Texas and New Orleans Railroad System</ref>\n*April 1: The new independent [[Toledo, Peoria and Western Railroad]] acquires the property of the former Toledo, Peoria and Western Railway,<ref name=Moodys-TP&Wold>Moody's (1976), p. 111</ref> owned jointly by the [[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad]] and [[Pennsylvania Company]] and in receivership since July 2, 1917.<ref>ICC (1920), [https://books.google.com/books?id=YH8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PT38 p. 438]</ref>\n*May 30: The [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Western Railroad]].<ref name=\"ICC 1927\"/>\n\n;{{anchor|1928}}1928\n*The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] buys control of the [[Lehigh Valley Railroad]] and [[Wabash Railway]].<!--or was the LV in September (?) 1962 and the Wabash in 1942?-->{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Illinois Power and Light Corporation]], which controls the electric [[Illinois Traction System]], acquires the [[Illinois Terminal Company]] and leases several subsidiaries to the IT, which becomes Class I.<ref name=IT/><ref>ICC (1927, 1928)</ref>\n*January 14: The [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad]] begins operating the former Chicago, Milwaukee and St. Paul Railway,<ref name=Moodys-MILW1>Moody's (1982), p. 1260</ref> in receivership since March 18, 1925.<ref name=\"ICC 1926\"/>\n*November 1: The [[Canadian National Railway]] consolidates ten of its U.S. subsidiaries to form the [[Grand Trunk Western Railroad]]. These subsidiaries include the Class I Grand Trunk Western Railway, [[Detroit, Grand Haven and Milwaukee Railway]], and [[Chicago, Detroit and Canada Grand Trunk Junction Railroad]], the latter actually operated under lease by the CN but reported separately.<ref>ICC (1928)</ref><ref>Moody's (1992), p. 237</ref>\n*November 28<!--or December 1?-->: Existing [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] subsidiary [[Baltimore and Eastern Railroad]] (not Class I), successor to part of the [[Maryland, Delaware and Virginia Railway]], acquires the property of former Pennsylvania subsidiary [[Baltimore, Chesapeake and Atlantic Railway]].<ref name=Moodys-B&E>Moody's (1976), p. 261</ref>\n\n;{{anchor|1929}}1929\n*The [[Missouri Pacific Railroad]] gains control of the [[Missouri-Illinois Railroad]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}<!--can't verify that it's not a subsidiary in 1928--> which also becomes Class I this year.<ref>ICC (1928, 1929)</ref>\n*The [[Muskogee Company]], owner of the [[Midland Valley Railroad]] and [[Kansas, Oklahoma and Gulf Railway]], buys the [[Oklahoma City-Ada-Atoka Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n*January 1: The [[Louisiana and Arkansas Railway]] leases the [[Louisiana Railway and Navigation Company]].<ref>ICC (1933)</ref><!--it apparently gained control in 1928?-->\n*January 1: The [[Reading Company]] leases subsidiaries [[Perkiomen Railroad]]<ref>ICC (1943)</ref> and [[Port Reading Railroad]].<ref>Moody's (1976), p. 220</ref>\n*January 17: The [[Southern Pacific Company]] gains full control of the [[Northwestern Pacific Railroad]] by purchasing the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]'s one-half share.<ref>Moody's (1992), p. 269</ref>\n*June 1<!--Moody's says June 1, 1928, but is apparently wrong-->: The [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] leases subsidiary [[Louisville, Henderson and St. Louis Railway]].<ref>ICC (1930)</ref><ref>Mundy's Earning Power of Railroads, 1938, p. 137</ref>\n*October 19: The [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]] purchases the [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway]] and subsidiary [[Kansas City, Mexico and Orient Railway of Texas]],<ref name=handbook-KCM&O/> and leases the former directly and the latter to [[Texas subsidiary]] [[Panhandle and Santa Fe Railway]].<!--says \"Both leases were effective August 1, 1929\" - meaning exactly what?--><ref>ICC (1937)</ref>\n\n==References==\n*[[Interstate Commerce Commission]], Annual Report on the Statistics of Railways in the United States, 1910-\n*Edward A. Lewis, American Shortline Railway Guide, 5th Edition, [[Kalmbach Publishing]], 1996\n*[[Moody's Transportation Manual]]\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Class I railroads}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timeline of Class I railroads (1910-29)}}\n[[Category:Class I railroads in North America| Timeline 1910]]\n[[Category:Rail transport timelines]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_Class_I_railroads_(1910%E2%80%931929)"}
{"title_page": "List of long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Short description|List of long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom}}\nThere are hundreds of '''[[long-distance footpath]]s in the United Kingdom''' designated in publications from public authorities, [[guidebook]]s and [[OS maps]].<ref name=LD /> They are mainly used for [[hiking]] and [[walking in the United Kingdom|walking]], but some may also be used, in whole or in part, for [[mountain biking ]] and [[horse riding]]. Most are in rural landscapes, in varying terrain, some passing through [[National Parks]] and [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/visiting/outdoor-activities/walking| title= Walking|publisher= National Parks|accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref> There is no formal definition of a long-distance path, though the British [[Long Distance Walkers Association]] defines one as a route \"20 miles [32 km] or more in length and mainly off-road.\"<ref name=LD>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/public/what_is_an_ldp.php|title=What is an LDP? [long-distance footpath]|publisher= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref> They usually follow existing [[Rights of way in the United Kingdom|rights of way]], often over private land, joined together and sometimes [[Trail blazing|waymarked]] to make a named route.<ref name=NA>{{cite journal| url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/9027 | title=Out in the country|publisher=[[Natural England]] | date= 29 November 2007 | accessdate=22 August 2018|pages = 12\u201313}}</ref> Generally, the surface is not specially prepared, with rough ground, uneven surfaces and [[stile]]s, which can cause accessibility issues for people with [[disabilities]].<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/9027 | title=Out in the country|publisher=[[Natural England]] | date= 29 November 2007 | accessdate=22 August 2018|page = 10}}</ref> Exceptions to this can be converted [[Rail transport|railways]], canal towpaths and some popular fell walking routes where stone-pitching and slabs have been laid to prevent [[erosion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fixthefells.co.uk/what-we-do/path-repair-techniques/|title=Path Repair Techniques|website=www.fixthefells.co.uk|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Many long-distance footpaths are arranged around a particular theme such as one specific range of hills or a historical or geographical connection.<ref name=NA />\n\n==England and Wales: National Trails==\n{{main|National Trails}}\n[[National Trails]] are a network of long-distance paths in England and Wales (plus a small stretch of the [[Pennine Way]] in Scotland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/pennine-way/routes|title=The Pennine Way - Route Description & Downloads |publisher=National Trails}}</ref>) funded by Natural England and Natural Resources Wales and maintained by [[local authorities]] under a Trail Partnership.<ref name=NT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/the-trails|title= The National Trails|accessdate=22 August 2018|publisher=National Trails website}}</ref> {{As of|August 2018}}, there are over {{convert|2500|mi|km}} of trails on sixteen routes. The newest trail, the [[England Coast Path]], is not complete though more sections are planned to open over the coming months, with a planned completion date of 2020.{{Update after|2020}}<ref name=NT /> There are 83 million visits to the National Trails each year and over 80,000 people complete a trail.<ref>[https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/ National Trails Website]</ref>\n\n[[File:Ivinghoe Beacon seen from The Ridgeway.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ivinghoe Beacon]] (the eastern trailhead) seen looking north from the Ridgeway]]\n[[File:Black Hill (Peak District).jpg|thumb|right|The paved surface of the Pennine Way on [[Black Hill (Peak District)|Black Hill]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n| [[Cleveland Way]] || {{convert|110|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]] || [[Helmsley]] || [[Filey Brigg]] || Runs around the edge of the [[North York Moors National Park]] in a [[horseshoe]] configuration.\n|-\n| [[Cotswold Way]] || {{convert|102|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cotswolds|The Cotswolds]], Central England || [[Chipping Campden]], [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Somerset]] || Runs along the [[Cotswold Edge]] [[escarpment]] of the Cotswold Hills.\n|-\n| [[England Coast Path]] || {{convert|2,795|mi|km|-2|disp=table|sortable=on}}<sup>\u2020</sup> || England || N/A || N/A || Will cover the entire coast of England and will be the longest managed and [[Trail blazing|waymarked]] coastal path in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path|title=England Coast Path|website=National Trails}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Glynd\u0175r's Way]] || {{convert|135|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Powys]], [[Mid Wales|mid]] [[Wales]] || [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]] || [[Welshpool]] || Runs in an extended loop.\n|-\n| [[Hadrian's Wall Path]] || {{convert|84|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England: [[Tyne and Wear]], [[Northumberland]], [[Cumbria]] || [[Wallsend]], Tyne and Wear || [[Bowness-on-Solway]], Cumbria || Runs from the east to west coast along the remains of [[Hadrian's Wall]].\n|-\n| [[North Downs Way]] || {{convert|153|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South Eastern England || [[Farnham]], Surrey ||  [[Dover]], Kent || Passes through the [[AONB|areas of outstanding natural beauty (AONB)]] of the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills]]  and [[Kent Downs]].\n|-\n| [[Offa's Dyke Path]] || {{convert|177|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wales\u2013England border]] || [[Sedbury]], [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Prestatyn]], [[Denbighshire]] || Follows close to the border near the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]].\n|-\n| [[Peddars Way]] and [[Norfolk Coast Path]]<sup>\u2021</sup> || {{convert|97|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England in [[Suffolk]] and [[Norfolk]] || [[Knettishall Heath]], [[Knettishall]], Suffolk ||  [[Cromer]], Norfolk || The two paths join at [[Holme-next-the-Sea]].\n|-\n| [[Pembrokeshire Coast Path]] || {{convert|186|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pembrokeshire]], southwest Wales || [[Poppit Sands]], near [[St Dogmaels]] || [[Amroth, Pembrokeshire|Amroth]] || Has a total of {{convert|35,000|ft}} of ascent and descent and lies almost completely within the [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nt.pcnpa.org.uk/website/sitefiles/nt_page.asp?PageID=6&SubPageID=20 |title=Pembrokeshire Coast Path Statistics |publisher=National Trails |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Pennine Bridleway]] || {{convert|205|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pennines]], Northern England || [[Middleton-by-Wirksworth]], [[Derbyshire]] || [[Ravenstonedale]], Cumbria || Runs roughly parallel to the Pennine Way.\n|-\n| [[Pennine Way]] || {{convert|267|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pennines]], Northern England and Southern [[Scotland]] || [[Edale]], Derbyshire || [[Kirk Yetholm]], [[Scottish Borders]] || Spans the length of the Pennines, according to the [[Ramblers]], \"one of Britain's best known and toughest\" trails.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ramblers' Association |title=Pennine Way National Trail |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/info/paths/pennine.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220133545/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/pennine.html |archivedate=20 February 2006 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Ridgeway]] || {{convert|87|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Berkshire Downs]], Southern England || [[Overton Hill]], near [[Avebury]], [[Wiltshire]] || [[Ivinghoe Beacon]], [[Buckinghamshire]] || [[Ancient trackway]] on a [[chalk]] ridge described as Britain's oldest road.\n|-\n| [[South Downs Way]] || {{convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  [[South Downs]] in Southern England || [[Winchester]], Hampshire || [[Eastbourne]], [[East Sussex]] || Within the [[South Downs National Park]].\n|-\n| [[South West Coast Path]] (South West Way) || {{convert|630|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England: [[Somerset]], [[Devon]], [[Cornwall]] & [[Dorset]] || [[Minehead]], Somerset || [[Poole Harbour]], Dorset || Originated as a route for the [[Her Majesty's Coastguard|Coastguard]] to walk from lighthouse to lighthouse patrolling for [[smugglers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southwestcoastpath.org.uk/about-coast-path/heritage-walks/|title=Heritage|publisher=South West Coast Path}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thames Path]] || {{convert|184|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern England || [[Kemble, Gloucestershire|Kemble]], Gloucestershire || [[Thames Barrier]], [[Charlton, London|Charlton]]|| Follows the [[River Thames]] from its source to the Thames Barrier in [[London]].\n|-\n| [[Yorkshire Wolds Way]] || {{convert|79|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Yorkshire]], England || [[Hessle]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] || [[Filey]], [[North Yorkshire]] || Runs around the [[Yorkshire Wolds]].\n|}\n<sup>\u2020</sup> {{small|When complete in 2020}}<br />\n<sup>\u2021</sup> {{small|Treated as one path by National Trails}}\n\n==Scotland: Great Trails==\n{{main|Scotland's Great Trails}}\n[[File:Fife Coast path at West Wemyss - geograph.org.uk - 1366601.jpg|thumb|right| [[Fife Coastal Path]] at West Wemyss]]\n[[File:West Highland Way 2005 Coe.jpg|thumb|right|[[Aonach Eagach|The Devil's Staircase]] on the [[West Highland Way]]]]\n[[File:Cliffs from Berwickshire Coastal path - geograph.org.uk - 323939.jpg|thumb|right|Cliffs from the [[Berwickshire Coastal Path]]]]\n[[File:A St Cuthbert's Way marker post - geograph.org.uk - 1387283.jpg|thumb|right|A [[St Cuthbert's Way]] marker post at the edge of the square between Grubbit Law and Wideopen Hill]]\n[[Scotland's Great Trails]] are long-distance \"people-powered\" trails (predominantly hiking trails but including cycling, horse-riding and canoe routes) in Scotland.<ref name=sgt1>{{cite web|title=Scotland's Great Trails: the official guide|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.org.uk/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> [[Scottish Natural Heritage]] maintains the official list of Scotland\u2019s Great Trails and is the custodian of the brand, but responsibility for creating and maintaining each route lies with each [[subdivisions of Scotland|local authority]] through which a route passes, although Scottish Natural Heritage provides some of the finance and publicity.<ref name=sgt2>{{cite web|title=About Scotland\u2019s Great Trails|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/aboutsgts/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> There are 29 routes, offering {{convert|1900|mi|km|sigfig=1}} of trails in total.<ref name=\"sgt2\"/>\n\nEach of the routes is clearly waymarked with a dedicated symbol, and run largely off-road. They range in length from {{convert|24|to|210|mi|km|-1}}, and are intended to be tackled over several days, either as a combination of day trips or as an end-to-end expedition. They are primarily intended for walkers, but may have sections suitable for cyclists and horse-riders.<ref name=sgt-faq>{{cite web|title=FAQs|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/faqs/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-07-05}}</ref> One of the trails, the Great Glen Canoe Trail, is designed for [[canoe]]ists and [[kayak]]ers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Great Glen Canoe Trail|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/trail/great-glen-canoe-trail/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-07-05}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n| [[Annandale Way]] || {{Convert|55|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Solway Coast]], Dumfries and Galloway || [[Moffat]] || [[Annan, Dumfries and Galloway|Annan]] || Follows the valley of the [[River Annan]] from its source in the [[Moffat Hills]] to the sea in the [[Solway Firth]].\n|-\n| [[Arran Coastal Way]] || {{Convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Arran]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route around the coastline of the Isle of Arran.\n|-\n| [[Ayrshire Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Ayrshire]] || Glenapp, [[Ballantrae]] || [[Skelmorlie]], North Ayrshire || Runs alongside the coast and forms part of the [[International Appalachian Trail]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ayrshirecoastalpath.org/|title=Scottish walking at its best!|website=ayrshirecoastalpath.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Berwickshire Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Borders]] and Northern England || [[Cockburnspath]], Scottish Borders || [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], [[Northumberland]] || Coastal path spanning the [[Anglo-Scottish border]].\n|-\n|[[Borders Abbeys Way]] || {{Convert|68|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Borders || N/A || N/A || Circular route in the Borders passing through the ruins of many [[abbeys]]: [[Kelso, Scottish Borders|Kelso]] \u2013 [[Jedburgh]] \u2013 [[Hawick]] \u2013 [[Selkirk, Scottish Borders|Selkirk]] \u2013 [[Melrose, Scottish Borders|Melrose]].\n|-\n|[[Cateran Trail]] || {{Convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Perth and Kinross]] and [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]] || [[Blairgowrie and Rattray]] || N/A || Circular route covering many conditions such as farmland, mountains and forest: [[Blairgowrie and Rattray|Blairgowrie]] \u2013 [[Kirkmichael]] \u2013 [[Spittal of Glenshee]] \u2013 [[Alyth]].\n|-\n|[[Clyde Walkway]] || {{Convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South Lanarkshire]] || [[Glasgow]] || [[New Lanark]] ||  Runs close to the [[River Clyde]] for most of its length.\n|-\n|[[Cowal Way]] || {{convert|57|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cowal|Cowal Peninsula]], [[Argyll and Bute]] || [[Portavadie]] || [[Inveruglas]] on [[Loch Lomond]] || Connects with the West Highland Way.\n|-\n|[[Cross Borders Drove Road]] || {{Convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Edinburgh]] and the Scottish Borders ||[[Little Vantage]], near Edinburgh || [[Hawick]]|| One of the newest trails based on existing routes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkacrossscotland.co.uk/the-cross-borders-drove-road/|title=The Cross Borders Drove Road|website= Walk Across Scotland}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dava Way]] || {{Convert|24|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Moray]] || [[Grantown-on-Spey]] || [[Forres]] || Follows the route of the former [[Highland Railway]] which closed in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.davaway.org.uk/|title=Walking and cycling along the Dava Way|website=www.davaway.org.uk/|accessdate= 21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Fife Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|117|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Fife]] || [[Kincardine-on-Forth|Kincardine]] || [[Newburgh, Fife|Newburgh]] || When opened it originally ran from [[North Queensferry]] to [[Tayport]], but was later extended.\n|-\n|[[Formartine and Buchan Way]] || {{Convert|53|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Aberdeenshire]] || [[Dyce]], near [[Aberdeen]] || [[Fraserburgh]] and [[Peterhead]] || Follows the track of the former railway line the [[Formartine and Buchan Railway]] which closed in 1970. The path branches into two sections at [[Maud, Aberdeenshire|Maud]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/aberdeenshire/formartine-buchan-way.shtml|title=The Formartine and Buchan Way|accessdate=22 August 2018|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Forth and Clyde Canal Pathway]] || {{Convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Central Belt]] || [[Bowling, West Dunbartonshire]] || [[Fountainbridge]], Edinburgh || Runs between the [[Firth of Forth]] and the [[Firth of Clyde]].\n|-\n|[[Great Glen Canoe Trail]]|| {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Highlands]] || [[Banavie]], near Fort William || [[Clachnaharry]], near [[Inverness]] || Coast-to-coast [[canoe]] trail on man-made canals and locks.\n|-\n|[[Great Glen Way]] || {{Convert|79|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Highlands || [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] || [[Inverness]] || Follows the [[Great Glen]].\n|-\n|[[Great Trossachs Path]] || {{Convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Trossachs]] || [[Callander]], [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling]] ||  [[Inversnaid]] on the bank of [[Loch Lomond]] || In the [[Loch Lomond and The Trossachs National Park]].\n|-\n|[[John Muir Way]] || {{Convert|134|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Central Belt || [[Helensburgh]], Argyll and Bute || [[Dunbar]], [[East Lothian]] || Named in honour of the Scottish [[conservation movement|conservationist]] [[John Muir]], who was born in Dunbar in 1838 and became a founder of the [[United States]] [[National Park Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/john-muir-way.shtml|title=The John Muir Way|website=walkhighlands.co.uk|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Kintyre Way]] || {{Convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Argyllshire]]|| [[Tarbert, Argyll and Bute|Tarbert]] || [[Machrihanish]] || On the [[Kintyre]] peninsula.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kintyreway.com/routes/|title=Route information and maps|website=Kintyre Way}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Moray Coast Trail]] || {{Convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Moray]] || [[Forres]] || [[Cullen, Moray|Cullen]]|| Part of the [[North Sea Trail]].\n|-\n|[[Mull of Galloway Trail]] || {{Convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[South Ayrshire]]|| [[Mull of Galloway]] || Glenapp, [[Ballantrae]] || Created and maintained by the ''Rotary Club of Stranraer''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mullofgallowaytrail.co.uk/|title=Walk the beautiful south-west corner of Scotland|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[River Ayr Way]] || {{Convert|44|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  Southern Scotland || [[Glenbuck]], [[East Ayrshire]] || [[Ayr]], South Ayrshire || Mostly follows the [[River Ayr]].\n|-\n|[[Rob Roy Way]] || {{Convert|92|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Perthshire]] and [[Stirlingshire]] || [[Drymen]], Stirling || [[Pitlochry]], Perth and Kinross || Takes its name from [[Robert Roy MacGregor|Rob Roy MacGregor]], a Scottish [[folk hero]] and [[outlaw]] of the early 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/rob-roy-way.shtml|title=The Rob Roy Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk|accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Romans and Reivers Route]] || {{Convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Southern Uplands]] || [[Ae, Scotland|Ae]] || [[Hawick]] || Mostly follows former [[Roman roads]].\n|-\n|[[St Cuthbert's Way]] || {{Convert|62|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Borders and Northern England|| [[Melrose, Scottish Borders|Melrose]], Scottish Borders || [[Lindisfarne]], [[Northumberland]] || Named after [[Cuthbert of Lindisfarne|Cuthbert]], a 7th-century [[saint]], a native of the Borders who spent his life in the service of the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/borders/st-cuthberts-way.shtml|title=St Cuthbert's Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Southern Upland Way]] || {{Convert|212|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern Uplands || [[Portpatrick]] || [[Cockburnspath]], [[Berwickshire]] ||Coast-to-coast walk from east to west.\n|-\n|[[Speyside Way]] || {{Convert|80|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Northern Scotland|| [[Aviemore]] || [[Buckie]], Moray || Follows the [[River Spey]]  through some of [[Banffshire]], [[County of Moray|Morayshire]] and [[Inverness-shire]].\n|-\n|[[Three Lochs Way]] || {{Convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Highland Boundary Fault]] to the Southern Highlands || [[Balloch, West Dunbartonshire|Balloch]], [[West Dunbartonshire]] || [[Inveruglas]], [[Argyll and Bute]] || For much of the way it passes through the [[Loch Lomond and The Trossachs National Park]].\n|-\n|[[West Highland Way]] || {{Convert|96|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Lowlands]] to the [[Scottish Highlands]] || [[Milngavie]], near Glasgow || [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], Highlands || Scotland's first and most popular long-distance walking route.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/west-highland-way.shtml|title= Scotland's Great Trails - The West Highland Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[West Island Way]] || {{Convert|30|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Bute]] ||[[Kilchattan Bay]] || [[Port Bannatyne]] || The first waymarked long-distance route on a Scottish island.<ref>[http://www.westislandway.co.uk/ West Island Way]</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other UK long-distance paths==\nThose included here meet the definition of a [[long-distance path]] as being around {{convert|50|km|0|abbr=in}} or more, particularly that they will take more than one day's walking to complete. Some shorter paths linking between major walks (e.g. Maelor Way) are also included.\n\n===Southern England===\n<!--See  Macmillan Ways Section for routes-->\n<!--Abbot's Way, Dartmoor removed as not long enough to class as LDP-->\n<!--Beacon Way removed as not long enough to class as LDP-->\n<!--Clarendon Way removed as not long enough to meet definition of LDP-->\n<!--*[[Pilgrims' Trail]], 45&nbsp;km (28&nbsp;mi) from [[Winchester]] to [[Portsmouth]] Included under Hampshire-->\n<!-- *[[Saints' Way]], [[Padstow]] - [[Fowey]] 42&nbsp;km (26&nbsp;mi) ([[Cornwall]]) Too short -->\n<!-- *[[Two Castles Trail]], {{convert|39|km|abbr=in}} from [[Okehampton]] to [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]] Too Short -->\n[[File:The 1066 Country Walk - geograph.org.uk - 1576650.jpg|thumb|right| The 1066 Country Walk near [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle]]]]\n[[File:Monarch's Way - geograph.org.uk - 752202.jpg|thumb|right| [[Monarch's Way]] looking back at the outskirts of [[Wolverhampton]]]]\n[[File:West Deane Way - geograph.org.uk - 1518266.jpg|thumb|right| Meadows on the [[West Deane Way]]]]\n[[File:All Saints Church, West Camel - geograph.org.uk - 289126.jpg|thumb|right| [[Church of All Saints, West Camel]], viewed from the [[Leland Trail]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n|[[1066 Country Walk]] || {{convert|31|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[East Sussex]] || [[Pevensey Castle]] near [[Pevensey]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Commemorates the year 1066 and the [[Battle of Hastings]].\n|-\n|[[Avon Valley Path]] || {{convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]], [[Hampshire]] and [[Dorset]] || [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]] || [[Salisbury]] || Takes its name from the [[River Avon, Hampshire|River Avon]] and passes through the western edge of the [[New Forest]].\n|-\n| [[Basingstoke Canal| Basingstoke Canal Towpath Trail]] || {{convert|33|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and [[Surrey]] || Penny Bridge, [[Up Nately]], [[Basingstoke]] || [[Woodham, Surrey|Woodham]] || Follows the path of the 200-year-old Basingstoke Canal.\n|-\n|[[Bournemouth Coast Path]] || {{convert|20|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dorset]] and Hampshire || [[Sandbanks]] || [[Milford on Sea]] || Coastal path connecting the [[South West Coast Path]] (via the Sandbanks Ferry) to the [[Solent Way]].\n|-\n|[[Capital Ring]] || {{convert|75|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[London]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route through inner London, crossing the [[Thames]] at [[Richmond, London|Richmond]] and [[Woolwich]].\n|-\n|[[Celtic Way]] || {{convert|725|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wales]] and Southwest England || [[Strumble Head]], [[Pembrokeshire]] || [[St Michael's Mount]], [[Cornwall]] || Visits more than 100 pre-historic sites including [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Celtic+Way|title=Celtic Way|publisher= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Channel to Channel Path]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South West Peninsula]] || [[Seaton, Devon]] || [[Watchet]], Somerset || Connects the [[English Channel]] with the [[Bristol Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Channel+to+Channel+(Devon+-+Somerset)|title=Channel to Channel Path| website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[Chiltern Way]] || {{convert|134|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Bedfordshire]], [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Hertfordshire]], [[Luton]] and [[Oxfordshire]] || [[Hemel Hempstead railway station]] || N/A || Circular route,  originally a {{convert|125|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Millennium Commission|Millennium Project]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Chiltern+Way|title=Chiltern Way|publisher=Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Coleridge Way]] || {{convert|51|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Somerset]] and [[Devon]] || [[Nether Stowey]] || [[Lynmouth]] || Starts in the [[Quantock Hills]] later moving on to the [[Brendon Hills]], within [[Exmoor National Park]].\n|-\n|[[Dartmoor Way]] || {{convert|95|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dartmoor]] || N/A || N/A || In the Dartmoor National Park in southern [[Devon]].\n|-\n|[[Devonshire Heartland Way]] || {{convert|43|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon || [[Okehampton]] || [[Stoke Canon]], [[Exeter]] || West-to-east across Devon, starting in Dartmoor near the Exe Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_id=8707|title=Devonshire Heartland Way|website= LDWA}} Retrieved 2012</ref>\n|-\n|[[Downs Link]] || {{convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Surrey]] and [[West Sussex]] || [[St. Martha's Hill]] near [[Guildford]] || [[Shoreham-by-Sea]] || Heads from the North Downs Way onto the South Downs Way at [[Steyning]].\n|-\n|[[East Devon Way]] || {{convert|38|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West England || [[Exmouth, Devon|Exmouth]], [[East Devon]] || [[Lyme Regis]], West [[Dorset]] || Runs inland but links with the [[South West Coast Path]] at both ends.\n|-\n|[[Essex Way]] || {{convert|81|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Essex]] || [[Epping, Essex|Epping]] || [[Harwich]] || Crosses [[Dedham Vale]] and [[John Constable|Constable]] country to finish at the [[River Stour, Suffolk|Stour estuary]].\n|-\n|[[Exe Valley Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon and Somerset || [[River Exe]] estuary || [[Exford, Somerset|Exford]] in [[Exmoor National Park]]|| Follows the valley of the [[River Exe]] from its source to the coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exploredevon.info/activities/walk/long-walks/exe-valley-way/|title= Exe Valley Way| website= Explore Devon}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Gordano Round]] || {{convert|27|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[North Somerset]] || Roath Road, [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]] || N/A || Figure of eight around the [[Gordano Valley]] via [[Clevedon]] and [[Abbots Leigh]].\n|-\n|[[Great Stones Way]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]] || [[Coate Water Country Park]], [[Swindon]] || [[Salisbury Cathedral]]|| From [[Barbury Castle]] to [[Old Sarum]] with optional detours to [[Avebury]] and [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Great+Stones+Way|title=Great Stones Way|website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Greater Ridgeway]] || {{convert|362|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South and Central England || [[Lyme Regis]], [[Dorset]] on the [[English Channel]] || [[Hunstanton]] on [[The Wash]] || Follows the [[Wessex Ridgeway]], [[The Ridgeway]] National Trail, the [[Icknield Way Path]] and the [[Peddars Way]] National Trail.\n|-\n|[[Greensand Way]] || {{convert|108|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Home counties]] || [[Haslemere]], Surrey || [[Hamstreet]], [[Kent]] || Follows the [[Greensand Ridge]] along the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills]] and Chart Hills.\n|-\n|[[Pilgrims' Trail|Hampshire Millennium Pilgrims Trail]] || {{convert|29|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] || [[Winchester]] || [[Portsmouth]] || Part of the historical Pilgrims' Trail, a 155-mile long-distance footpath connecting [[Winchester Cathedral]] to [[Mont Saint-Michel]] in [[Normandy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/countryside/walking/pilgrimstrail|title=Pilgrim's Trail|website=Hampshire County Council|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hardy Way]] || {{convert|220|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[West Country]] || [[Hardy's Cottage]], [[Higher Bockhampton]] || [[Stinsford]], Dorset || Almost circular, the endpoints being a mile apart, and named after the writer [[Thomas Hardy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Hardy+Way|title=Hardy Way|website=Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[High Weald Landscape Trail]] || {{convert|90|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[West Sussex]], [[East Sussex]], [[Kent]] || [[Horsham]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Passes through the landscapes of the [[High Weald Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]. \n|-\n|[[Isle of Wight Coastal Path]] || {{convert|70|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Wight]] || [[Ryde]] || N/A || Circular coastal route mainly following public footpaths.\n|-\n|[[Itchen Way]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] || [[Hinton Ampner]] near [[New Alresford|Alresford]] || [[Sholing]] || Follows the [[River Itchen, Hampshire|River Itchen]] from its source.\n|-\n|[[Jubilee Trail (footpath)|Jubilee Trail]] || {{convert|88|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset || [[Forde Abbey]] || [[Bokerley Dyke]] || Created to celebrate [[The Ramblers|The Ramblers' Association]]'s Diamond Jubilee and passes through many historical sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jubilee Trail (Dorset)|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Jubilee+Trail+(Dorset)|publisher=LDWA|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[King's Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Winchester]] || [[Portchester]] ||  Created by the Ramblers' Association as a memorial to the late Allan King (who formed many local groups in Hampshire).\n|-\n|[[Land's End Trail]] || {{convert|303|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West Peninsula || [[Land's End]], Cornwall || [[Avebury]], [[Wiltshire]] || Links Land's End with many of England's central long-distance trails.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_id=260|title=Land's End Trail|website= LDWA webpage}} Retrieved 26 February 2012</ref>\n|-\n|[[Leland Trail]] || {{convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || [[King Alfred's Tower]], [[Brewham]] || [[Ham Hill, Somerset|Ham Hill]] || Named after the [[antiquary]] and poet [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Leland+Trail|title=Leland Trail\n|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Liberty Trail]] || {{convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset and [[Dorset]] || [[Ham Hill, Somerset|Ham Hill]] || [[Lyme Regis]] || Based on the route rebels travelled to join the [[Monmouth Rebellion]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.visitsouthsomerset.com/index.jsp?articleid=12643 |title=Liberty Trail |access-date=25 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025190810/http://www.visitsouthsomerset.com/index.jsp?articleid=12643 |archive-date=25 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Limestone Link]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South West England]] || [[Mendip Hills]], Somerset || [[Cold Aston]], [[Gloucestershire]] || Connects with the [[Mendip Way]] and the [[Cotswold Way]].\n|-\n|[[London Outer Orbital Path]] (''The LOOP'') || {{convert|150|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || London || [[Erith]] || [[Rainham, London|Rainham]] || Circular route around the edge of [[Outer London]].\n|-\n|[[Mendip Way]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || [[Uphill]] near [[Weston-super-Mare]] || [[Frome]] || On the [[Mendip Hills]], giving views over the [[Somerset Levels]].\n|-\n|[[Monarch's Way]] || {{convert|615|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern England || [[Worcester]] || [[Shoreham-by-Sea]], West Sussex || Approximates the escape route taken by [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]] in 1651 after being defeated in the [[Battle of Worcester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Monarch%27s+Way|title=Monarch's Way|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New Lipchis Way]] || {{convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] and [[West Sussex]] || [[Liphook]] || [[West Wittering]] || Passes through [[Midhurst]] and [[Chichester]] crossing the [[Western Weald]] and [[South Downs]].\n|-\n|[[Orange Way]] || {{convert|350|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  [[Devon]], [[Dorset]], [[Hampshire]], [[Berkshire]] and [[Buckinghamshire]] || [[Brixham]], Devon || London || Follows the march in 1688 of [[Prince William of Orange]] and his army from Brixham to London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange Way|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_name=Orange+Way|work=LDWA website|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oxford Canal Walk]] || {{convert|82|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Oxfordshire]], [[Warwickshire]] and the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] || [[Oxford]] || [[Coventry]] || Follows the [[towpath]] of the [[Oxford Canal]].<ref>[http://www.waterscape.com/things-to-do/walking/routes/230/oxford-canal-walk  Oxford Canal Walk]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oxford Green Belt Way]] || {{convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Oxfordshire || N/A || N/A || Circular route through the [[Oxford Green Belt]].\n|-\n|[[Oxfordshire Way]] || {{convert|62|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Oxfordshire and [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Bourton-on-the-Water]] || [[Henley-on-Thames]] || Passes from the [[Cotswolds]] to the [[Chiltern Hills]].\n|-\n|[[Pilgrims' Way]] || {{convert|120|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South Eastern England || [[Winchester, Hampshire|Winchester]] || Shrine of [[Thomas Becket]], [[Canterbury]]|| Historical route taken by [[pilgrims]] to and from the shrine of Thomas Becket. An ancient trail of which perhaps two-thirds is still identifiable, much of it now incorporated into the [[North Downs Way]] National Trail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Pilgrims+Way|title=Pilgrims Way|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Quantock Greenway]] || {{convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || N/A || N/A || A figure-of-eight centred on [[Triscombe]] in the [[Quantock Hills]].\n|-\n|[[River Parrett Trail]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset & Somerset || Chedington || [[Bridgwater Bay]], [[Bristol Channel]] || Follows the [[River Parrett]] to the coast.\n|-\n|[[Royal Military Canal Path]] || {{convert|27|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent and East Sussex || [[Seabrook, Kent|Seabrook]] || [[Pett Level]] || Follows the [[Royal Military Canal]] and touches the northern edge of [[Romney Marsh]].\n|-\n|[[Samaritans Way South West]] || {{convert|103|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West England || [[Clifton Suspension Bridge]] || [[Lynmouth]] || Opened by the Ramblers and the [[Samaritans (charity)|Samaritans]] in part to help local farmers. Only the section from [[Bristol]] to [[Goathurst]] is [[waymarking|waymarked]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/samaritanssouthwest.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807174810/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/samaritanssouthwest.html |archivedate=7 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }},</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Sarum Way|Sarum Way]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route around the city of [[Salisbury]], only partly waymarked.\n|-\n|[[Saxon Shore Way]] || {{convert|163|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South East England ||  [[Gravesend]], Kent || [[Hastings]], East Sussex, || Traces the shoreline as it was in [[Roman Britain|Roman]] times and visits many historical sites of the period.<ref>[https://www.visitkent.co.uk/saxon-shore-way/ Saxon Shore Way] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822050051/https://www.visitkent.co.uk/saxon-shore-way/ |date=22 August 2018 }}, Visit Kent</ref>\n|-\n|[[Serpent Trail]] || {{convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire, Surrey and West Sussex || [[Haslemere]] || [[Petersfield]] || Designed to join up many of the [[heathland]] areas in the western [[Weald]].\n|-\n|[[Severn Way]] || {{convert|210|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Mid Wales]] and Western England || [[Plynlimon]], the [[Cambrian Mountains]] || [[Bristol]] || Follows the course of the [[River Severn]] from its source to the [[Severn Estuary]].\n|-\n|[[Shipwrights Way]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Alice Holt Forest]] || [[Portsmouth]] || Traces the route that might have been taken by timber from forest to [[shipyards]] for the construction of [[warships]].<ref>[https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/countryside/walking/shipwrightsway Shipwrights Way], [[Hampshire County Council]]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Solent Way]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Milford on Sea]] || [[Emsworth]] || Follows the coast of the [[Solent]].\n|-\n|[[Stour Valley Walk]] || {{convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent || [[Pegwell Bay]] || [[Lenham]] ||  Follows the [[River Stour, Kent|River Stour]], through the Low [[Weald]] and [[Kent Downs]], from its source to its estuary.\n|-\n|[[Stour Valley Way]]  || {{convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset and Wiltshire || [[Stourton with Gasper]] || [[Hengistbury Head]] || Follows the  River Stour as it winds through the Dorset countryside.\n|-\n|[[St. Swithun's Way]] || {{convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and Surrey || [[Winchester Cathedral]] || [[Farnham]] || Named after [[Swithun]], a 9th-century [[Bishop of Winchester]], and roughly follows a short stretch of the [[Pilgrims' Way]].\n|-\n|[[Sussex Border Path]] || {{convert|138|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || West & East Sussex || [[Thorney Island (West Sussex)|Thorney Island]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Follows the Sussex border with Hampshire, Surrey and Kent.\n|-\n|[[Sussex Ouse Valley Way]] || {{convert|42|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || West & East Sussex || [[Lower Beeding]] || [[Seaford, East Sussex|Seaford]] || Follows the [[River Ouse, Sussex|River Ouse]] from its source to the [[English Channel]].\n|-\n|[[Tarka Trail]] || {{convert|180|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Devon]] || [[Barnstaple]] || N/A || Two separate circular routes based on the fictional route taken by [[Tarka the Otter]] in the book of the same name.\n|-\n|[[Test Way]] || {{convert|49|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Berkshire]] and [[Hampshire]] || [[Walbury Hill]] || [[Totton and Eling]] || Passes through the towns of [[Romsey]] and [[Totton]] and starts in the [[Test Valley]].\n|-\n|[[Thames Down Link]] || {{convert|15|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || London and Surrey || [[Kingston Bridge, London|Kingston Bridge]] || [[Box Hill & Westhumble railway station|Box Hill Station]] || Links the [[Thames Path]] and the [[North Downs Way]].\n|-\n|[[Three Castles Path]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and Berkshire || [[Winchester Castle]] || [[Windsor Castle]] || As well as Winchester Castle and Windsor Castle, passes through [[Odiham Castle]]; unwaymarked.\n|-\n|[[Two Moors Way]] || {{convert|102|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon & Somerset || [[Ivybridge]], [[Dartmoor National Park]] || [[Lynmouth]], [[North Devon Coast]] || Across Dartmoor over exposed moorland.\n|-\n|[[Vanguard Way]] || {{convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Surrey, Kent and East Sussex || [[East Croydon]] || [[Newhaven, East Sussex|Newhaven]] || Connects Central London with the [[Wandle Trail]] along the [[River Wandle]] from [[Croydon]].\n|-\n|[[Wayfarers Walk]] || {{convert|70|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Berkshire and Hampshire || [[Walbury Hill]] || [[Emsworth]] || Approximates an ancient route that might have been used by [[Droving|drovers]] taking cattle to market.\n|-\n|[[Wealdway]] || {{convert|83|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent and East Sussex || [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] || [[Eastbourne]] || Connects the [[Thames Estuary]] with the English Channel and also traverses the [[Ashdown Forest]].\n|-\n|[[Wessex Ridgeway]] || {{convert|136|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Wiltshire and Dorset || [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]] || [[Lyme Regis]] || One of the four long-distance footpaths referred to as the [[Greater Ridgeway]].\n|-\n|[[West Deane Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Taunton Deane]] area of [[Somerset]] || [[Taunton]] || N/A || Circular walk in the Vale of Taunton Deane.\n|-\n|[[West Devon Way]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon || [[Okehampton]] || [[Radford, Plymstock|Radford Castle]], Hooe Lake, [[Plymouth]] || Links with the [[Tamar Valley Discovery Trail]] and the [[Two Castles Trail]] to form the 'West Devon Triangle', a 90-mile circuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=West+Devon+Way|title=West Devon Way|publisher=The Long Distance Walkers Association|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wey South Path]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Surrey and West Sussex || [[Guildford]] || [[Houghton, West Sussex|Houghton Bridge]] || Follows the banks of the [[River Wey]] and the [[Wey and Arun Canal]].\n|}\n\n===Thames to Mersey===\n\n<!--Cross Cotswold Pathway \u2013 see [[Macmillan Ways]] below -->\n<!--Colne Valley Path removed as not long enough to meet definition of LDP-->\n<!-- Grafton Way, Northants, removed as too short at 13miles/21k -->\n<!-- *[[Knightley Way]], [[Northamptonshire]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Knightley Way|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Knightley+Way|publisher=LDWA|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref> \u2013 too short at 12 miles -->\n<!-- *[[Six Shires Circuit]], {{convert|331|km|0|abbr=in|order=flip}} in [[Bedfordshire]], [[Cambridgeshire]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Northamptonshire]] and [[Rutland]] - Needs reference -->\n<!-- [[File:The Viking Way, descending to Cringle Brook - geograph.org.uk - 544394.jpg|thumb|right|[[The Viking Way]], looking down to to [[Cringle Brook]]]] -->\n[[File:Footpath - Derwent Valley Heritage Way - geograph.org.uk - 215806.jpg|thumb|right| The [[Derwent Valley Heritage Way]] along Whitewells Road]]\n[[File:Trent Valley Way - geograph.org.uk - 497951.jpg|thumb|right| A view of the former [[High Marnham power station]] on the [[Trent Valley Way]]]]\n[[File:Cromford Canal - geograph.org.uk - 1522419.jpg|thumb|right| The [[Derwent Valley Heritage Way]] next to the [[Cromford Canal]]]]\n[[File:The Viking Way at Spot Height 62m - geograph.org.uk - 410384.jpg|thumb|right| A field of [[rapeseed]] on the [[Viking Way]]]]\n\n{| class=\