ire Way]] || {{convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Tutshill]] || [[Tewkesbury]] || Routes through the [[Forest of Dean]], [[Cotswolds]] and the [[Severn Plain]].\n|-\n|[[Gritstone Trail]] || {{convert|35|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cheshire East]] and [[Staffordshire]] || [[Disley railway station]], [[Disley]] || [[Mow Cop]], [[Kidsgrove]] || Mostly through the western section of the [[Peak District]] National Park.\n|-\n|[[Heart of England Way]] || {{convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[English Midlands|Midlands]] || [[Milford, Staffordshire|Milford]], Staffordshire || [[Bourton-on-the-Water]], Gloucestershire || Links the [[Cannock Chase|Cannock Chase Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] with the [[Cotswolds#Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|Cotswolds Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]; officially recognised by the four councils it passes through.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heartofenglandway.org/the-route/about-the-route/|title=About the Route|website=www.heartofenglandway.org|accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Herefordshire Trail]] || {{convert|154|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Herefordshire]] || [[Ledbury]], Herefordshire || N/A || Circular route linking the market towns of [[Leominster]], [[Bromyard]], [[Ledbury]], [[Ross-on-Wye]] and [[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]]. [[waymarking|Waymarks]] planned but not yet in place.\n|-\n|[[Hereward Way]] || {{convert|110|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[East Anglia]] || [[Oakham]] || [[East Harling]] ||  Through [[Thetford Forest]] linking the [[Viking Way]] and the [[Peddars Way]] long-distance footpaths. The [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]] to [[Peterborough]] section is not fully [[waymarking|waymarked]], but walkers travelling between those two places can follow the [[waymarking|waymarked]] [[Torpel Way]].\n|-\n|[[Hertfordshire Way]] || {{convert|194|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hertfordshire]] || N/A || N/A || Circular walk in open countryside, although some parts are within 20 miles of London. Passes through the county town of [[Hertford]] and the towns of [[Royston, Hertfordshire|Royston]] and [[Bishop\u2019s Stortford]]. \n|-\n|[[Icknield Way Path]] || {{convert|110|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Cambridgeshire]], [[Norfolk]] || [[Ivinghoe Beacon]] || [[Knettishall Heath]] || [[Prehistoric]] pathways passing through many sites of archaeological remains.<ref>[http://www.icknieldwaypath.co.uk/ Icknield Way Path]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Jack Mytton Way]] || {{convert|93|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Shropshire]] || [[Bridgnorth]] || [[Much Wenlock]] || Runs through the [[Shropshire Hills]] and the [[Clee Hills]] including parts of [[Wenlock Edge]].\n|-\n|[[Jurassic Way]] || {{convert|88|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[The Midlands]] || [[Banbury]], Oxfordshire || [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]], Lincolnshire || Mostly follows a [[Jurassic]] [[limestone]] ridge, from where its name derives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Jurassic+Way|title= Jurassic Way | publisher= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Lea Valley Walk]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South East England]] || [[Leagrave]], [[Bedfordshire]] || [[Limehouse Basin]], [[Limehouse]], [[East End of London|East London]] || Follows the [[River Lea]] from its source and along the [[Lee Navigation]] to the [[East India Docks]] in [[London]].\n|-\n|[[Limestone Way]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Derbyshire, [[Staffordshire]] || [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]] || [[Rocester]] || Through the limestone  [[Derbyshire Dales]] finishing in [[Dove Valley]].\n|-\n|[[Limey Way]] || {{convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Derbyshire]] || [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]] || [[Dovedale]] || In the [[White Peak]] area in limestone countryside visiting twenty dales.\n|-\n|[[Maelor Way]] || {{convert|24|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Shropshire]], [[Cheshire]] and into [[Wrexham County Borough|Wrexham]], [[Wales]] || [[Grindley Brook]] || [[Bronygarth]] || Links six long-distance footpaths, the [[Offa's Dyke Path]] National Trail, while travelling through meadows and woodland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrexham.gov.uk/english/leisure_tourism/prow/maelor_way.htm|title=The Guide to the Maelor Way|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Mercian Way]] || {{convert|230|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[The Midlands]] and [[Northern England]] || [[Salisbury]] || [[Chester]] || Part of [[National Cycle Network|National Cycle Route]] 4, but also well used by walkers.\n|-\n|[[Midshires Way]] || {{convert|230|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South-East England, the Midlands and Northern England || [[Chiltern Hills]] near [[Bledlow]], [[Buckinghamshire]] || [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]] || Footpath and bridleway linking the [[Ridgeway National Trail|Ridgeway]] with the [[Pennine Way]] across Middle England.\n|-\n|[[Mortimer Trail]] || {{convert|30|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Shropshire and [[Herefordshire]] || [[Ludlow]] || [[Kington, Herefordshire|Kington]] || Runs through the [[Welsh Marches]] on the English side of the Anglo-Welsh border and named after the [[Mortimer]] family of ruling [[Marcher Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Mortimer+Trail|title=Mortimer Trail|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nar Valley Way]] || {{convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Norfolk || [[King's Lynn]] || [[Gressenhall]] || Through the watershed of the [[River Nar]].<ref>[http://www.west-norfolk.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=21716 Borough Council of King's Lynn & West Norfolk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415215314/http://www.west-norfolk.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=21716 |date=15 April 2008 }} Retrieved 28 February 2012</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nene Way]] || {{convert|110|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Northamptonshire]], Cambridgeshire and Lincolnshire || [[Badby]] || [[Lincolnshire]] || Follows the course of the [[River Nene]].\n|-\n|[[New River Path]] || {{convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hertfordshire and North London || New Gauge, [[Hertford]] || New River Head, [[Islington]] || Follows the course of the [[New River (England)|New River]] aqueduct.\n|-\n|[[North Worcestershire Path]] || {{convert|35|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Worcestershire]] || [[Kinver]] || [[Major's Green]] || Links four [[country parks]] in the north-east area of the historic county.\n|-\n|[[Ouse Valley Way]] || {{convert|150|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || The Midlands and the East of England || [[Syresham]], [[Northamptonshire]] || [[The Wash]] || Follows the [[River Great Ouse]] from its source to the sea.\n|-\n|[[Pathfinder March]] || {{convert|46|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Cambridgeshire || N/A || N/A || Annual circular route around former [[RAF]] Pathfinder airfields in [[Cambridgeshire]], held on the Saturday closest to Midsummers Day.\n|-\n|[[Peak District Boundary Walk]] || {{convert|190|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Derbyshire, Cheshire, Yorkshire, Staffordshire || [[Buxton]] Market Place || [[Buxton]] Market Place || A circular walking trail, broadly following the boundary of the [[Peak District]] national park. The route was developed by the Friends of the Peak District (a branch of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]]).\n|-\n|[[Robin Hood Way]] || {{convert|104|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || The Midlands || [[Nottingham Castle]] || [[Edwinstowe]], [[Sherwood Forest]] || Commemorates the [[folklore]] of [[Robin Hood]].\n|-\n|[[Sabrina Way]] || {{convert|203|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || The Midlands and Central England || [[Hartington, Derbyshire|Hartington]], Derbyshire || [[Great Barrington, Gloucestershire|Great Barrington]], Gloucestershire|| [[Bridleway]] providing a link between t