hire || [[Shrewsbury]] || [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]] || Re-waymarked in 2017 to 2019, the Main Route South (122 miles) and Main Route North (70 miles) are circulars from [[Shrewsbury]], with a further 10-mile northern spur to [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]]. <ref>[https://shropshireway.org.uk/ Shropshire Way Association] </ref>\n|-\n|[[South Cheshire Way]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Cheshire, Shropshire and Staffordshire || [[Grindley Brook]] || [[Mow Cop]] ||Connects with several other long-distance paths, including the [[Maelor Way]], the [[Staffordshire Way]] and the [[Sandstone Trail|Sandstone]] and [[Cheshire Gritstone Trail|Gritstone Trails]].\n|-\n|[[Staffordshire Way]] || {{convert|92|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Staffordshire || [[Mow Cop]] || [[Kinver Edge]] || Opened in three stages by [[Staffordshire County Council]] between 1977 and 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.staffordshire.gov.uk/environment/eLand/RightsofWay/PromotedRoutes/distancewalks/staffordshire-way-booklet-2.pdf|title=The Staffordshire Way - Official Guide|publisher=[[Staffordshire County Council]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Stour Valley Path]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[East Anglia]] || [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]] || [[Cattawade]], [[Manningtree]] || Follows the [[Drainage basin|catchment area]] of the [[River Stour, Suffolk|River Stour]] and the majority of the route forms part of [[European walking route E2|European Path E2]].\n|-\n|[[St Edmund Way]] || {{convert|79|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Essex, Suffolk and [[Norfolk]] || [[Manningtree]] || [[Brandon, Suffolk|Brandon]] || Follows Stour Valley Path; not waymarked but on OS mapping.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Edmund Way|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_name=St+Edmund+Way|publisher=LDWA|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St Kenelm's Trail|St. Kenelm's Trail]] || {{convert|95|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Gloucestershire and Worcestershire || [[Clent Hills]] || [[Winchcombe]] || Originally devised by John Price, linking the two places most commonly associated with the legend of [[St Kenelm]].\n|-\n|[[St. Peter's Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Essex || [[Chipping Ongar]] || [[Church of St Peter-on-the-Wall, Bradwell-on-Sea|Chapel of St Peter-on-the-Wall]] || Runs across the agricultural land of Essex passing [[Hanningfield Reservoir]] and the inlets of the [[Blackwater Estuary]] going on to reach the coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essexhighways.org/uploads/files/st_peters_way.pdf|title=The St Peter\u2019s Way|publisher= Essex Highways|accessdate= 21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Suffolk Coast Path]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Suffolk]] || [[Felixstowe]] || [[Lowestoft]] || Follows the [[Heritage coast]].\n|-\n|[[Swan's Way (footpath)|Swan's Way]] || {{convert|65|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Northamptonshire, Buckinghamshire and Oxfordshire || [[Salcey Forest]], [[Milton Keynes]] || [[Goring-on-Thames]] || Bridleway forming the Buckinghamshire section of the [[Midshires Way]].\n|-\n|[[Tas Valley Way]] || {{convert|25|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Norfolk]] || [[Cringleford]] || [[Attleborough]] || Follows the course of the [[River Tas]] to the source near [[New Buckenham]].<ref>[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Tas+Valley+Way   Tas Valley Way], LDWA</ref>\n|-\n|[[Telford T50 50 Mile Trail]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Telford]] || [[Telford Town Park]] || [[n/a]] || A waymarked 50 mile route created in 2018 to celebrate Telford's 50th birthday. Many rural sections. <ref>[https://www.telfordt5050miletrail.org.uk/ Telford T50 50 Mile Trail] </ref>\n|-\n|[[Three Forests Way]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Essex and [[Hertfordshire]] || [[Harlow]] || N/A || Circular route through [[Epping Forest|Epping]], [[Hainault Forest Country Park|Hainault]] and [[Hatfield Forest|Hatfield]] forests on the borders of [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]].<ref>[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_id=469  Three Forests Way], LDWA</ref>\n|-\n|[[Three Shires Way]] || {{convert|49|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || East Anglia || [[Grafham Water]], Cambridgeshire || [[Tathall End]], Milton Keynes || Bridleway through rural landscape and [[ancient woodland]]. It originally ended in [[Salcey Forest]] but the [[Grafham Water Circular Ride]], of 12.4 miles around the [[Grafham Water|reservoir]], has now been added to the route.<ref>[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Three+Shires+Way]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Trent Valley Way]] || {{convert|116|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire and [[Lincolnshire]] || [[Trent Lock]] || [[Alkborough]] || Follows the [[River Trent]]; originally created in 1998.\n|-\n|[[Viking Way]] || {{convert|147|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Lincolnshire]] and [[Rutland]] || [[Barton-upon-Humber]] || [[Oakham]] || Links other major routes including the [[Macmillan Way]] and the [[Yorkshire Wolds Way]]; most is designated as part of the European [[E2 European long distance path|E2 footpath]]. \n|-\n|[[Way for the Millennium]] || {{convert|41|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Staffordshire]] || [[Newport, Shropshire]] || [[Burton upon Trent]] || East\u2013west route across Staffordshire, designed for easy walking.\n|-\n|[[Weavers Way]] || {{convert|61|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Norfolk || [[Cromer]] || [[Great Yarmouth]] || Can be combined with the [[Peddars Way]] to make a circuit around Norfolk; links with the [[North Norfolk Coastal Path]] and the [[Angles Way]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.norfolk.gov.uk/out-and-about-in-norfolk/norfolk-trails/long-distance-trails/weavers-way/about-weavers-way-and-points-of-interest|title=About Weavers' Way and points of interest|publisher=Norfolk County Council}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[W