path_name=St+Bega%27s+Way|title=St Bega's Way|publisher=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Cuthbert's Way]] || {{convert|62|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Borders]] and Northumberland || [[Melrose, Scotland|Melrose]] || [[Lindisfarne]] || Links [[Melrose Abbey]], where [[Cuthbert]] began his religious life, with his burial place on [[Lindisfarne|Holy Island]].\n|-\n|[[St Oswald's Way]] || {{convert|97|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Northumberland]] || [[Lindisfarne]] || [[Battle of Heavenfield|Heavenfield]] || Links places associated with [[Oswald of Northumbria|St. Oswald]], the king of Northumbria in the early 7th century.\n\n|- \n|[[Stanza Stones Trail]] ||{{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || West Yorkshire || [[Marsden, West Yorkshire|Marsden]] || [[Ilkley]] ||  Links six stones engraved with poems by [[Simon Armitage]]<ref name=\"ldwa-stanza\">{{cite web |title=Stanza Stones Trail |url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Stanza+Stones+Trail |publisher=LDWA |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Teesdale Way]] || {{convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Cumbria and North Yorkshire || [[Dufton]] || [[Warrenby]] ||  Follows the [[River Tees]] as it passes Cumbrian moorlands to Teeside and the coast.\n|-\n|[[Trans Pennine Trail]] || {{convert|350|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Lancashire, Greater Manchester, East Yorkshire and [[Derbyshire]] || [[Southport]] || [[Hornsea]] || Runs coast to coast across northern England, forming part of [[European walking route E8]].\n|-\n|[[Weardale Way]] || {{convert|73|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[County Durham]], [[Tyne and Wear]] || [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] || [[Wearhead]] || Follows the [[River Wear]] from the sea to the east Pennines.\n|-\n|[[White Rose Walk]] || {{convert|35|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || North Yorkshire || [[Kilburn White Horse]] || [[Roseberry Topping]] || Takes in the highest peaks in the area such as [[Carlton Moor]], [[Sutton Bank]] and [[Urra Moor]].\n|-\n|[[The White Rose Way]] || {{convert|104|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Yorkshire || [[Leeds]] || [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] || Runs from Leeds to the [[Yorkshire Coast]].\n|-\n|[[Wilberforce Way]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Yorkshire || [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] || [[York]] ||Waymarked route marking the bicentenary of the abolition of the British Transatlantic slave trade in the 1807 Act of Parliament introduced by Hull-born [[William Wilberforce]].\n|-\n|[[Windermere Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cumbria]] || [[Bowness-on-Windermere]] || N/A || Circular route around [[Windermere]] in the [[Lake District]].\n|-\n|[[Witton Weavers Way]] || {{convert|33|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Lancashire || [[Witton Park]] || N/A || Circular route around the [[West Pennine Moors]], [[Blackburn]] and [[Darwen]].\n|-\n|[[Yorkshire Water Way]] || {{convert|104|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || North Yorkshire, West Yorkshire, South Yorkshire ||[[Kettlewell]] || [[Langsett Reservoir]] || Walk connecting over 25 reservoirs maintained by [[Yorkshire Water]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Yorkshire Water Way - LDWA Long Distance Paths |url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Yorkshire+Water+Way |website=www.ldwa.org.uk |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Wales===\n\n*The [[Beacons Way]], an east\u2013west route of 161&nbsp;km (100&nbsp;mi) through the heart of the [[Brecon Beacons National Park]]\n*[[Cambrian Way]], an [[waymarking|unwaymarked]] high level 440&nbsp;km (273&nbsp;mi) route from [[Cardiff]] to [[Conwy]]\n*[[Cistercian Way (Wales)|Cistercian Way]] \u2013 1050&nbsp;km (650&nbsp;mi) long, circumnavigates Wales via its [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] Abbeys\n*[[Clwydian Way]], 243&nbsp;km (151&nbsp;mi), circular from [[Prestatyn]] via [[Llangollen]], [[Corwen]] and [[Denbigh]]\n*[[Dyfi Valley Way]], 172&nbsp;km (107&nbsp;mi) from [[Aberdyfi]] to [[Borth|Ynyslas]]\n*[[Glynd\u0175r's Way]] 206&nbsp;km (128&nbsp;mi) from [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]] to [[Machynlleth]]\n*[[Landsker Borderlands Trail]], a 96&nbsp;km (60&nbsp;mi) route in [[Pembrokeshire]] and [[Carmarthenshire]], centred on [[Whitland]]\n*[[Marches Way]] 320&nbsp;km (200&nbsp;mi) from [[Chester]] to [[Cardiff]] through the [[Welsh Marches]]\n*The [[Maelor Way]], is a key link path, running 38&nbsp;km (24&nbsp;mi) from the [[Offa's Dyke Path]] [[National Trail]] at [[Bronygarth]] to the [[Shropshire Way]], [[Sandstone Trail]], [[Llangollen Canal]], [[South Cheshire Way]], and the [[Marches Way]] all at [[Grindley Brook]] near [[Whitchurch, Shropshire|Whitchurch]]\n*[[Monmouthshire Way]], {{convert|116|mi|order=flip|adj=on}} circular route in [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]].\n* [[Monnow Valley Walk]] 65&nbsp;km (40&nbsp;mi) from [[Monmouth]] to [[Hay-on-Wye]] following the [[River Monnow]]\n* [[North Wales Pilgrims Way]] 215&nbsp;km (133&nbsp;mi) from near [[Holywell, Flintshire|Holywell]] to [[Aberdaron]] or [[Bardsey Island]]\n* [[O Fon i Fynwy|O Fon i Fynw<nowiki/>y]] 585&nbsp;km (364&nbsp;mi) from [[Holyhead]] to [[Chepstow]]\n*[[Rhymney Valley Ridgeway Walk]], 45&nbsp;km (28&nbsp;mi) circular walk around the [[Caerphilly]] basin in [[South Wales]]\n*[[Saint Illtyd's Walk]], 103&nbsp;km (64&nbsp;mi) walk from the [[Carmarthenshire]] coast at [[Pembrey Country Park]] near [[Llanelli]], ending at [[Margam Abbey]] in [[Margam Park]]\n<!-- *[[Saint Tecwyn's Way]], 7\u00a0km (4\u00bd\u00a0mi) walk from [[Llanfihangel-y-traethau]] to Saint Tecwyn's church at [[Llandecwyn]], largely following the [[Wales Coast Path]]. Too Short -->\n*The Snowdonia Slate Trail, an {{convert|83|mi|adj=on}} waymarked route through the slate areas of Snowdonia National Park<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_name=Snowdonia+Slate+Trail |title=Snowdonia Slate Trail |publisher=Long Distance Walkers Association |date= |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Taff Trail]], 109&nbsp;km (68&nbsp;mi) from [[Brecon]] to [[Cardiff]]\n*[[Usk Valley Walk]], 77&nbsp;km (48&nbsp;mi) from [[Caerleon]] to [[Brecon]]\n*[[Valeways Millennium Heritage Trail]], a circular walk of 111&nbsp;km (69&nbsp;mi) in the [[Vale of Glamorgan]]\n* The [[Wales Coast Path]], an 870 miles (1,400&nbsp;km) walking route from [[Chepstow]] in the south to [[Queensferry, Flintshire|Queensferry]] in the north, following the whole of the coastline of Wales. The following sections continue to be marketed as long-distance footpaths in their own right:\n**[[North Wales Path]] 96&nbsp;km (60&nbsp;mi) from [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] to [[Prestatyn]]\n**[[Anglesey Coastal Path]], a circular route of 200&nbsp;km (124&nbsp;mi) around the island of [[Anglesey]]\n**[[Ll\u0177n Coastal Path]] (also known as The Pilgrim Trail), 150&nbsp;km (93&nbsp;mi) between [[Caernarfon]] and [[Porthmadog]] in [[Gwynedd]]\n**[[Ceredigion Coast Path]] \u2013 currently still being developed, so not all [[waymarking|waymarked]] \u2013 101&nbsp;km (63&nbsp;mi) from [[Borth|Ynyslas]] to [[Cardigan, Ceredigion|Cardigan]]\n**[[Pembrokeshire Coast Path]] 300&nbsp;km (186&nbsp;mi) coastal trail from [[Amroth, Pembrokeshire|Amroth]] in the south to [[St. Dogmaels]] in the north\n*[[Wye Valley Walk]], [[Chepstow]] \u2013 [[Plynlimon]] 218&nbsp;km (135&nbsp;mi)<!-- Note: This footpath goes through England as well as Wales -->\n\n===Scotland===\n{{see also|Long-distance footpaths in Scotland}}\n*[[Cape Wrath Trail]], runs around 300&nbsp;km (186&nbsp;mi) from [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] to [[Cape Wrath]]; as the route is [[waymarking|unwaymarked]], different guides to it suggest slightly different routes. See [http://www.capewrathtrail.co.uk here].\n*[[Central Scottish Way]], 251&nbsp;km (156&nbsp;mi) from [[Milngavie]] to [[Byrness]] (just over the border in [[Northumberland]], [[England]])\n*[[Coast to Coast (Scottish path)|Coast to Coast]], 205&nbsp;km (128&nbsp;mi), [[Oban]] to [[St Andrews]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_id=88|title=Coast to Coast (Scotland)|work=Long Distance Walker's Association|accessdate=17 July 2009}} \u2013 includes links to guidebooks</ref> 128 miles, {{ISBN|978-0-9526900-8-5}}\n*[[The East Highland Way]], runs from Fort William to Aviemore\n*[[John o' Groats Trail]], 231&nbsp;km (145&nbsp;mi) from [[Inverness]] to [[John o'Groats]]\n*[[Sir Walter Scott Way]] from [[Moffat]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]] to [[Cockburnspath]], [[Scottish Borders]]\n\n===Northern Ireland===\n*[[Ulster Way]], runs for about 960&nbsp;km (600&nbsp;mi), mainly in [[Northern Ireland]], with some sections in the [[Republic of Ireland]]\n\n===The Macmillan Ways===\n{{See also|Macmillan Ways}}\n\nThe ''Macmillan Ways'' are a set of paths that promotes and raises money for the [[Macmillan Cancer Relief]] charity.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n|[[Macmillan Way]] || {{convert|290|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern England || [[Abbotsbury]] in [[Dorset]] || [[Boston, Lincolnshire]] ||  For the first 30 miles it crosses open [[fen]] then it follows the [[oolitic limestone]] belt. It is the longest of the [[Macmillan Ways]]. \n|-\n|[[Macmillan Way West]] || {{convert|102|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset and Devon || [[Castle Cary]] || [[Barnstaple]] || Follows the [[River Cary]] and then onto the [[Quantock Hills]] and to Exmoor. \n|-\n|[[Cross Britain Way]] || {{convert|280|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England and Wales || [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[Lincolnshire]] || [[Barmouth]], [[Gwynedd]] || The terrain varies from the flat land of [[The Fens]] to the Welsh [[Berwyn Mountains]]. \n|-\n|[[Macmillan Abbotsbury Langport Link]] || {{convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South West England]] || [[Abbotsbury]] || [[Langport]] || Allows walkers to go {{convert|126|mi}} coast-to-coast from Abbotsbury to Barnstaple, using the Macmillan Way West.\n|-\n|[[Macmillan Cross Cotswold Pathway]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cotswolds]] || [[Banbury Cross]] || [[Bath, Somerset]] || Provides links from much of Oxfordshire to the Macmillan Way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Macmillan+Way+-+Cross+Cotswold+Pathway|title=Macmillan Way - Cross Cotswold Pathway|website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cotswold Link]] || {{convert|21|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Gloucestershire]] and Oxfordshire || [[Chipping Campden]] || Banbury Cross || Links to the [[Cotswold Way]] National Trail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Macmillan+Way+-+Cotswold+Link+-+Chipping+Campden+to+Banbury|title=Macmillan Way - Cotswold Link - Chipping Campden to Banbury|website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== European walking routes ==\n\nSeveral [[European long-distance paths|European walking routes]] pass through the United Kingdom. They all use sections of UK long-distance paths.\n*[[European walking route E2|E2]] from [[Stranraer]] to [[Dover]], with an alternative route to [[Harwich]]\n*[[European walking route E8|E8]] from [[Liverpool]] to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n*[[European walking route E9|E9]] from [[Plymouth]] to Dover\n*The [[North Sea Trail]] covers seven countries with [[North Sea]] coastlines.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adventure travel]] for worldwide options\n*[[backpacking (wilderness)|Backpacking]] and [[Ultralight backpacking]]\n*[[Hiking]] and [[Thru-hiking]]\n*[[Hillwalking]]\n*[[Land's End to John o' Groats]]\n*[[List of Conservation topics]]\n*[[List of long-distance trails]]\n*[[Long Distance Walkers Association]]\n*[[Raad ny Foillan]], a long-distance path on the [[Isle of Man]]\n*[[Ramblers' Association]]\n*[[Scrambling]]\n*[[Walking in London]]\n*[[Walking in the United Kingdom]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Trails in the United Kingdom}}\n*[http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/ldp_members_home.php The Long Distance Walkers Association: Long distance paths database]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071126123940/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/info/paths/index.html Ramblers' Association: Paths and routes]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170518003349/http://nationalcoastalpath.co.uk/ Scottish National Coastal Route]\n*[http://www.snh.gov.uk/enjoying-the-outdoors/where-to-go/routes-to-explore/scotlands-great-trails/ Scotland's Great Trails]\n{{Recreational walks in England}}\n\n{{UK Trails}}\n\n[[Category:Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom| 01]]\n[[Category:Lists of hiking trails|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom geography-related lists|Footpaths (long distance)]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom transport-related lists|Footpaths (long distance)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Short description|List of long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom}}\nThere are hundreds of '''[[long-distance footpath]]s in the United Kingdom''' designated in publications from public authorities, [[guidebook]]s and [[OS maps]].<ref name=LD /> They are mainly used for [[hiking]] and [[walking in the United Kingdom|walking]], but some may also be used, in whole or in part, for [[mountain biking ]] and [[horse riding]]. Most are in rural landscapes, in varying terrain, some passing through [[National Parks]] and [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalparks.gov.uk/visiting/outdoor-activities/walking| title= Walking|publisher= National Parks|accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref> There is no formal definition of a long-distance path, though the British [[Long Distance Walkers Association]] defines one as a route \"20 miles [32 km] or more in length and mainly off-road.\"<ref name=LD>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/public/what_is_an_ldp.php|title=What is an LDP? [long-distance footpath]|publisher= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref> They usually follow existing [[Rights of way in the United Kingdom|rights of way]], often over private land, joined together and sometimes [[Trail blazing|waymarked]] to make a named route.<ref name=NA>{{cite journal| url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/9027 | title=Out in the country|publisher=[[Natural England]] | date= 29 November 2007 | accessdate=22 August 2018|pages = 12\u201313}}</ref> Generally, the surface is not specially prepared, with rough ground, uneven surfaces and [[stile]]s, which can cause accessibility issues for people with [[disabilities]].<ref>{{cite journal| url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/9027 | title=Out in the country|publisher=[[Natural England]] | date= 29 November 2007 | accessdate=22 August 2018|page = 10}}</ref> Exceptions to this can be converted [[Rail transport|railways]], canal towpaths and some popular fell walking routes where stone-pitching and slabs have been laid to prevent [[erosion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fixthefells.co.uk/what-we-do/path-repair-techniques/|title=Path Repair Techniques|website=www.fixthefells.co.uk|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Many long-distance footpaths are arranged around a particular theme such as one specific range of hills or a historical or geographical connection.<ref name=NA />\n\n==England and Wales: National Trails==\n{{main|National Trails}}\n[[National Trails]] are a network of long-distance paths in England and Wales (plus a small stretch of the [[Pennine Way]] in Scotland<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/pennine-way/routes|title=The Pennine Way - Route Description & Downloads |publisher=National Trails}}</ref>) funded by Natural England and Natural Resources Wales and maintained by [[local authorities]] under a Trail Partnership.<ref name=NT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/the-trails|title= The National Trails|accessdate=22 August 2018|publisher=National Trails website}}</ref> {{As of|August 2018}}, there are over {{convert|2500|mi|km}} of trails on sixteen routes. The newest trail, the [[England Coast Path]], is not complete though more sections are planned to open over the coming months, with a planned completion date of 2020.{{Update after|2020}}<ref name=NT /> There are 83 million visits to the National Trails each year and over 80,000 people complete a trail.<ref>[https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/ National Trails Website]</ref>\n\n[[File:Ivinghoe Beacon seen from The Ridgeway.jpg|right|thumb|[[Ivinghoe Beacon]] (the eastern trailhead) seen looking north from the Ridgeway]]\n[[File:Black Hill (Peak District).jpg|thumb|right|The paved surface of the Pennine Way on [[Black Hill (Peak District)|Black Hill]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n| [[Cleveland Way]] || {{convert|110|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]] || [[Helmsley]] || [[Filey Brigg]] || Runs around the edge of the [[North York Moors National Park]] in a [[horseshoe]] configuration.\n|-\n| [[Cotswold Way]] || {{convert|102|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cotswolds|The Cotswolds]], Central England || [[Chipping Campden]], [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Somerset]] || Runs along the [[Cotswold Edge]] [[escarpment]] of the Cotswold Hills.\n|-\n| [[England Coast Path]] || {{convert|2,795|mi|km|-2|disp=table|sortable=on}}<sup>\u2020</sup> || England || N/A || N/A || Will cover the entire coast of England and will be the longest managed and [[Trail blazing|waymarked]] coastal path in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path|title=England Coast Path|website=National Trails}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Glynd\u0175r's Way]] || {{convert|135|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Powys]], [[Mid Wales|mid]] [[Wales]] || [[Knighton, Powys|Knighton]] || [[Welshpool]] || Runs in an extended loop.\n|-\n| [[Hadrian's Wall Path]] || {{convert|84|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England: [[Tyne and Wear]], [[Northumberland]], [[Cumbria]] || [[Wallsend]], Tyne and Wear || [[Bowness-on-Solway]], Cumbria || Runs from the east to west coast along the remains of [[Hadrian's Wall]].\n|-\n| [[North Downs Way]] || {{convert|153|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South Eastern England || [[Farnham]], Surrey ||  [[Dover]], Kent || Passes through the [[AONB|areas of outstanding natural beauty (AONB)]] of the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills]]  and [[Kent Downs]].\n|-\n| [[Offa's Dyke Path]] || {{convert|177|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wales\u2013England border]] || [[Sedbury]], [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Prestatyn]], [[Denbighshire]] || Follows close to the border near the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]].\n|-\n| [[Peddars Way]] and [[Norfolk Coast Path]]<sup>\u2021</sup> || {{convert|97|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England in [[Suffolk]] and [[Norfolk]] || [[Knettishall Heath]], [[Knettishall]], Suffolk ||  [[Cromer]], Norfolk || The two paths join at [[Holme-next-the-Sea]].\n|-\n| [[Pembrokeshire Coast Path]] || {{convert|186|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pembrokeshire]], southwest Wales || [[Poppit Sands]], near [[St Dogmaels]] || [[Amroth, Pembrokeshire|Amroth]] || Has a total of {{convert|35,000|ft}} of ascent and descent and lies almost completely within the [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nt.pcnpa.org.uk/website/sitefiles/nt_page.asp?PageID=6&SubPageID=20 |title=Pembrokeshire Coast Path Statistics |publisher=National Trails |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Pennine Bridleway]] || {{convert|205|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pennines]], Northern England || [[Middleton-by-Wirksworth]], [[Derbyshire]] || [[Ravenstonedale]], Cumbria || Runs roughly parallel to the Pennine Way.\n|-\n| [[Pennine Way]] || {{convert|267|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Pennines]], Northern England and Southern [[Scotland]] || [[Edale]], Derbyshire || [[Kirk Yetholm]], [[Scottish Borders]] || Spans the length of the Pennines, according to the [[Ramblers]], \"one of Britain's best known and toughest\" trails.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ramblers' Association |title=Pennine Way National Trail |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/info/paths/pennine.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220133545/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/pennine.html |archivedate=20 February 2006 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Ridgeway]] || {{convert|87|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Berkshire Downs]], Southern England || [[Overton Hill]], near [[Avebury]], [[Wiltshire]] || [[Ivinghoe Beacon]], [[Buckinghamshire]] || [[Ancient trackway]] on a [[chalk]] ridge described as Britain's oldest road.\n|-\n| [[South Downs Way]] || {{convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  [[South Downs]] in Southern England || [[Winchester]], Hampshire || [[Eastbourne]], [[East Sussex]] || Within the [[South Downs National Park]].\n|-\n| [[South West Coast Path]] (South West Way) || {{convert|630|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || England: [[Somerset]], [[Devon]], [[Cornwall]] & [[Dorset]] || [[Minehead]], Somerset || [[Poole Harbour]], Dorset || Originated as a route for the [[Her Majesty's Coastguard|Coastguard]] to walk from lighthouse to lighthouse patrolling for [[smugglers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southwestcoastpath.org.uk/about-coast-path/heritage-walks/|title=Heritage|publisher=South West Coast Path}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thames Path]] || {{convert|184|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern England || [[Kemble, Gloucestershire|Kemble]], Gloucestershire || [[Thames Barrier]], [[Charlton, London|Charlton]]|| Follows the [[River Thames]] from its source to the Thames Barrier in [[London]].\n|-\n| [[Yorkshire Wolds Way]] || {{convert|79|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Yorkshire]], England || [[Hessle]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] || [[Filey]], [[North Yorkshire]] || Runs around the [[Yorkshire Wolds]].\n|}\n<sup>\u2020</sup> {{small|When complete in 2020}}<br />\n<sup>\u2021</sup> {{small|Treated as one path by National Trails}}\n\n==Scotland: Great Trails==\n{{main|Scotland's Great Trails}}\n[[File:Fife Coast path at West Wemyss - geograph.org.uk - 1366601.jpg|thumb|right| [[Fife Coastal Path]] at West Wemyss]]\n[[File:West Highland Way 2005 Coe.jpg|thumb|right|[[Aonach Eagach|The Devil's Staircase]] on the [[West Highland Way]]]]\n[[File:Cliffs from Berwickshire Coastal path - geograph.org.uk - 323939.jpg|thumb|right|Cliffs from the [[Berwickshire Coastal Path]]]]\n[[File:A St Cuthbert's Way marker post - geograph.org.uk - 1387283.jpg|thumb|right|A [[St Cuthbert's Way]] marker post at the edge of the square between Grubbit Law and Wideopen Hill]]\n[[Scotland's Great Trails]] are long-distance \"people-powered\" trails (predominantly hiking trails but including cycling, horse-riding and canoe routes) in Scotland.<ref name=sgt1>{{cite web|title=Scotland's Great Trails: the official guide|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.org.uk/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> [[Scottish Natural Heritage]] maintains the official list of Scotland\u2019s Great Trails and is the custodian of the brand, but responsibility for creating and maintaining each route lies with each [[subdivisions of Scotland|local authority]] through which a route passes, although Scottish Natural Heritage provides some of the finance and publicity.<ref name=sgt2>{{cite web|title=About Scotland\u2019s Great Trails|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/aboutsgts/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> There are 29 routes, offering {{convert|1900|mi|km|sigfig=1}} of trails in total.<ref name=\"sgt2\"/>\n\nEach of the routes is clearly waymarked with a dedicated symbol, and run largely off-road. They range in length from {{convert|24|to|210|mi|km|-1}}, and are intended to be tackled over several days, either as a combination of day trips or as an end-to-end expedition. They are primarily intended for walkers, but may have sections suitable for cyclists and horse-riders.<ref name=sgt-faq>{{cite web|title=FAQs|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/faqs/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-07-05}}</ref> One of the trails, the Great Glen Canoe Trail, is designed for [[canoe]]ists and [[kayak]]ers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Great Glen Canoe Trail|url=http://www.scotlandsgreattrails.com/trail/great-glen-canoe-trail/|publisher=Scotland's Great Trails|accessdate=2018-07-05}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n| [[Annandale Way]] || {{Convert|55|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Solway Coast]], Dumfries and Galloway || [[Moffat]] || [[Annan, Dumfries and Galloway|Annan]] || Follows the valley of the [[River Annan]] from its source in the [[Moffat Hills]] to the sea in the [[Solway Firth]].\n|-\n| [[Arran Coastal Way]] || {{Convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Arran]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route around the coastline of the Isle of Arran.\n|-\n| [[Ayrshire Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Ayrshire]] || Glenapp, [[Ballantrae]] || [[Skelmorlie]], North Ayrshire || Runs alongside the coast and forms part of the [[International Appalachian Trail]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ayrshirecoastalpath.org/|title=Scottish walking at its best!|website=ayrshirecoastalpath.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Berwickshire Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Borders]] and Northern England || [[Cockburnspath]], Scottish Borders || [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], [[Northumberland]] || Coastal path spanning the [[Anglo-Scottish border]].\n|-\n|[[Borders Abbeys Way]] || {{Convert|68|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Borders || N/A || N/A || Circular route in the Borders passing through the ruins of many [[abbeys]]: [[Kelso, Scottish Borders|Kelso]] \u2013 [[Jedburgh]] \u2013 [[Hawick]] \u2013 [[Selkirk, Scottish Borders|Selkirk]] \u2013 [[Melrose, Scottish Borders|Melrose]].\n|-\n|[[Cateran Trail]] || {{Convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Perth and Kinross]] and [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]] || [[Blairgowrie and Rattray]] || N/A || Circular route covering many conditions such as farmland, mountains and forest: [[Blairgowrie and Rattray|Blairgowrie]] \u2013 [[Kirkmichael]] \u2013 [[Spittal of Glenshee]] \u2013 [[Alyth]].\n|-\n|[[Clyde Walkway]] || {{Convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South Lanarkshire]] || [[Glasgow]] || [[New Lanark]] ||  Runs close to the [[River Clyde]] for most of its length.\n|-\n|[[Cowal Way]] || {{convert|57|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Cowal|Cowal Peninsula]], [[Argyll and Bute]] || [[Portavadie]] || [[Inveruglas]] on [[Loch Lomond]] || Connects with the West Highland Way.\n|-\n|[[Cross Borders Drove Road]] || {{Convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Edinburgh]] and the Scottish Borders ||[[Little Vantage]], near Edinburgh || [[Hawick]]|| One of the newest trails based on existing routes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkacrossscotland.co.uk/the-cross-borders-drove-road/|title=The Cross Borders Drove Road|website= Walk Across Scotland}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dava Way]] || {{Convert|24|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Moray]] || [[Grantown-on-Spey]] || [[Forres]] || Follows the route of the former [[Highland Railway]] which closed in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.davaway.org.uk/|title=Walking and cycling along the Dava Way|website=www.davaway.org.uk/|accessdate= 21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Fife Coastal Path]] || {{Convert|117|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Fife]] || [[Kincardine-on-Forth|Kincardine]] || [[Newburgh, Fife|Newburgh]] || When opened it originally ran from [[North Queensferry]] to [[Tayport]], but was later extended.\n|-\n|[[Formartine and Buchan Way]] || {{Convert|53|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Aberdeenshire]] || [[Dyce]], near [[Aberdeen]] || [[Fraserburgh]] and [[Peterhead]] || Follows the track of the former railway line the [[Formartine and Buchan Railway]] which closed in 1970. The path branches into two sections at [[Maud, Aberdeenshire|Maud]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/aberdeenshire/formartine-buchan-way.shtml|title=The Formartine and Buchan Way|accessdate=22 August 2018|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Forth and Clyde Canal Pathway]] || {{Convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Central Belt]] || [[Bowling, West Dunbartonshire]] || [[Fountainbridge]], Edinburgh || Runs between the [[Firth of Forth]] and the [[Firth of Clyde]].\n|-\n|[[Great Glen Canoe Trail]]|| {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Highlands]] || [[Banavie]], near Fort William || [[Clachnaharry]], near [[Inverness]] || Coast-to-coast [[canoe]] trail on man-made canals and locks.\n|-\n|[[Great Glen Way]] || {{Convert|79|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Highlands || [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]] || [[Inverness]] || Follows the [[Great Glen]].\n|-\n|[[Great Trossachs Path]] || {{Convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Trossachs]] || [[Callander]], [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling]] ||  [[Inversnaid]] on the bank of [[Loch Lomond]] || In the [[Loch Lomond and The Trossachs National Park]].\n|-\n|[[John Muir Way]] || {{Convert|134|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Central Belt || [[Helensburgh]], Argyll and Bute || [[Dunbar]], [[East Lothian]] || Named in honour of the Scottish [[conservation movement|conservationist]] [[John Muir]], who was born in Dunbar in 1838 and became a founder of the [[United States]] [[National Park Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/john-muir-way.shtml|title=The John Muir Way|website=walkhighlands.co.uk|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Kintyre Way]] || {{Convert|100|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Argyllshire]]|| [[Tarbert, Argyll and Bute|Tarbert]] || [[Machrihanish]] || On the [[Kintyre]] peninsula.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kintyreway.com/routes/|title=Route information and maps|website=Kintyre Way}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Moray Coast Trail]] || {{Convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Moray]] || [[Forres]] || [[Cullen, Moray|Cullen]]|| Part of the [[North Sea Trail]].\n|-\n|[[Mull of Galloway Trail]] || {{Convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dumfries and Galloway]] and [[South Ayrshire]]|| [[Mull of Galloway]] || Glenapp, [[Ballantrae]] || Created and maintained by the ''Rotary Club of Stranraer''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mullofgallowaytrail.co.uk/|title=Walk the beautiful south-west corner of Scotland|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[River Ayr Way]] || {{Convert|44|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  Southern Scotland || [[Glenbuck]], [[East Ayrshire]] || [[Ayr]], South Ayrshire || Mostly follows the [[River Ayr]].\n|-\n|[[Rob Roy Way]] || {{Convert|92|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Perthshire]] and [[Stirlingshire]] || [[Drymen]], Stirling || [[Pitlochry]], Perth and Kinross || Takes its name from [[Robert Roy MacGregor|Rob Roy MacGregor]], a Scottish [[folk hero]] and [[outlaw]] of the early 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/rob-roy-way.shtml|title=The Rob Roy Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk|accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Romans and Reivers Route]] || {{Convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Southern Uplands]] || [[Ae, Scotland|Ae]] || [[Hawick]] || Mostly follows former [[Roman roads]].\n|-\n|[[St Cuthbert's Way]] || {{Convert|62|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Scottish Borders and Northern England|| [[Melrose, Scottish Borders|Melrose]], Scottish Borders || [[Lindisfarne]], [[Northumberland]] || Named after [[Cuthbert of Lindisfarne|Cuthbert]], a 7th-century [[saint]], a native of the Borders who spent his life in the service of the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/borders/st-cuthberts-way.shtml|title=St Cuthbert's Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Southern Upland Way]] || {{Convert|212|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern Uplands || [[Portpatrick]] || [[Cockburnspath]], [[Berwickshire]] ||Coast-to-coast walk from east to west.\n|-\n|[[Speyside Way]] || {{Convert|80|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Northern Scotland|| [[Aviemore]] || [[Buckie]], Moray || Follows the [[River Spey]]  through some of [[Banffshire]], [[County of Moray|Morayshire]] and [[Inverness-shire]].\n|-\n|[[Three Lochs Way]] || {{Convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Highland Boundary Fault]] to the Southern Highlands || [[Balloch, West Dunbartonshire|Balloch]], [[West Dunbartonshire]] || [[Inveruglas]], [[Argyll and Bute]] || For much of the way it passes through the [[Loch Lomond and The Trossachs National Park]].\n|-\n|[[West Highland Way]] || {{Convert|96|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Scottish Lowlands]] to the [[Scottish Highlands]] || [[Milngavie]], near Glasgow || [[Fort William, Highland|Fort William]], Highlands || Scotland's first and most popular long-distance walking route.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/west-highland-way.shtml|title= Scotland's Great Trails - The West Highland Way|website=www.walkhighlands.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[West Island Way]] || {{Convert|30|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Bute]] ||[[Kilchattan Bay]] || [[Port Bannatyne]] || The first waymarked long-distance route on a Scottish island.<ref>[http://www.westislandway.co.uk/ West Island Way]</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other UK long-distance paths==\nThose included here meet the definition of a [[long-distance path]] as being around {{convert|50|km|0|abbr=in}} or more, particularly that they will take more than one day's walking to complete. Some shorter paths linking between major walks (e.g. Maelor Way) are also included.\n\n===Southern England===\n<!--See  Macmillan Ways Section for routes-->\n<!--Abbot's Way, Dartmoor removed as not long enough to class as LDP-->\n<!--Beacon Way removed as not long enough to class as LDP-->\n<!--Clarendon Way removed as not long enough to meet definition of LDP-->\n<!--*[[Pilgrims' Trail]], 45&nbsp;km (28&nbsp;mi) from [[Winchester]] to [[Portsmouth]] Included under Hampshire-->\n<!-- *[[Saints' Way]], [[Padstow]] - [[Fowey]] 42&nbsp;km (26&nbsp;mi) ([[Cornwall]]) Too short -->\n<!-- *[[Two Castles Trail]], {{convert|39|km|abbr=in}} from [[Okehampton]] to [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]] Too Short -->\n[[File:The 1066 Country Walk - geograph.org.uk - 1576650.jpg|thumb|right| The 1066 Country Walk near [[Battle, East Sussex|Battle]]]]\n[[File:Monarch's Way - geograph.org.uk - 752202.jpg|thumb|right| [[Monarch's Way]] looking back at the outskirts of [[Wolverhampton]]]]\n[[File:West Deane Way - geograph.org.uk - 1518266.jpg|thumb|right| Meadows on the [[West Deane Way]]]]\n[[File:All Saints Church, West Camel - geograph.org.uk - 289126.jpg|thumb|right| [[Church of All Saints, West Camel]], viewed from the [[Leland Trail]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Name\n! colspan=2 | Length\n! rowspan=2 | Region\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint one\n! rowspan=2 | Endpoint two\n! rowspan=2 | Description\n|-\n! mi\n! km\n|-\n|[[1066 Country Walk]] || {{convert|31|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[East Sussex]] || [[Pevensey Castle]] near [[Pevensey]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Commemorates the year 1066 and the [[Battle of Hastings]].\n|-\n|[[Avon Valley Path]] || {{convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]], [[Hampshire]] and [[Dorset]] || [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]] || [[Salisbury]] || Takes its name from the [[River Avon, Hampshire|River Avon]] and passes through the western edge of the [[New Forest]].\n|-\n| [[Basingstoke Canal| Basingstoke Canal Towpath Trail]] || {{convert|33|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and [[Surrey]] || Penny Bridge, [[Up Nately]], [[Basingstoke]] || [[Woodham, Surrey|Woodham]] || Follows the path of the 200-year-old Basingstoke Canal.\n|-\n|[[Bournemouth Coast Path]] || {{convert|20|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dorset]] and Hampshire || [[Sandbanks]] || [[Milford on Sea]] || Coastal path connecting the [[South West Coast Path]] (via the Sandbanks Ferry) to the [[Solent Way]].\n|-\n|[[Capital Ring]] || {{convert|75|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[London]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route through inner London, crossing the [[Thames]] at [[Richmond, London|Richmond]] and [[Woolwich]].\n|-\n|[[Celtic Way]] || {{convert|725|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wales]] and Southwest England || [[Strumble Head]], [[Pembrokeshire]] || [[St Michael's Mount]], [[Cornwall]] || Visits more than 100 pre-historic sites including [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Celtic+Way|title=Celtic Way|publisher= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Channel to Channel Path]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South West Peninsula]] || [[Seaton, Devon]] || [[Watchet]], Somerset || Connects the [[English Channel]] with the [[Bristol Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Channel+to+Channel+(Devon+-+Somerset)|title=Channel to Channel Path| website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[Chiltern Way]] || {{convert|134|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Bedfordshire]], [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Hertfordshire]], [[Luton]] and [[Oxfordshire]] || [[Hemel Hempstead railway station]] || N/A || Circular route,  originally a {{convert|125|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Millennium Commission|Millennium Project]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Chiltern+Way|title=Chiltern Way|publisher=Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Coleridge Way]] || {{convert|51|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Somerset]] and [[Devon]] || [[Nether Stowey]] || [[Lynmouth]] || Starts in the [[Quantock Hills]] later moving on to the [[Brendon Hills]], within [[Exmoor National Park]].\n|-\n|[[Dartmoor Way]] || {{convert|95|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Dartmoor]] || N/A || N/A || In the Dartmoor National Park in southern [[Devon]].\n|-\n|[[Devonshire Heartland Way]] || {{convert|43|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon || [[Okehampton]] || [[Stoke Canon]], [[Exeter]] || West-to-east across Devon, starting in Dartmoor near the Exe Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_id=8707|title=Devonshire Heartland Way|website= LDWA}} Retrieved 2012</ref>\n|-\n|[[Downs Link]] || {{convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Surrey]] and [[West Sussex]] || [[St. Martha's Hill]] near [[Guildford]] || [[Shoreham-by-Sea]] || Heads from the North Downs Way onto the South Downs Way at [[Steyning]].\n|-\n|[[East Devon Way]] || {{convert|38|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West England || [[Exmouth, Devon|Exmouth]], [[East Devon]] || [[Lyme Regis]], West [[Dorset]] || Runs inland but links with the [[South West Coast Path]] at both ends.\n|-\n|[[Essex Way]] || {{convert|81|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Essex]] || [[Epping, Essex|Epping]] || [[Harwich]] || Crosses [[Dedham Vale]] and [[John Constable|Constable]] country to finish at the [[River Stour, Suffolk|Stour estuary]].\n|-\n|[[Exe Valley Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon and Somerset || [[River Exe]] estuary || [[Exford, Somerset|Exford]] in [[Exmoor National Park]]|| Follows the valley of the [[River Exe]] from its source to the coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exploredevon.info/activities/walk/long-walks/exe-valley-way/|title= Exe Valley Way| website= Explore Devon}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Gordano Round]] || {{convert|27|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[North Somerset]] || Roath Road, [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]] || N/A || Figure of eight around the [[Gordano Valley]] via [[Clevedon]] and [[Abbots Leigh]].\n|-\n|[[Great Stones Way]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]] || [[Coate Water Country Park]], [[Swindon]] || [[Salisbury Cathedral]]|| From [[Barbury Castle]] to [[Old Sarum]] with optional detours to [[Avebury]] and [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Great+Stones+Way|title=Great Stones Way|website= Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Greater Ridgeway]] || {{convert|362|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South and Central England || [[Lyme Regis]], [[Dorset]] on the [[English Channel]] || [[Hunstanton]] on [[The Wash]] || Follows the [[Wessex Ridgeway]], [[The Ridgeway]] National Trail, the [[Icknield Way Path]] and the [[Peddars Way]] National Trail.\n|-\n|[[Greensand Way]] || {{convert|108|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Home counties]] || [[Haslemere]], Surrey || [[Hamstreet]], [[Kent]] || Follows the [[Greensand Ridge]] along the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills]] and Chart Hills.\n|-\n|[[Pilgrims' Trail|Hampshire Millennium Pilgrims Trail]] || {{convert|29|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] || [[Winchester]] || [[Portsmouth]] || Part of the historical Pilgrims' Trail, a 155-mile long-distance footpath connecting [[Winchester Cathedral]] to [[Mont Saint-Michel]] in [[Normandy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/countryside/walking/pilgrimstrail|title=Pilgrim's Trail|website=Hampshire County Council|accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hardy Way]] || {{convert|220|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[West Country]] || [[Hardy's Cottage]], [[Higher Bockhampton]] || [[Stinsford]], Dorset || Almost circular, the endpoints being a mile apart, and named after the writer [[Thomas Hardy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Hardy+Way|title=Hardy Way|website=Long Distance Walkers Association}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[High Weald Landscape Trail]] || {{convert|90|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[West Sussex]], [[East Sussex]], [[Kent]] || [[Horsham]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Passes through the landscapes of the [[High Weald Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]. \n|-\n|[[Isle of Wight Coastal Path]] || {{convert|70|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Isle of Wight]] || [[Ryde]] || N/A || Circular coastal route mainly following public footpaths.\n|-\n|[[Itchen Way]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] || [[Hinton Ampner]] near [[New Alresford|Alresford]] || [[Sholing]] || Follows the [[River Itchen, Hampshire|River Itchen]] from its source.\n|-\n|[[Jubilee Trail (footpath)|Jubilee Trail]] || {{convert|88|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset || [[Forde Abbey]] || [[Bokerley Dyke]] || Created to celebrate [[The Ramblers|The Ramblers' Association]]'s Diamond Jubilee and passes through many historical sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jubilee Trail (Dorset)|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Jubilee+Trail+(Dorset)|publisher=LDWA|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[King's Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Winchester]] || [[Portchester]] ||  Created by the Ramblers' Association as a memorial to the late Allan King (who formed many local groups in Hampshire).\n|-\n|[[Land's End Trail]] || {{convert|303|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West Peninsula || [[Land's End]], Cornwall || [[Avebury]], [[Wiltshire]] || Links Land's End with many of England's central long-distance trails.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_id=260|title=Land's End Trail|website= LDWA webpage}} Retrieved 26 February 2012</ref>\n|-\n|[[Leland Trail]] || {{convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || [[King Alfred's Tower]], [[Brewham]] || [[Ham Hill, Somerset|Ham Hill]] || Named after the [[antiquary]] and poet [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Leland+Trail|title=Leland Trail\n|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Liberty Trail]] || {{convert|28|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset and [[Dorset]] || [[Ham Hill, Somerset|Ham Hill]] || [[Lyme Regis]] || Based on the route rebels travelled to join the [[Monmouth Rebellion]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.visitsouthsomerset.com/index.jsp?articleid=12643 |title=Liberty Trail |access-date=25 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025190810/http://www.visitsouthsomerset.com/index.jsp?articleid=12643 |archive-date=25 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Limestone Link]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[South West England]] || [[Mendip Hills]], Somerset || [[Cold Aston]], [[Gloucestershire]] || Connects with the [[Mendip Way]] and the [[Cotswold Way]].\n|-\n|[[London Outer Orbital Path]] (''The LOOP'') || {{convert|150|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || London || [[Erith]] || [[Rainham, London|Rainham]] || Circular route around the edge of [[Outer London]].\n|-\n|[[Mendip Way]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || [[Uphill]] near [[Weston-super-Mare]] || [[Frome]] || On the [[Mendip Hills]], giving views over the [[Somerset Levels]].\n|-\n|[[Monarch's Way]] || {{convert|615|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Southern England || [[Worcester]] || [[Shoreham-by-Sea]], West Sussex || Approximates the escape route taken by [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]] in 1651 after being defeated in the [[Battle of Worcester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Monarch%27s+Way|title=Monarch's Way|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[New Lipchis Way]] || {{convert|40|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Hampshire]] and [[West Sussex]] || [[Liphook]] || [[West Wittering]] || Passes through [[Midhurst]] and [[Chichester]] crossing the [[Western Weald]] and [[South Downs]].\n|-\n|[[Orange Way]] || {{convert|350|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} ||  [[Devon]], [[Dorset]], [[Hampshire]], [[Berkshire]] and [[Buckinghamshire]] || [[Brixham]], Devon || London || Follows the march in 1688 of [[Prince William of Orange]] and his army from Brixham to London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange Way|url=http://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?menu_type=S&path_name=Orange+Way|work=LDWA website|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oxford Canal Walk]] || {{convert|82|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Oxfordshire]], [[Warwickshire]] and the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] || [[Oxford]] || [[Coventry]] || Follows the [[towpath]] of the [[Oxford Canal]].<ref>[http://www.waterscape.com/things-to-do/walking/routes/230/oxford-canal-walk  Oxford Canal Walk]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oxford Green Belt Way]] || {{convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Oxfordshire || N/A || N/A || Circular route through the [[Oxford Green Belt]].\n|-\n|[[Oxfordshire Way]] || {{convert|62|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Oxfordshire and [[Gloucestershire]] || [[Bourton-on-the-Water]] || [[Henley-on-Thames]] || Passes from the [[Cotswolds]] to the [[Chiltern Hills]].\n|-\n|[[Pilgrims' Way]] || {{convert|120|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South Eastern England || [[Winchester, Hampshire|Winchester]] || Shrine of [[Thomas Becket]], [[Canterbury]]|| Historical route taken by [[pilgrims]] to and from the shrine of Thomas Becket. An ancient trail of which perhaps two-thirds is still identifiable, much of it now incorporated into the [[North Downs Way]] National Trail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Pilgrims+Way|title=Pilgrims Way|website=LDWA}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Quantock Greenway]] || {{convert|37|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Somerset || N/A || N/A || A figure-of-eight centred on [[Triscombe]] in the [[Quantock Hills]].\n|-\n|[[River Parrett Trail]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset & Somerset || Chedington || [[Bridgwater Bay]], [[Bristol Channel]] || Follows the [[River Parrett]] to the coast.\n|-\n|[[Royal Military Canal Path]] || {{convert|27|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent and East Sussex || [[Seabrook, Kent|Seabrook]] || [[Pett Level]] || Follows the [[Royal Military Canal]] and touches the northern edge of [[Romney Marsh]].\n|-\n|[[Samaritans Way South West]] || {{convert|103|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South West England || [[Clifton Suspension Bridge]] || [[Lynmouth]] || Opened by the Ramblers and the [[Samaritans (charity)|Samaritans]] in part to help local farmers. Only the section from [[Bristol]] to [[Goathurst]] is [[waymarking|waymarked]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/samaritanssouthwest.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807174810/http://www.ramblers.org.uk/INFO/paths/samaritanssouthwest.html |archivedate=7 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }},</ref>\n|-\n|[[The Sarum Way|Sarum Way]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Wiltshire]] || N/A || N/A || Circular route around the city of [[Salisbury]], only partly waymarked.\n|-\n|[[Saxon Shore Way]] || {{convert|163|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || South East England ||  [[Gravesend]], Kent || [[Hastings]], East Sussex, || Traces the shoreline as it was in [[Roman Britain|Roman]] times and visits many historical sites of the period.<ref>[https://www.visitkent.co.uk/saxon-shore-way/ Saxon Shore Way] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822050051/https://www.visitkent.co.uk/saxon-shore-way/ |date=22 August 2018 }}, Visit Kent</ref>\n|-\n|[[Serpent Trail]] || {{convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire, Surrey and West Sussex || [[Haslemere]] || [[Petersfield]] || Designed to join up many of the [[heathland]] areas in the western [[Weald]].\n|-\n|[[Severn Way]] || {{convert|210|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Mid Wales]] and Western England || [[Plynlimon]], the [[Cambrian Mountains]] || [[Bristol]] || Follows the course of the [[River Severn]] from its source to the [[Severn Estuary]].\n|-\n|[[Shipwrights Way]] || {{convert|50|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Alice Holt Forest]] || [[Portsmouth]] || Traces the route that might have been taken by timber from forest to [[shipyards]] for the construction of [[warships]].<ref>[https://www.hants.gov.uk/thingstodo/countryside/walking/shipwrightsway Shipwrights Way], [[Hampshire County Council]]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Solent Way]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire || [[Milford on Sea]] || [[Emsworth]] || Follows the coast of the [[Solent]].\n|-\n|[[Stour Valley Walk]] || {{convert|52|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent || [[Pegwell Bay]] || [[Lenham]] ||  Follows the [[River Stour, Kent|River Stour]], through the Low [[Weald]] and [[Kent Downs]], from its source to its estuary.\n|-\n|[[Stour Valley Way]]  || {{convert|64|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Dorset and Wiltshire || [[Stourton with Gasper]] || [[Hengistbury Head]] || Follows the  River Stour as it winds through the Dorset countryside.\n|-\n|[[St. Swithun's Way]] || {{convert|34|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and Surrey || [[Winchester Cathedral]] || [[Farnham]] || Named after [[Swithun]], a 9th-century [[Bishop of Winchester]], and roughly follows a short stretch of the [[Pilgrims' Way]].\n|-\n|[[Sussex Border Path]] || {{convert|138|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || West & East Sussex || [[Thorney Island (West Sussex)|Thorney Island]] || [[Rye, East Sussex|Rye]] || Follows the Sussex border with Hampshire, Surrey and Kent.\n|-\n|[[Sussex Ouse Valley Way]] || {{convert|42|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || West & East Sussex || [[Lower Beeding]] || [[Seaford, East Sussex|Seaford]] || Follows the [[River Ouse, Sussex|River Ouse]] from its source to the [[English Channel]].\n|-\n|[[Tarka Trail]] || {{convert|180|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Devon]] || [[Barnstaple]] || N/A || Two separate circular routes based on the fictional route taken by [[Tarka the Otter]] in the book of the same name.\n|-\n|[[Test Way]] || {{convert|49|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Berkshire]] and [[Hampshire]] || [[Walbury Hill]] || [[Totton and Eling]] || Passes through the towns of [[Romsey]] and [[Totton]] and starts in the [[Test Valley]].\n|-\n|[[Thames Down Link]] || {{convert|15|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || London and Surrey || [[Kingston Bridge, London|Kingston Bridge]] || [[Box Hill & Westhumble railway station|Box Hill Station]] || Links the [[Thames Path]] and the [[North Downs Way]].\n|-\n|[[Three Castles Path]] || {{convert|60|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Hampshire and Berkshire || [[Winchester Castle]] || [[Windsor Castle]] || As well as Winchester Castle and Windsor Castle, passes through [[Odiham Castle]]; unwaymarked.\n|-\n|[[Two Moors Way]] || {{convert|102|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon & Somerset || [[Ivybridge]], [[Dartmoor National Park]] || [[Lynmouth]], [[North Devon Coast]] || Across Dartmoor over exposed moorland.\n|-\n|[[Vanguard Way]] || {{convert|66|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Surrey, Kent and East Sussex || [[East Croydon]] || [[Newhaven, East Sussex|Newhaven]] || Connects Central London with the [[Wandle Trail]] along the [[River Wandle]] from [[Croydon]].\n|-\n|[[Wayfarers Walk]] || {{convert|70|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Berkshire and Hampshire || [[Walbury Hill]] || [[Emsworth]] || Approximates an ancient route that might have been used by [[Droving|drovers]] taking cattle to market.\n|-\n|[[Wealdway]] || {{convert|83|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Kent and East Sussex || [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]] || [[Eastbourne]] || Connects the [[Thames Estuary]] with the English Channel and also traverses the [[Ashdown Forest]].\n|-\n|[[Wessex Ridgeway]] || {{convert|136|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Wiltshire and Dorset || [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]] || [[Lyme Regis]] || One of the four long-distance footpaths referred to as the [[Greater Ridgeway]].\n|-\n|[[West Deane Way]] || {{convert|45|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || [[Taunton Deane]] area of [[Somerset]] || [[Taunton]] || N/A || Circular walk in the Vale of Taunton Deane.\n|-\n|[[West Devon Way]] || {{convert|36|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Devon || [[Okehampton]] || [[Radford, Plymstock|Radford Castle]], Hooe Lake, [[Plymouth]] || Links with the [[Tamar Valley Discovery Trail]] and the [[Two Castles Trail]] to form the 'West Devon Triangle', a 90-mile circuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=West+Devon+Way|title=West Devon Way|publisher=The Long Distance Walkers Association|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Wey South Path]] || {{convert|32|mi|km|0|disp=table|sortable=on}} || Surrey and West Sussex || [[Guildford]] || [[Houghton, West Sussex|Houghton Bridge]] || Follows the banks of the [[River Wey]] and the [[Wey and Arun Canal]].\n|}\n\n===Thames to Mersey===\n\n<!--Cross Cotswold Pathway \u2013 see [[Macmillan Ways]] below -->\n<!--Colne Valley Path removed as not long enough to meet definition of LDP-->\n<!-- Grafton Way, Northants, removed as too short at 13miles/21k -->\n<!-- *[[Knightley Way]], [[Northamptonshire]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Knightley Way|url=https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Knigh