eth Centuries''. {{ISBN|0-312-00524-5}}.\n* [[Bhaskar Sunkara]] (editor), ''The ABCs of Socialism.'' Verso, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-78478-726-4}}.\n* Katherine Verdery, ''What Was Socialism, What Comes Next'', Princeton. 1996. {{ISBN|0-691-01132-X}}.\n* {{cite web|last=Webb|first=Sidney|url=https://sourcebooks.fordham.edu/mod/1889webb.asp|title=The Basis of Socialism \u2013 Historic|year=1889|publisher=Library of Economics and Liberty|authorlink=Sidney Webb, 1st Baron Passfield}}\n* [[James Weinstein (author)|James Weinstein]], ''Long Detour: The History and Future of the American Left'', [https://web.archive.org/web/20040803131902/http://www.westviewpress.com/about.html Westview Press], 2003, hardcover, 272 pages. {{ISBN|0-8133-4104-3}}.\n* Peter Wilberg, [http://www.newgnosis.co.uk/deep.html ''Deep Socialism: A New Manifesto of Marxist Ethics and Economics''], 2003. {{ISBN|1-904519-02-4}}.\n* [[Edmund Wilson]], ''To the Finland Station: A Study in the Writing and Acting of History'', Garden City, NY: Doubleday, 1940. {{LCCN|40034338}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.britannica.com/topic/socialism Socialism] \u2014 entry at ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''   \n* {{curlie|Society/Politics/Socialism/|Socialism}}\n* {{IEP|socialis/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120208125248/http://repository.library.georgetown.edu/handle/10822/552531 Cuban Socialism] from the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160115205405/https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/handle/10822/552494 Dean Peter Krogh Foreign Affairs Digital Archives].\n* {{cite EB1922|last=Cole|first=G. D. H.|authorlink=G. D. H. Cole|wstitle=Socialism|short=x}}\n* {{cite NIE|last=Ely|first=Richard T.|authorlink=Richard T. Ely|last2=Adams|first2=Thomas Sewall|author2link=Thomas Sewall Adams|wstitle=Socialism|short=x}}\n\n{{socialism}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{anti-war}}\n{{aspects of capitalism}}\n{{political ideologies}}\n{{social and political philosophy}}\n{{socialism by state}}\n{{Soviet Union topics}}\n{{Western culture}}\n}}\n{{subject bar|portal1=Socialism|portal2=Society|wikt=yes|commons=yes|commons-search=Category:Socialism|n=yes|n-search=yes|q=yes|s=yes|s-search=Portal:Socialism|b=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q7272}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Socialism| ]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalism]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascism]]\n[[Category:Economic ideologies]]\n[[Category:Economic systems]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics| ]]\n[[Category:Political ideologies]]\n[[Category:Political movements]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socialism"}
{"title_page": "Marika Makaroff", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n| name               = Marika Makaroff\n| image              = GutsyAnimations MarikaMakaroff.jpg\n| alt                = Marika Makaroff\n| birth_name         = Katja Marika Makaroff\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1973|06|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Helsinki, Finland]]\n| residence          = [[Porvoo, Finland]]\n| occupation         = CEO, Creative Director, Executive Producer\n| years_active       = 1998 - present\n| known              = Founder of Gutsy, Creative director of Moominvalley\n| home_town          = [[Vantaa, Finland]]\n| title              = CEO of Gutsy Animations\n| children           = 3\n| relatives          = [[Mia Makaroff]] (sister)\n| website            = www.gutsy.fi\n}}\n'''Katja Marika Makaroff''' (b. 5. June 1973, Helsinki) is an awarded content creator and Creative Director from Finland. She is the CEO and founder of Gutsy Animations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutsy.fi|title=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|website=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> Marika has worked over 20 years in media, mainly in executive roles. She was the creative director in Fremantle Media and Filmlance International and the CEO in Fremantle Media Finland and Friday TV.\n\nShe has created multiple entertainment formats and produced Finnish versions of many popular TV shows, such as ''The Apprentice, Dragons Den, Idols, Top Model and X Factor''. She has also produced drama and sold content to over 70 countries. Marika won the prestigious Silver one award for branded content in 2011 for her format ''Buy this''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mtv.fi/viihde/ohjelmat/brandarit/uutiset/artikkeli/suomalainen-tv-sarja-niittaa-mainetta-palkittiin-new-yorkissa/5108036|title=Suomalainen tv-sarja niitt\u00e4\u00e4 mainetta  \u2013 palkittiin New Yorkissa|work=mtv.fi|access-date=2017-06-22|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kauppalehti.fi/uutiset/mainoskilpailun-paapalkinto-suomeen/fUdSjAbZ|title=https://www.kauppalehti.fi/uutiset/mainoskilpailun-paapalkinto-suomeen/fUdSjAbZ|website=www.kauppalehti.fi|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref>\n\nMarika is currently working as the executive producer and creative director of the awarded TV-series ''[[Moominvalley (TV series)|Moominvalley]]'', that premiered in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutsy.fi/moomin|title=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|website=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|access-date=2017-06-27}}</ref> The series' first episode was the most watched program on Finnish national broadcaster [[Yle]]'s streaming service, Yle Areena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2020/01/21/useita-ylen-tv-ohjelmia-miljoonakastiin-vuonna-2019-muumilaakson-avausjakso|title=Useita Ylen tv-ohjelmia miljoonakastiin vuonna 2019 \u2013 Muumilaakson avausjakso ker\u00e4si reilusti yli 2,1 miljoonaa katsojaa|website=yle.fi|language=fi-FI|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> She is the CEO of '''Gutsy Animations''', which was awarded the \u2018National Winner\u2019 in the 2019 European Business Awards, one of the world's largest business competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessawardseurope.com/|title=The European Business Awards|website=www.businessawardseurope.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMarika became known for there work as a journalist in both television and radio. She worked series such as ''[[Jyrki (TV show)|Jyrki]], Wild bunch'' and ''Under construction Finland''. In 2003 she led the series ''Makaroff & Modig''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vintti.yle.fi/yle.fi/makaroffmodig/makaroff.html|title={{!}}YLE{{!}} TV1 :: Makaroff & Modig {{!}} yle.fi {{!}} Arkistoitu|website=vintti.yle.fi|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref>'','' a political talk show she hosted together with journalist [[Silvia Modig]]. In 2005 Marika became the CEO of [[FremantleMedia|Fremantle Media Finland]]. In 2011 she became the Creative director of the company, overseeing all creative development in the Nordics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://realscreen.com/2011/03/30/fremantlemedia-finland-names-makaroff-creative-director/|title=FremantleMedia Finland names Makaroff creative director|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> In 2014 she moved to Stockholm to become the CEO of [[Friday TV]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fridaytv.se/news/|title=News|website=www.fridaytv.se|language=en|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2014/04/ex-fremantlemedia-finland-boss-joins-friday/256722/|title=Ex-FremantleMedia Finland boss joins Friday - TBI Vision|date=2014-04-04|work=TBI Vision|access-date=2017-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015 she became the creative director of [[Filmlance]] international, that is known for creating original format of the TV-series [[The Bridge (2011 TV series)|The Bridge]].\n\nIn 2016 Makaroff launched the production company Gutsy together with co-founder Aram Aflatuni. Gutsy aims to create global and high quality content, that is above all meaningful.\n\nMarika is currently working as the creative director and executive producer in an animated TV-series ''[[Moominvalley]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Moomin (TV Series 2019\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6921882/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_1|accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref> The series is based on the beloved [[Moomin]] books and comics by the Finnish author and illustrator [[Tove Jansson]]. The series, directed by Oscar winner [[Steve Box]] (2006 ''Best Animation feature'' [[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit|''Wallace and Gromit: Curse of the were-rabbit'']])\n\n''Moominvalley'' premiered in spring 2019. The series has been extremely successful in its reviews and ratings worldwide. The first episode of ''Moominvalley'' was viewed by 600,000 viewers when it premiered in Finland's Yle TV2 in February 2019. It also became the most watched television series episode of all time in Yle's streaming service, Yle Areena, bringing the total viewership of the first episode in Finland to over two million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2020/01/21/useita-ylen-tv-ohjelmia-miljoonakastiin-vuonna-2019-muumilaakson-avausjakso|title=Useita Ylen tv-ohjelmia miljoonakastiin vuonna 2019 \u2013 Muumilaakson avausjakso ker\u00e4si reilusti yli 2,1 miljoonaa katsojaa|website=yle.fi|language=fi-FI|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Moominvalley was awarded the ''Best Animated Kid's Programme'' at TBI's Content Innovation Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/10/13/endemol-shine-kew-sky-among-content-innovation-award-winners/|title=Endemol Shine, Kew, Sky among Content Innovation Award winners|date=2019-10-13|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\u00a0The series also won a ''Golden Venla'' award for 2019 Best Children's Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kultainenvenla.fi/arkisto/voittajat-2019/|title=Voittajat 2019|website=Kultainen Venla|language=fi|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> The series has been sold to over 25 territories worldwide.\n\nAlongside ''Moominvalley'', Gutsy Animations is in development with various other productions.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makaroff, Marika}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n| name               = Marika Makaroff\n| image              = GutsyAnimations MarikaMakaroff.jpg\n| alt                = Marika Makaroff\n| birth_name         = Katja Marika Makaroff\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1973|06|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Helsinki, Finland]]\n| residence          = [[Porvoo, Finland]]\n| occupation         = CEO, Creative Director, Executive Producer\n| years_active       = 1998 - present\n| known              = Founder of Gutsy, Creative director of Moominvalley\n| home_town          = [[Vantaa, Finland]]\n| title              = CEO of Gutsy Animations\n| children           = 3\n| relatives          = [[Mia Makaroff]] (sister)\n| website            = www.gutsy.fi\n}}\n'''Katja Marika Makaroff''' (b. 5. June 1973, Helsinki) is an awarded content creator and Creative Director from Finland. She is the CEO and founder of Gutsy Animations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutsy.fi|title=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|website=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> Marika has worked over 20 years in media, mainly in executive roles. She was the creative director in Fremantle Media and Filmlance International and the CEO in Fremantle Media Finland and Friday TV. \n\nShe has created multiple entertainment formats and produced Finnish versions of many popular TV shows, such as ''The Apprentice, Dragons Den, Idols, Top Model and X Factor''. She has also produced drama and sold content to over 70 countries. Marika won the prestigious Silver one award for branded content in 2011 for her format ''Buy this''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mtv.fi/viihde/ohjelmat/brandarit/uutiset/artikkeli/suomalainen-tv-sarja-niittaa-mainetta-palkittiin-new-yorkissa/5108036|title=Suomalainen tv-sarja niitt\u00e4\u00e4 mainetta  \u2013 palkittiin New Yorkissa|work=mtv.fi|access-date=2017-06-22|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kauppalehti.fi/uutiset/mainoskilpailun-paapalkinto-suomeen/fUdSjAbZ|title=https://www.kauppalehti.fi/uutiset/mainoskilpailun-paapalkinto-suomeen/fUdSjAbZ|website=www.kauppalehti.fi|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> \n\nMarika is currently working as the executive producer and creative director of the awarded TV-series ''[[Moominvalley (TV series)|Moominvalley]]'', that premiered in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gutsy.fi/moomin|title=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|website=Gutsy Media {{!}} Creating meaningful content for global audiences|access-date=2017-06-27}}</ref> The series' first episode was the most watched program on Finnish national broadcaster [[Yle]]'s streaming service, Yle Areena. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2020/01/21/useita-ylen-tv-ohjelmia-miljoonakastiin-vuonna-2019-muumilaakson-avausjakso|title=Useita Ylen tv-ohjelmia miljoonakastiin vuonna 2019 \u2013 Muumilaakson avausjakso ker\u00e4si reilusti yli 2,1 miljoonaa katsojaa|website=yle.fi|language=fi-FI|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> She is the CEO of '''Gutsy Animations''', which was awarded the \u2018National Winner\u2019 in the 2019 European Business Awards, one of the world\u2019s largest business competitions. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessawardseurope.com/|title=The European Business Awards|website=www.businessawardseurope.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMarika became known for there work as a journalist in both television and radio. She worked series such as ''[[Jyrki (TV show)|Jyrki]], Wild bunch'' and ''Under construction Finland''. In 2003 she led the series ''Makaroff & Modig''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vintti.yle.fi/yle.fi/makaroffmodig/makaroff.html|title={{!}}YLE{{!}} TV1 :: Makaroff & Modig {{!}} yle.fi {{!}} Arkistoitu|website=vintti.yle.fi|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref>'','' a political talk show she hosted together with journalist [[Silvia Modig]]. In 2005 Marika became the CEO of [[FremantleMedia|Fremantle Media Finland]]. In 2011 she became the Creative director of the company, overseeing all creative development in the Nordics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://realscreen.com/2011/03/30/fremantlemedia-finland-names-makaroff-creative-director/|title=FremantleMedia Finland names Makaroff creative director|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref> In 2014 she moved to Stockholm to become the CEO of [[Friday TV]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fridaytv.se/news/|title=News|website=www.fridaytv.se|language=en|access-date=2017-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2014/04/ex-fremantlemedia-finland-boss-joins-friday/256722/|title=Ex-FremantleMedia Finland boss joins Friday - TBI Vision|date=2014-04-04|work=TBI Vision|access-date=2017-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015 she became the creative director of [[Filmlance]] international, that is known for creating original format of the TV-series [[The Bridge (2011 TV series)|The Bridge]].\n\nIn 2016 Makaroff launched the production company Gutsy together with co-founder Aram Aflatuni. Gutsy aims to create global and high quality content, that is above all meaningful.  \n\nMarika is currently working as the creative director and executive producer in an animated TV-series ''[[Moominvalley]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Moomin (TV Series 2019\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6921882/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_1|accessdate=2017-06-22}}</ref> The series is based on the beloved [[Moomin]] books and comics by the Finnish author and illustrator [[Tove Jansson]]. The series, directed by Oscar winner [[Steve Box]] (2006 ''Best Animation feature'' [[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit|''Wallace and Gromit: Curse of the were-rabbit'']]) \n\n\n\n''Moominvalley'' premiered in spring 2019. The series has been extremely successful in its reviews and ratings worldwide. The first episode of ''Moominvalley'' was viewed by 600,000 viewers when it premiered in Finland's Yle TV2 in February 2019. It also became the most watched television series episode of all time in Yle's streaming service, Yle Areena, bringing the total viewership of the first episode in Finland to over two million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2020/01/21/useita-ylen-tv-ohjelmia-miljoonakastiin-vuonna-2019-muumilaakson-avausjakso|title=Useita Ylen tv-ohjelmia miljoonakastiin vuonna 2019 \u2013 Muumilaakson avausjakso ker\u00e4si reilusti yli 2,1 miljoonaa katsojaa|website=yle.fi|language=fi-FI|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 Moominvalley was awarded the ''Best Animated Kid's Programme'' at TBI's Content Innovation Awards. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tbivision.com/2019/10/13/endemol-shine-kew-sky-among-content-innovation-award-winners/|title=Endemol Shine, Kew, Sky among Content Innovation Award winners|date=2019-10-13|website=TBI Vision|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\u00a0The series also won a ''Golden Venla'' award for 2019 Best Children's Program. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kultainenvenla.fi/arkisto/voittajat-2019/|title=Voittajat 2019|website=Kultainen Venla|language=fi|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> The series has been sold to over 25 territories worldwide. \n\nAlongside ''Moominvalley'', Gutsy Animations is in development with various other productions. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makaroff, Marika}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marika_Makaroff"}
{"title_page": "Swedification", "text_new": "{{more sources|date=July 2018}}\n{{Geographical imbalance|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Ortsskylt.jpg|thumb|[[Gammalsvenskby]], a Swedish village in southern Ukraine, was founded by expelled [[Estonian Swedes]] in the late 18th century.]]\n'''Swedification''' refers to the spread of the [[Swedish language]], [[Swedes|people]] and [[Culture of Sweden|culture]] or policies which introduced these changes.\n\n== Swedification of Scania ==\nAfter the [[Treaty of Roskilde]], which was one of the peace treaties that ended the [[Second Northern War]], all areas in the historical region of [[Sk\u00e5neland]] were ceded by [[Denmark-Norway]] to the [[Swedish Empire]] in early 1658. One of the most important questions for the Swedish Empire was on how to make the Scanians feel Swedish, rather Danish. On [[16 April]] 1658, representatives of [[Scania]], [[Blekinge]] and [[Halland]]'s nobility, citizens, clergy and peasants gathered for a day of fury in Malm\u00f6 Town Hall. On a given sign, the ombuds fell to the knees and promised their new king's faithfulness. The oath was appointed by a secretary. [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Charles X Gustav]] was not present but was represented by an empty chair surrounded by Swedish soldiers.\n\nIn 1662, a so-called farm day in Malm\u00f6 was held, and the Scanians accepted new taxes and regulations that differed completely from Danish law. \"Lilla tullen\" (\"the small customs\") was such an idea. All goods brought into cities would be charged with customs, just as in other Swedish cities. Each city council was to have least two Swedish-born members among the councilors. Like in the rest of Sweden, the cities were divided into [[staple right|stacks]] and settlements. Many nationals also forcibly obtained mayor seats. At the same time, inhabitants of Scania received representation in the [[Riksdag]], unlike other areas that had been conquered by the Swedish Empire.\n\nWhen Charles X Gustav landed in Helsingborg in 1658, he met Bishop [[Peder Winstrup]] from Lund on the pier, who  became a driving force for the establishment of the [[University of Lund]] as a Swedish counterweight to the [[University of Copenhagen]]. In 1666, the former was established under the name \"Regia Academia Carolina\", and its official opening ceremony took place in January 1668.\n\nThe Swedification of Scania did not begin until about two decades after the Treaty of Roskilde.<ref name=ABC>{{cite journal| last1= Larsdotter | first1=Anna | title = Sk\u00e5ningarna bytte aldrig spr\u00e5k | date = 2010 | journal = Spr\u00e5ktidningen |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[Johan Gyllenstierna]] suggested forced immigration to the Baltics, but that was never carried out.{{clarification needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cultural assimilation}}\n\n[[Category:Swedish nationalism]]\n[[Category:Cultural assimilation]]\n[[Category:Swedish language]]\n[[Category:Finland\u2013Sweden relations]]\n[[Category:Historical linguistics]]\n[[Category:History of Europe]]\n[[Category:Political history of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Swedish Livonia]]\n[[Category:Swedish Empire]]\n[[Category:Transliteration]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Sweden]]\n\n{{Sweden-hist-stub}}\n{{Socio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more sources|date=July 2018}}\n{{Geographical imbalance|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Ortsskylt.jpg|thumb|[[Gammalsvenskby]], a Swedish village in southern Ukraine, was founded by expelled [[Estonian Swedes]] in the late 18th century.]]\n'''Swedification''' refers to the spread of the [[Swedish language]], [[Swedes|people]] and [[Culture of Sweden|culture]] or policies which introduced these changes.\n\n== Swedification of Scania ==\nAfter the [[Treaty of Roskilde]], which was one of the peace treaties that ended the [[Second Northern War]], all areas in the historical region of [[Sk\u00e5neland]] were ceded by [[Denmark-Norway]] to the [[Swedish Empire]] in early 1658. One of the most important questions for the Swedish Empire was on how to make the Scanians feel Swedish, rather Danish. On [[16 April]] 1658, representatives of [[Scania]], [[Blekinge]] and [[Halland]]'s nobility, citizens, clergy and peasants gathered for a day of fury in Malm\u00f6 Town Hall. On a given sign, the ombuds fell to the knees and promised their new king's faithfulness. The oath was appointed by a secretary. [[Charles X Gustav of Sweden|Charles X Gustav]] was not present but was represented by an empty chair surrounded by Swedish soldiers.\n\nIn 1662, a so-called farm day in Malm\u00f6 was held, and the Scanians accepted new taxes and regulations that differed completely from Danish law. \"Lilla tullen\" (\"the small customs\") was such an idea. All goods brought into cities would be charged with customs, just as in other Swedish cities. Each city council was to have least two Swedish-born members among the councilors. Like in the rest of Sweden, the cities were divided into [[staple right|stacks]] and settlements. Many nationals also forcably obtained mayor seats. At the same time, inhabitants of Scania received representation in the [[Riksdag]], unlike other areas that had been conquered by the Swedish Empire.\n\nWhen Charles X Gustav landed in Helsingborg in 1658, he met Bishop [[Peder Winstrup]] from Lund on the pier, who  became a driving force for the establishment of the [[University of Lund]] as a Swedish counterweight to the [[University of Copenhagen]]. In 1666, the former was established under the name \"Regia Academia Carolina\", and its official opening ceremony took place in January 1668.\n\nThe Swedification of Scania did not begin until about two decades after the Treaty of Roskilde.<ref name=ABC>{{cite journal| last1= Larsdotter | first1=Anna | title = Sk\u00e5ningarna bytte aldrig spr\u00e5k | date = 2010 | journal = Spr\u00e5ktidningen |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[Johan Gyllenstierna]] suggested forced immigration to the Baltics, but that was never carried out.{{clarification needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cultural assimilation}}\n\n[[Category:Swedish nationalism]]\n[[Category:Cultural assimilation]]\n[[Category:Swedish language]]\n[[Category:Finland\u2013Sweden relations]]\n[[Category:Historical linguistics]]\n[[Category:History of Europe]]\n[[Category:Political history of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Swedish Livonia]]\n[[Category:Swedish Empire]]\n[[Category:Transliteration]]\n[[Category:Cultural history of Sweden]]\n\n{{Sweden-hist-stub}}\n{{Socio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swedification"}
